<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ComputerSmuggling 1stLd-Writethru a0851 12-22 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Smuggling, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0851,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Marks Breakup of High-Tech Smuggling Network, Customs Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `Customs said ... and Iraq' to CORRECT city
to
Great Lakes Beach, Mich., sted Great Lakes, Mich.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who allegedly tried to ship a $1.1 million
mainframe computer to a Soviet-bloc country has been arrested,
breaking up a large high-technology smuggling network, the U.S.
Customs Service said Thursday.
   Customs said the investigation covered six U.S. cities and eight
foreign countries, including Libya, Iran and Iraq.
   The computer, a Digital Equipment Corp. VAX 8800, has military
and civilian applications, and the man was trying to ship it to
Bulgaria, the center for computer technolgy in the Soviet bloc, said
Patrick O'Brien, special Customs agent in charge in Miami.
   The computer can upgrade and control systems that launch and
guide ballistic missiles, operate radar or run a mass-transit
system, Customs said. It is on a federal list that regulates the
export of technologically advanced products.
   The computer, which likely would have been used by the Soviet
defense system, was seized last week at Miami International Airport,
O'Brien said.
   Search warrants were being served at U.S. companies that
manufacture VAX-type computers, the system most highly sought by the
Soviets, officials said.
   ``Four or five make this kind,'' said Dexter Lehtinen, U.S.
attorney for the Southern District of Florida. ``They all will be
checked out'' for possible involvement with the smuggling network,
he said.
   Neither Lehtinen nor Customs would identify the companies.
   O'Brien said Customs arrested Eddy Gorandus Haak, a Dutch
national, on Dec. 14 after he paid $50,000 in Swiss francs to
undercover agents. They had promised to help Haak smuggle the
computer to Bulgaria.
   The arrest and seizure followed an eight-month investigation and
left the smuggling network ``in disarray,'' O'Brien said.
   Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan said more arrests are expected
in both Chicago and Boston, where search warrants were being served.
   Customs said the investigation covered activity in Boston,
Chicago, New York, Newark, N.J., Houston, Great Lakes Beach, Mich.;
and Belgium, Austria, Yugoslavia, Romania, Hungary, Libya, Iran and
Iraq.
   O'Brien said the smuggling network has purchased and diverted
numerous VAX computers systems this year. Those computer systems and
others smuggled to Soviet countries in the past several years are
worth tens of millions of dollars, Customs said.
   ``Their whole defense system is converting to the VAX,'' O'Brien
said at a news conference. ``But they cannot build their own. The
only way they can get it is through the United States.
   ``If we can deny them from taking ours, they have to build the
factories,'' he said. ``It comes out of their defense budget and
really slows them down.''
   ``By getting one of these computers, they have saved themselves
10 years and hundreds of millions of dollars in research and
development,'' Sheehan said. ``These countries are walking from the
Stone Age into the 21st century in one step at the expense of the
United States, and they're using this technology for interests
contrary to United States interests.''
   Haak, 42, is a resident of Belsele, Belgium. A grand jury
returned a three-count indictment charging him with conspiring to
illegally export computer equipment from the United States to
Bulgaria.
   If convicted of all counts, Haak could receive a maximum sentence
of 35 years in prison and a $5.75 million fine.
   Haak appeared before a federal magistrate Thursday and was denied
bond because of the likelihood he would flee from the United States,
Lehtinen said.
</TEXT>
