<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BudgetDeficit     12-22 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget Deficit,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deficit Shrinking Slightly, But Analysts Say Trend Threatened</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is getting off to a good start
toward reducing the budget deficit in 1989, but analysts say rising
interest rates and a slowing economy will make the task increasingly
difficult.
   The Treasury Department said Wednesday that a budget gap of $56.5
billion for the first two months of the fiscal year, which began
Oct. 1, was 2.4 percent lower than for the same period in the
previous year.
   The federal government ran up a $29.0 billion budget deficit in
November and $27.4 billion in October. The November red ink was 7.4
percent higher than a year earlier, but the October figure was 10.9
percent below the year-earlier total.
   The October deficit was held down by two special factors, a
decline in farm subsidy payments and a drop in military spending
caused by a shift in paycheck dates.
   The Reagan administration is projecting the budget deficit in
fiscal 1989 will shrink to $145.5 billion from $155.1 billion in the
1988 fiscal year ended Sept. 30. The Congressional Budget Office
forecasts a $148 billion shortfall.
   ``This year, we're going to have a bigger deficit because the
economy isn't going to grow as fast as it did in 1988 and interest
rates will be higher,'' said Michael K. Evans, an economic
consultant in Washington. ``We had a break (in October) but now
we're just about even.''
   Weak growth hurts deficit-cutting efforts by slowing tax
collections. Higher interest rates force the government to spend
more to finance the $2.7 trillion national debt.
   The need to spend billions of dollars to clean up government
nuclear power plants and to rescue the ailing savings and loan
industry also could add to President-elect Bush's budget problems.
   ``On the face of it, it looks like we're beginning to put in a
good performance for 1989 ... but everyone is fairly skeptical about
whether we will be able to maintain that pace. There are a lot of
expenditures in the pipeline,'' said Samuel D. Kahan, an economist
with Kleinwort Benson Government Securities Inc. in Chicago.
   Government revenue in November totaled $64.4 billion, or $7.4
billion higher than a year earlier. But spending rose an even
heftier $9.4 billion to $93.4 billion.
   As usual, the largest spending categories in November were the
military, Social Security, other programs in the Department of
Health and Human Services, interest on the national debt and farm
subsidies.
   Military spending totaled $23.9 billion last month and $49.1
billion for the fiscal year so far, up 6.9 percent from the same
period a year ago.
   Spending for Social Security totaled $18.4 billion last month and
$35.8 billion for the past two months, up 6.3 percent from the same
period in the 1988 fiscal year.
   Interest on the national debt totaled $18.1 billion last month
and $33.3 billion so far this fiscal year, an increase of 8.3
percent over the same period last year.
   The other HHS programs, including Medicare and Medicaid, spent
$13.6 billion in November and $25.3 billion so far this budget year,
a 0.6 percent decline.
   Spending by the Agriculture Department totaled $5.3 billion in
November and $11.1 billion since Oct. 1, down 13.6 percent from
fiscal 1988.
   Evans said the drought assistance to farmers likely will boost
farm spending in coming months.
   ``Even though the numbers haven't shown up in the budget, they
have to. Congress passed the drought relief bill. It's just a matter
of timing as to when the Treasury sends out the checks. That'll be
about $5 billion,'' he said.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which insures deposits in
commercial banks, spent $1.71 billion more than it collected in
revenue in November. It spent $840 million last month as part of the
$2 billion rescue of First Republic Bank of Dallas.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which backs
deposits in savings institutions, spent $1.07 billion more than it
collected so far this fiscal year, approximately double from last
year.
</TEXT>
