<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0159EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorstNukes     12-22 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Worst Nukes,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maryland Plant Is Added To List Of Worst US Nuclear Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An atomic reactor in New York and a
twin-reactor plant in southern Maryland where a worker recently
drowned have been added to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission's list
of the nation's worst nuclear power stations.
   The Calvert Cliffs plant, near Lusby, Md., about 50 miles
southeast of Washington, has recently had a number of accidents,
including one in which a worker drowned in a condensate tank that
was blanketed with nitrogen gas.
   Also added Wednesday to the NRC's ``watch list'' of problem
plants was the Nine Mile Point No. 2 reactor on the shores of Lake
Ontario near Scriba, N.Y.
   At the same time, the commission removed from its list of problem
reactors the Rancho Seco plant near Sacramento, Calif., as well as
Commonwealth Edison's Dresden units No. 2 and 3 near Morris, Ill.
   Rancho Seco, operated by the Sacramento Municipal Utility
District, narrowly avoided being shut down in a ballot question in
November. Instead, voters decided to give the plant another 18
months to prove that it can be operated efficiently.
   Altogether, the NRC's semi-annual rating had 16 reactors at nine
different locations on the watch list, meaning they warrant
particularly close attention.
   Assessing overall performance of the nation's 110 operating
nuclear power reactors, Thomas E. Murley, director of the NRC's
office of nuclear reactor regulation, told the commissioners at a
briefing Wednesday ``there are firm indications that show that
average operating performance is improving.''
   But he added that ``we have a long way to go,'' noting there were
problems with complacency about safety at some plants.
   The Calvert Cliffs plant includes two 825-megawatt pressurized
water reactors that went into commercial service in the mid-1970s.
   William Russell, administrator of the NRC's King of Prussia, Pa.,
regional office, said the Maryland plant had been put on the problem
list due to ``fairly significant operational errors and failures to
follow procedures.''
   He cited three incidents at Calvert Cliffs:
   _On June 6, during a test of emergency diesel generators, ``the
operators failed to follow procedures and put the voltage regulators
from the automatic mode to manual mode ... and failed to restore
them to automatic following the test.'' This meant the emergency
generators were inoperative for 48 hours until the problem was
discovered.
   _On July 4, while starting up one of the reactors, operators
failed to respond properly when they got two different readings for
the reactor's power because instruments were not recalibrated for a
new fuel cycle. ``This was particularly disturbing in that they had
extra people available ... and there were a number of opportunities
for people to question what was being done,'' Russell said.
   _On Sept. 15, a worker drowned in a condensate tank used to store
fresh water for use in the plant's steam system. This happened after
one worker entering the tank passed out due to nitrogen gas
blanketing the top of the tank. Another worker then entered the tank
to help the first one, fell into the water and drowned.
   In a statement, Edward A. Crooke, president of Baltimore Gas and
Electric Co., owner of Calvert Cliffs, said the utility was
dedicated to taking all necessary steps to address the NRC's
concerns.
   ``Our goal in all of this is to promptly return Calvert Cliffs to
a position of excellence in the commercial nuclear industry. We will
be satisfied with nothing less,'' Crooke said.
   Regarding Nine Mile Point No. 2, owned by Niagara Mohawk Power
Co., Russell told the commission the reactor was added to the list
because ``we concluded that they were not able to effectively
operate the station.''
   He pointed to ``a very high rate of scrams (sudden shutdowns) and
operating events'' and said the utility needed to develop a
``comprehensive plan'' to deal with deficiencies at the plant.
   The plant's unit No. 1 was already on the NRC's problem list.
   Stephen Brady, a spokesman for Niagara Mohawk, said William J.
Donlon, the utility's chairman, had sent a telegram to the NRC
saying the company has taken steps to strengthen its nuclear
management team and is ``driving hard to improve operations at Nine
Mile Point Units 1 and 2 to make those plants the standard of the
industry.''
   Other plants on the NRC's problem list are Sequoyah 1 and 2,
owned by the Tennessee Valley Authority; Browns Ferry 1, 2 and 3,
also TVA; Turkey Point 3 and 4, Florida Power & Light Co.; Fermi 2,
Detroit Edison Co.; Fort Calhoun, Omaha, Public Power District;
Pilgrim, Boston Edison Co.; and Peach Bottom 2 and 3, Philadelphia
Electric Co.
</TEXT>
