<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomosexualRights     12-22 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homosexual Rights,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Council Passes Ordinance Protecting Homosexual Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council reversed two previous votes
Wednesday and approved an ordinance protecting the rights of
homosexuals.
   ``This grants everyone in the city a right of a house, a job and
city services,'' said Mayor Eugene Sawyer. ``There's nothing
outlandish about that.''
   Sawyer, who personally lobbied for the ordinance, met with
reporters along with leaders of the homosexual and lesbian
communities after the council action.
   In addition to homosexuals, the ordinance protects the elderly
and the handicapped from discrimination in housing, employment and
other areas.
   The measure was approved 28 to 17, with some aldermen saying they
had changed their minds since the ordinance was last defeated, while
others said they hadn't changed their minds but switched their vote
to reflect their constituents' views.
   Alderman Bernard Stone said his North Side ward supports the
human rights ordinance, but he said he still believes homosexuality
``is an abomination.''
   With a special mayoral primary election coming up in February,
some aldermen were under pressure to abandon previous opposition so
the mayoral candidates they support would not lose the votes of
homosexuals.
   Sawyer himself had voted against the ordinance when he was an
alderman in 1986, but like all the major mayoral candidates now
supports the ordinance.
</TEXT>
