<DOCNO> AP881222-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0034EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HomelessActivistTrial     12-22 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Activist Trial,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Denies `Choice Of Evils' Argument</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homeless activist charged with trespassing may
not use a ``choice of evils'' argument to defend her illegal
occupation of a vacant federal house last August, a judge ruled
Wednesday.
   Denver County Judge Raymond Satter denied Dorothy King's motion
to use the defense, saying he was unconvinced it was applicable to
her case.
   Had the defense been allowed, a jury could have acquitted King of
the trespassing charge if it found she committed the crime to
prevent a greater evil _ in this case, the lack of shelter for the
homeless.
   After Satter denied the motion, jury selection began. Opening
arguments were expected to begin Thursday morning, a spokeswoman for
Satter's court said.
   King, 36, faces the misdemeanor trespassing charge for taking a
group of women and children from the shelter she operated to a
vacant house owned by the federal Department of Housing and Urban
Development on Aug. 15.
   King was arrested after refusing to leave the house. The next
day, HUD Regional Director Grady Maples made 55 vacant HUD-owned
houses available to community groups as leased housing for the
homeless.
   The action was justified because she was trying to find housing
for the destitute and call attention to the plight of the more than
2,000 homeless people in Denver, her attorneys, Diana DeGette and
Chuck Owens, argued on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
