<DOCNO> AP881222-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0222EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MafiaMurders     12-22 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mafia Murders,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Mafia Member Slain Over Lunch; 11 Mafiosos Sentenced To
Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GELA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspected Mafioso, his wife and two of
their children were slain by a gunman as they ate their lunchtime
soup, police reported.
   The family members were among eight people slain Wednesday in
four separate attacks apparently linked to organized crime gangs in
Italy.
   In the tip of the ``toe'' of Italy, a man on trial as a suspected
member of the 'ndrangheta, Calabria's version of the Sicilian Mafia,
was shot to death as he began his day as a garbage collector near
Reggio di Calabria.
   In Milan, police said a man linked to crime mob activity in the
northern metropolis was fatally shot at his fruit stand.
   Later Wednesday, two people were killed by gunmen who drove up to
their car at a red light in a town near Naples.
   Police in Sicily said the Gela attack took place in the home of
the family of Salvatore Polara, a suspected Mafia figure. Polara's
third son was wounded in the shooting.
   During the past year, there have been 40 murders in Gela linked
to mob activities such as drug-dealing and extortion.
   Citizens in the city of 80,000 recently held demonstrations
against the Mafia presence, and Italy's top anti-Mafia fighter,
magistrate Domenico Sica, visited after local officials reported the
situation was grave.
   In the town of Casalnuovo near Naples, gunmen in two autos opened
fire on a car at a red light on Wednsday, killing 28-year-old Angelo
d'Alife and 24-year-old Angelo Fico, ANSA reported. Two other men in
the car were wounded.
   The two cars used by the gunmen were later found burned.
   The attack appeared to be the work of the Neopolitan version of
the Mafia, the Camorra, ANSA said.
   Meanwhile in Turin, a court convicted 15 people of killing,
robbing and drug trafficking Wednesday in connection with an
organized crime war for control of the drug market in northern
Italy, ANSA reported.
   Eleven received life sentences and four were sentenced to less
than six years of jail.
   During the trial, a defendant had tossed a homemade bomb into the
courtroom. It caused minor damage and no injuries.
   And in Messina, Sicily, four people, including a man who
allegedly led the Sicilian Mafia, were acquitted Wednesday of the
car-bomb killing of a top judge and three other people, news
agencies reported.
   It was the sixth trial of Michele ``the Pope'' Greco, his brother
Salvatore and two other men for the July 1983 slaying.
   The car bomb killed Judge Rocco Chinnici, who had directed
investigations into the Mafia's multimillion-dollar heroin
trafficking between Sicily and the United States. Also slain were
two of Chinnici's bodyguards and a doorman.
   The judges of the Messina Court of Appeals said there was
insufficient evidence to convict the Greco brothers of planning the
attack.
   However, the court convicted all four of ``association of a Mafia
kind'' and sentenced Michele Greco to 12 years and Salvatore to 10
years in jail.
   Michele Greco is already serving a life term for ordering the
assassination of Gen. Alberto Dalla Chiesa, leader of the nation's
fight against the Mafia. He is nicknamed ``the Pope'' for the
position he allegedly held several years ago at the top of the
pyramid-like Mafia hierarchy.
   Salvatore Greco is a fugitive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
