<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Britain-Crash-US 3rdLd-Writethru a0432 12-22 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Crash-US, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0432,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crash Shocks University With 38 Students Booked On Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after 8th graf, `Neither Pan Am...' to
update with VW saying two top executive had boarding passes. Picks
up 9th graf pvs, `There were....' Lore is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SUC1, DT12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syracuse University officials expressed shock
Wednesday on learning that 38 of their students were booked on the
Pan Am jumbo jet that crashed in Scotland with 258 people aboard,
and anxious relatives gathered at Kennedy Airport.
   At the campus in Syracuse, more than 25,000 people attending a
basketball game paused for a minute of silence and a brief prayer by
the university minister. About 500 mourners sat in silence and lit
candles at a later prayer service led by chaplains of five faiths
Wednesday night.
   The Rev. Paul Kowalewski, a Protestant chaplain, said the
ceremony filled a need in the university community.
   ``We gathered because we needed to come together. The students
needed to demonstrate their sorrow, to be with one another,''
Kowalewski said.
   ``Its going to be hard to think about Christmas this year,'' said
Chris Healy, a junior from Seaford, N.Y. ``All I can think about is
their parents, some of them haven't seen their kids since August.''
   Chancellor Melvin Eggers called the crash, in which Scottish
police said no survivors were found, the ``greatest tragedy in the
university's history.''
   ``It's hard to put into words the jolt and shock this kind of
thing gives a person,'' he said at a news conference. ``I kept
asking how will we face the next few hours.''
   Neither Pan Am nor the university would release passenger names
before Thursday, saying the list still had to be compiled and
relatives notified.
   However, some names were announced by other sources.
   James Fuller, 50, vice president in charge of Volkswagen United
States Inc., and Lou Marengo, 33, the company's marketing director,
had boarding passes for Flight 103 and apparently died in the crash,
Volkswagen spokesman Tom McDonald said in Troy, Mich.
   There were 38 Syracuse students booked on Pan Am Flight 103 from
London to New York, and 36 were confirmed to have been aboard,
Eggers said.
   University officials planned a prayer service Wednesday night.
They said they would have canceled the game, but heard of the crash
too late.
   The students were part of a group of about 250, mostly juniors,
selected for study in Europe based on their academic standing and
ability to adapt to a foreign country, said Lore Heath, associate
director of the university's Division of International Programs
Abroad.
   The program includes the cost of their flight over, but students
made their own arrangements for return travel, Heath said. The
semester's program ended Saturday.
   Flight 103 was scheduled to stop in New York, where some
passengers were to change planes and depart for Detroit under the
same flight number, to arrive early Thursday.
   At the Pan Am terminal at John F. Kennedy International Airport,
people arriving to meet the plane were escorted to a private area by
security personnel.
   ``My baby, my baby,'' sobbed one woman who was supported by
security officers as she was led to an elevator.
   A young man approached an information booth, saying he had a
relative on the flight, and was immediately surrounded by
photographers. He knocked one of the cameras to the ground before
going to the waiting area.
   ``Things are bad enough _ let's let them get the people who are
meeting the airplane up there,'' said one of the security officers.
A pathway to the elevator was then cordoned off.
   A woman whose son, a 21-year-old Syracuse University student, was
on the plane, found herself surrounded by cameras. Sobbing, she
looked up and said, ``Look, my son is dead, what else do you want?''
   A Red Cross spokeswoman, Carla Abell, said the room where friends
and relatives of about 25 families were taken was like ``a hospital
waiting room.''
   ``There's a lot of fear, there's a lot of total numbness,'' she
said. ``Some people are collapsing.''
   On the television screens listing arrivals, beside Flight 103 was
the message, ``SEE AGT,'' for ``see agent.''
   At Pan Am headquarters in Manhattan, Jeffrey Kriendler, vice
president for corporate communications, said at a news conference
that it was too early to speculate on the crash's cause.
   ``We have no indication there were any problems,'' he said.
``There was no contact from the captain or any of the crew members.
There were no problems, no indication whatsoever prior to the flight
that there were any problems on board that aircraft.''
   He said the airline was sending crash experts from around the
country to the site.
   The crew included three cockpit personnel based in New York and
12 flight attendants stationed in London, he said.
   The plane had been through a routine check ``within the past
week,'' Kriendler said.
   He said Pan Am had not received any threats in recent months.
</TEXT>
