<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Sherover-Marcuse     12-22 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Sherover-Marcuse,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Racism Pioneer and Widow of Herbert Marcuse Dies at 49</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erica Sherover-Marcuse, who created
workshops to combat racism and was the widow of philosopher Herbert
Marcuse, has died at age 49 after a three-year battle with breast
cancer.
   Sherover-Marcuse, who died Dec. 15 at her home here, devoted the
last 10 years of her life to her workshops.
   She conducted them for small groups as well as large gatherings
in institutional settings, focused on helping participants to take
pride in their own heritage as a means of building alliances with
racial minorities, said David Weingarten, a friend for 12 years and
former classmate in Boston.
   Her goal was to help people understand that ``racism was a
catastrophe also for white people,'' said Weingarten. ``She always
thought that the way you change institutions was to change the
individual first.''
   In 1976, she married Marcuse, the political philosopher and
professor at the University of California, San Diego.
   Marcuse, who traveled around the world in the 1960s and has been
described as the ``guru of the left,'' died in 1979 at age 81.
   Survivors include a sister.
</TEXT>
