<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Crash, 12th Ld-Writethru, a0455, a0450, a0451,1075</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jumbo Jet Crashes Into Village; Hundreds Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7 pvs with two grafs to ADD report on plane's
maintenance history. Picks up 8th pvs, `Pan Am ...' In 1st Add,
INSERTS three grafs after 21st, `The Aloha ... rip away.'' to ADD
details of maintenance history. Should stand for AMs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY24,50,59,63,67,68; LaserGraphic NY27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pan Am jumbo jet bound for New York
with 258 Christmas travelers crashed Wednesday in a Scottish
village, exploding in a huge fireball, destroying 40 homes and
spreading burning wreckage for 10 miles.
   No survivors were found from the Boeing 747, according to John
Boyd, the police chief for the area. Royal Air Force rescuers said
the plane ``demolished two rows of houses. There are no survivors
from those houses.''
   The jetliner, Pan Am Flight 103, crashed in the heart of the
village of Lockerbie, 10 miles northeast of Dumfries in southern
Scotland, about an hour after departing London's Heathrow Airport.
   A Heathrow spokesman said three children were on the plane, and
many of the passengers were laden with Christmas gifts. There were
15 crew members among the 258 people aboard.
   ``The aircraft clearly experienced some form of explosion,'' said
Scottish Secretary Malcolm Rifkind, because wreckage was scattered
over a very wide area. But Rifkind, who arrived early Thursday with
U.S. Ambassador Charles Price, refused to speculate on the cause.
   Police, airline and Civil Aviation officials also said they had
no idea what caused the crash. The only possibility immediately
ruled out by the Civil Aviation Authority was a collision with
another aircraft.
   The Los Angeles Times reported in Thursday's editions that the
jet had a maintenance history that included an on-board fire, cracks
and corrosion. Delivered to Pan Am in 1970, it underwent a
structural modification in 1987.
   Pan Am said there was no communication with the cockpit that
indicated any problem before the crash. Civil aviation officials
said Scottish air traffic controllers had been talking routinely to
the jet until minutes before the crash, when the pilot was asked a
question and no reply was received.
   Shortly after that, the plane disappeared from the radar screen
at about 7:15 p.m. (2:15 p.m. EST) without issuing a distress
signal, said CAA spokesman Richard Wright.
   New York's Syracuse University said it confirmed that 36 of its
students studying abroad were on the plane and that two others held
tickets for the flight, but it was uncertain if they were aboard.
   There were unconfirmed reports some U.S. servicemen were aboard.
   In Thursday's editions, The Washington Post quoted a State
Department spokesman as saying six members of the department's
Diplomatic Security Service, who were returning from Beirut, were
aboard the jet. State Department spokesman Ben Justesen said he
could not confirm the report.
   The U.N. commissioner for Namibia, Bernt Carlsson, 50, of Sweden,
also was a passenger, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani. On
Thursday, representatives from South Africa, Cuba and Angola are to
sign a pact that begins an independence plan for Namibia.
   Also aboard were John Mulroy, The Associated Press director of
international communications, and his son, Sean, and
daughter-in-law, Ingrid.
   Two American Volkswagen executives were believed on the plane.
James Fuller, 50, vice president in charge of Volkswagen United
States Inc., and Lou Marengo, 33, the marketing director of the
Troy, Mich.-based automaker, had boarding passes for the flight,
said Volkswagen spokesman Tom McDonald.
   ``It is obviously still too early to put a precise figure on the
number of dead and injured but indications suggest there were no
survivors from the aircraft,'' Boyd told a news conference.
   The RAF Rescue and Coordination Center said two rows of houses _
about 40 in all _ were demolished and ``a rescue situation does not
exist any more. We are just recovering bodies.''
   Boyd said five cars traveling along the a highway near Lockerbie
were hit by parts of the aircraft and no one inside them survived.
   The plane was in pieces before it plunged into the village of
2,500, plowing down a street and crashing into a highway bypass
outside Lockerbie.
   The blue-and-white nose section, bearing the Pan Am Clipper's
name Maid of the Seas, landed in a muddy field near a church at the
village of Tundergarth, 3 miles from Lockerbie. Orange life jackets
and a dinghy lay nearby.
   Police standing by the wreckage said several bodies were found in
nearby woods.
   Witnesses to the crash described an approaching roar, then a huge
bang followed by a 300-foot tower of flame. Burning debris rained on
the town, scattering debris and chunks of smoldering metal.
   ``We thought it was an earthquake, but it was above us,'' said
villager Cathy Gilmour. ``We saw this great ball of fire, as if it
were stars.''
   Helicopters, ambulances and mountain rescue teams rushed to the
village in southwest Scotland. Traffic jams blocked access, and the
village square was sealed off for fear that a gas station hit in the
crash could blow up.
   Lockerbrie resident Sheila McDonald was delivering Christmas
presents to a friend's home on a hillside overlooking the town when
she heard ``a horrible droning sound.''
   ``This V-shaped object just seemed to come flying through the air
... it was the wings and front section of an aircraft ... another
part came just behind and all around seemed to be red dots like
sparks,'' she said.
   ``It hit some houses in the town and there was a mass of flame
and everything just started to shake.''
   Police said wreckage was strewn over 10 miles.
   ``Wreckage has fallen at six different locations both within
Lockerbie and some miles outside the town. There are bodies at each
of these locations,'' Boyd, told a news conference.
   Villager John Glasgow said: ``The whole road was ablaze. Two
houses were blazing. The road was completely covered with masonry,
garden gates and apparently parts of the plane, but not very big
parts. There was a lot of smoking debris on fire. It looked as if
the road was burning.''
   ``There was a terrible explosion and the whole sky lit up and the
sky was actually raining fire,'' said Mike Carnahan, a resident who
was a few hundred yards from the scene.
</TEXT>
