<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Crash 12thLd-Writethru 1stAdd 12-22 0928</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Crash, 12th Ld-Writethru, 1st Add, a0451,0952</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LOCKERBIE: the scene.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``It was just like liquid. We have actually found an aluminum
rivet embedded in the metal of my car,'' Carnahan told the British
Broadcasting Corp. television.
   Carnahan said he believed the plane was on fire before it crashed
because ``it was trailing flames when it went over the village.''
   Flight 103 had taken off 25 minutes late and was at 31,000 feet
when contact was lost, the Heathrow Airport Authority said.
   The aircraft was following its exact flight plan, said Jeffrey
Kriendler, a spokesman for Pan American World Airways in New York.
   ``Nothing would suggest that weather was a factor, especially
since we believe it happened at altitude,'' he said.
   A collision with another aircraft also was ruled out.
   ``We have rerun radar records and these indicate there were
apparently no other aircraft in the vicinity,'' said Wright, the
civil aviation spokesman.
   The jet took off from Heathrow at 1:25 p.m. EST and disappeared
off radar screens an hour later, said Pat Coffey, spokesman for the
RAF Rescue Coordination Center near Edinburgh, Scotland.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, using a Boeing
727, with passengers who continued on to New York boarding a Boeing
747 in London. That plane normally connects with another 727 flying
from New York to Detroit.
   Conrad Jacoby, the Pan Am chief for central Europe, told the ZDF
television network that 48 people had boarded the flight in
Frankfurt. It was not known how many of them got on the Boeing 747.
   Air Force Maj. Mike Stepp, a spokesman for the Defense
Department, said he had no information on whether any U.S. military
personnel were aboard.
   The airline did not release a passenger list.
   At the Pan Am terminal at Kennedy International Airport in New
York, a TV monitor told people waiting for Flight 103 to ``see
agent.'' At the Clipper Club, a lounge for waiting passengers, a Pan
Am employee turned down the sound on a TV set when a report of the
crash was broadcast.
   Another witness, hotelier Graham Byerley, said the fireball from
the plane towered 200 to 300 feet into the air.
   Carnahan said: ``All I could see was flames and fire ... I could
see several houses on the skyline whose roofs were totally off and
all you could see was flaming timbers and what was left of the
houses.''
   Les Callaghan, spokesman for Dumfries and Galloway Royal
Infirmary, said the hospital treated about 12 people believed to be
local residents hurt when the plane crashed in the village of 2,500.
   A Pan Am 727 left London early Thursday for Scotland carrying
airline representatives, British Department of Transport officials
and a Boeing technical representative to assist in work at the crash
site, said airline spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon in New York.
   Other Pan Am officials were en route from New York, she said.
   In addition, National Transportation Safety Board officials from
Washington were dispatched to the scene to help with the
investigation.
   The crashed jet was delivered to Pan Am in February 1970, said
David Jimenez, spokesman for Boeing Commercial Airplanes in Everett,
Wash. It had about 16,500 cycles, with one cycle being a takeoff and
a landing, Jimenez said. That is not considered a particularly high
number for a commercial jetliner, he said.
   The Aloha Airlines 737 that lost part of its fuselage in flight
in April had more than 89,000 cycles, a factor that was investigated
in determining whether metal fatigue caused part of the fuselage to
rip away.
   Service records filed with the Federal Aviation Administration
show that since 1980, the 747 that crashed Wednesday experienced at
least 24 mechanical difficulties severe enough to warrant notation,
the Los Angeles Times reported.
   In 1980, five reports were filed, including one that cited a
crack and one that cited failure of the plane to turn when it was on
autopilot. Another difficulty involved a flame-out of an engine
during cruise flight, the newspaper said.
   Reports in 1981 and 1983 cited numerous cracks in the plane's
floor beams and a floor beam web; a 1984 report detailed fractures
in exhaust casing rails and trailing edge flaps that were locked in
place, the Times said.
   Pan Am said the jetliner was part of the Civil Reserve Air Fleet,
a program to provide planes to the U.S. government in the event of
national emergency. It was converted by Boeing in Wichita, Kan., in
1987 to make it cargo-capable in 48 hours for the national emergency
program, the airline said.
   The Air Force pays for the modification, but it was unable to
convince most airlines to participate, said Boeing spokesman Paul
Fang, so the conversion, involving adding a cargo door and
strengthening the floor, was not a common procedure.
   A Japan Air Lines 747 crashed Aug. 12, 1985, killing 520 people.
It was the worst single-plane aircraft accident in history. Boeing
later admitted its faulty repairs were one of the causes of the
crash, which was attributed to a crack in the rear cabin wall that
caused a sudden loss of pressure. The force of the air tore the
plane's tail apart.
   The FAA in 1986 ordered a modification of all Boeing 747s as a
result of that crash.
   Two Boeing 747 jets collided on a runway in the Canary Islands in
1977, killing more than 500 people.
   Pan Am suffered a major crash involving one of its airplanes in
July 1982, when a Boeing 727 crashed after taking off from New
Orleans International Airport in a thunderstorm, killing 154 people.
