<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoldierEspionage     12-22 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier Espionage,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier And Turkish National Arrested For Espionage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army intelligence analyst who boasted of
spying for greed and a Turkish-born Floridian were arrested for
selling ``highly sensitive'' documents to East Bloc agents over six
years, authorities said.
   Warrant Officer James William Hall III, 30, who is stationed at
nearby Fort Stewart and served in West Germany, was arrested here
Wednesday and taken to the base detention facility, said Lt. Col.
John Chapala, an Army spokesman in Washington.
   Huseyin Yildirim was arrested at his home in Belleair Beach,
Fla., near St. Petersburg, and was scheduled to appear before a U.S.
magistrate in Tampa, Fla., for a bond hearing this afternoon.
   Yildirim, a 60-year-old Turkish native, was charged with
conspiracy to commit espionage by giving agents of a foreign
government national defense secrets, said Ed Dutko, an agent in the
FBI's Savannah office. If convicted, Yildirim could be sentenced to
life in prison.
   Hall has not yet been formally charged, Chapala said.
   ``Hall, as a member of the military, can be charged with a
similar offense by the military and court-martialed,'' Dutko said.
``Yildirim is a civilian, so he faces civilian charges.''
   Chapala said he could provide nothing ``on the classification or
nature of the information allegedly provided by Hall or to whom it
went.''
   But published reports today said the espionage inflicted serious
damage on electronic spying efforts in Europe, although the damage
was still being assessed.
   Hall's home in Richmond Hill and Yildirim's home were searched
Wednesday by FBI and Army intelligence officers, the FBI said.
   The arrests followed a meeting at a Savannah hotel Tuesday night
between Hall and an FBI agent posing as a Soviet intelligence
officer, according to an affidavit FBI agent Charles B. Youmans Jr.
filed Wednesday with U.S. Magistrate G.R. Smith here.
   Hall told the unidentified agent ``that he had been passing
highly sensitive signal intelligence documents to both the Soviets
and the East German intelligence services since late 1982,'' the
affidavit said.
   ``Hall boasted of the important signal intelligence information
he had passed, and admitted his motivation to be greed,'' the
document said. It did not give details on the information.
   Hall said Yildirim participated in the copying of the documents
and acted as the Army man's courier and paymaster until last
January, the affidavit said. The affidavit said Hall was paid in
U.S. and German currency, but did not say how much he made.
   Hall also told the undercover agent that Yildirim contacted him
after his transfer to Fort Stewart and met with him in Savannah, the
document said.
   Hall has spent most of his Army career as a signals
intelligence-electronics warfare analyst, working on intercepted
radio traffic, telephone conversations and coded messages, Chapala
said.
   The New York City native joined the Army in 1976. The first of
three European assignments came the following year, when he was
assigned to an Army security agency company in Schneeberg, West
Germany, Chapala said.
   In 1981, Hall went to West Berlin, where he again worked in a
signals intelligence assignment.
   Hall returned to the United States in 1985 and was assigned to a
military intelligence group at Fort Monmouth, N.J. In 1986, he
returned to West Germany, serving in a military intelligence
battalion in Frankfurt.
   He was sent back to the United States in May 1987, and was
assigned to Fort Stewart last July.
   Chapala said there was no indication of any connection between
Hall's arrest and another military spy case last summer involving
NATO secrets.
   A former U.S. Army sergeant, Clyde Lee Conrad, was arrested in
that case in West Germany last August, and two Hungarian-born
brothers were sentenced to 18 months in prison in October in Sweden
for relaying NATO information to Hungary. Investigators said Conrad
reported to a Hungarian spymaster living in Vienna, Austria.
</TEXT>
