<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Unions     12-22 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Unions,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gonzalez Seeks Conciliation With Unions After General Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez has agreed to
some demands for higher wages and pensions made by labor unions
whose general strike brought the country to a standstill last week.
   In a speech to Parliament on Wednesday, the 46-year-old Socialist
_ a former labor lawyer _ pledged to increase wages of civil
servants and raise the lowest pensions to the legal mininum wage,
the equivalent of $394 a month. He also said he would withdraw a
controversial youth employment program.
   But Gonzalez rejected union demands that the government broaden
availability of unemployment insurance from 30 percent to 48 percent
of the 2.7 million jobless and recognize civil servants' right to
enter collective bargaining.
   He also ruled out calling early elections, which now must be held
by June 1990.
   In a Dec. 14 general strike, 7.8 million of the country's 11.8
workers stayed off the job to call for a bigger share in the
country's booming economy.
   The strike called by the Socialist General Workers Union and the
Communist Workers Commissions brought nearly all industrial,
commercial and labor activity to a halt.
   Gonzalez offered to meet today with union leaders and the head of
the country's key business organization after acknowledging before
the 350-seat lower house that the strike represented political
failure for his government.
   Antonio Gutierrez, head of the Workers Commissions, said
Wednesday he did not plan to join the meeting with the Spanish
Employers Organization president Jose Maria Cuevas. But he said he
would meet with Gonzalez and other union leaders later.
   Both unions said their leaders would not attend today's meeting
if Gonzalez insisted business' top leader be present. Gonzalez said
if the labor leaders failed to show up he would meet with them
Friday or Saturday.
   The prime minister has urged unions to negotiate their
differences with the government to maintain the economy's current 5
percent annual growth rate.
</TEXT>
