<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-MissedFlight     12-22 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Missed Flight,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serviceman Got On Ill-fated Plane After Missing Earlier Flight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOPPATOWNE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army lieutenant who missed the plane he
intended to take on his way home for Christmas boarded the Pam Am
jumbo jet that crashed in Scotland, reportedly killing the 258
people aboard, his father said.
   First Lt. George W. Williams, 24, who was stationed near
Frankfurt, West Germany, missed his flight because of a traffic jam,
said the father, George Williams of Joppatowne.
   ``I just talked to him this morning,'' Williams said Wednesday
night. ``Because he missed his flight from Frankfurt ... he had to
make new connections. He told me there was a big backup on the
Autobahn,'' Germany's high-speed highway.
   Williams said his son was coming home for the first time in 16
months.
   The elder Williams and his wife, Judy, waited by the phone in
their suburban Baltimore home until Pan Am officials called them
about 11 p.m. to tell them their son was aboard Flight 103.
   The Boeing 747 plunged to earth in the village of Lockerbie in
southern Scotland. No survivors were found.
   The flight to New York was carrying passengers from Frankfurt and
London.
   The younger Williams had won a full ROTC scholarship after
graduating from Joppatowne High School, and attended Tulane
University. He graduated from Western Maryland College in 1986.
   He was stationed at Bad Kreuznach, where he was a helicopter
forward observer. He was about midway through a three-year tour in
West Germany, his father said.
   ``He enjoyed being in the Army. He enjoyed his time in Germany.
He was doing well,'' and was up for the captain's list next month,
Williams said.
</TEXT>
