<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Crash-Lockerbie     12-22 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Lockerbie,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Where Plane Crashed Famous For Fossils</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockerbie, the Scottish town ravaged by the crash
of Pan Am Flight 103, is celebrated among fossil hunters for
footprints of dinosaurs.
   The small community in southwest Scotland, 15 miles north of the
English border, is nestled in the middle of the narrow valley of the
Annan River.
   The quarry near Lockerbie that supplies the town's construction
materials is locally famous for the dinosaur footprints.
   Lockerbie was a center for lamb and horse sales in the late 17th
century and lamb sales have been held every year on Lamb Hill since
1680. The town manufactures cheese, cream and woollen goods, and
hosts livestock fairs.
   Its prosperity grew in the 19th century when the railway arrived
from Carlisle in northern England and moved northward to Scotland's
industrial center of Glasgow. The town had railway workshops until
World War I.
   Several of the landowners were connected with the Jardine
Matheson Co., which made a fortune in the China tea trade and
remains one of the major trading companies in Hong Kong.
   Lockerbie, in the regional district of Dumfries and Galloway, was
the scene of savage fighting for generations between the Maxwell and
Johnstone families.
   The Maxwells held the lower end of the Annandale valley and the
Johnstones the center. In 1593, the Johnstones decisively defeated
the Maxwells at Dryfe Sands, killing 700 of them, including their
chief.
</TEXT>
