<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Carlsson     12-22 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Carlsson,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Commissioner for Namibia Was On Pan Am Jetliner That Crashed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brent Carlsson of Sweden, the U.N. official
who was to guide the African territory of Namibia to independence,
was one of the passengers on the Pan Am jetliner that crashed in
Scotland, officials said.
   All 258 people on board the plane perished in Wednesday's crash.
   Carlsson, 50, was the U.N. commissioner for Namibia, also known
as South-West Africa. He was to have been a witness today for the
signing of an accord granting independence to the territory.
   The United Nations considered Carlsson the chief official of
Namibia, and he planned to guide the transition to an independent
government following signing of the accords allowing for transition
to an independent government.
   The foreign ministers of South Africa, Cuba and Angola are to
sign an accord guaranteeing South Africa will end its 73-year rule
over Namibia, and that 50,000 Cuban troops will withdraw from Angola.
   South African Foreign Minister R.F. Botha told The Associated
Press he arrived in New York on the Pan Am flight just before Flight
103.
   Carlsson had been commissioner for Namibia since July 1987. The
United Nations in 1966 revoked a League of Nations mandate giving
South Africa the right to govern Namibia, and asserted its own
authority over the territory.
   South Africa defied the U.N. declaration until this month, when
it signed a preliminary accord under which South Africa will
withdraw from Namibia and Cuba will pull its troops out of the
neighboring Marxist state of Angola.
   The Swedish diplomat faced death more than once. During a trip to
Nicaragua in 1980 he escaped when he canceled a flight following a
tip. A bomb exploded later in the plane, killing four of its
passengers.
   ``People and organizations fighting for freedom and democracy and
against suppression and dictatorships must realize death might be
waiting around the corner,'' he told the Stockholm evening
Aftonbladet in a 1983 interview following the slaying of PLO
official Issam Sartawi in Portugal.
   He earlier acted as a special emissary to the Middle East and
Africa from 1983-85 for Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme. From
1976-83, he was general secretary of the Socialist International.
   The diplomat was personal secretary and adviser to the trade
minister from 1967-70, served as an undersecretary of state in
Sweden's Ministry for Foreign Affairs, and was international
secretary of the Swedish Social Democratic Party from 1970-76.
   He traveled and met extensively with leaders in southern Africa
in the course of his duties.
   The United Nations in 1966 revoked a League of Nations mandate
giving South Africa the right to govern Namibia, and asserted its
own authority over the territory.

</TEXT>
