<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Soviets     12-22 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Soviets,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Says Moscow Does Not Back Philippine Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze said today that Moscow does not support local Marxist
rebels and will not seek to ``drive a wedge'' between Manila and the
United States.
   Shevardnadze, the highest-ranking Soviet official ever to visit
this former U.S. colony, also invited President Corazon Aquino to
the Soviet Union before departing for North Korea after a 24-hour
stay.
   Mrs. Aquino said a date for her trip would be set after Foreign
Secretary Raul Manglapus visits Moscow next year.
   During a luncheon meeting with Mrs. Aquino, Shevardnadze said he
had come to the Philippines ``to dispel the myth'' of a Soviet
military buildup in Asia and to stress the need for negotiations
``to sort out our differences.''
   ``We have to take a first step toward building new relationships
in the Asia-Pacific region,'' he said.
   Shevardnadze, who arrived Wednesday from Japan, urged a
conference of Asian foreign ministers to reduce tensions in the
region.
   ``We have absolutely no intention of trying to drive a wedge
between the Philippines and its traditional allies,'' Shevardnadze
added in a reference to the United States.
   During his talks, Shevardnadze avoided detailed discussions on
U.S. military bases in the Philippines. In October, Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev offered to withdraw Kremlin forces from Vietnam
if the Americans close their six bases in this country.
   Shevardnadze told reporters at a departure news conference that
Moscow's view of the U.S. bases ``is negative but, of course, what
happens to the bases is entirely for the government and people of
the Philippines to decide.''
   In October, the United States and the Philippines signed an
agreement allowing Washington to use Subic Bay Naval Base, Clark Air
Base and four smaller installations until 1991 in return for $962
million in economic and military aid over two years.
   Mrs. Aquino's spokesman, Teodoro Benigno, said Shevardnadze told
the president the Soviets would never interfere in internal
Philippine affairs.
   ``The Soviet Union has never supported, nor has any intention of
supporting (the rebels),'' Benigno quoted Shevardnadze as saying.
Later, the Soviet official told reporters: ``I would like to state
in all responsibility, that the Soviet Union is not giving and will
never give support to any insurgent group.''
   The Maoist Communist Party of the Philippines has been waging a
nearly 20-year-old insurgency to establish a Marxist state.
   Filipino and Western sources say there is no evidence of Soviet
support to the rebels but that Filipino Communists have been making
overtures to Moscow and other Communist countries.
   Filipino officials praised the Shevardnadze visit and said it
marked a first step in overcoming what Manglapus called ``biases ...
acquired in the early years of the Cold War.''
   The Philippines, which gained independence from the United States
in 1946, has been among the slowest non-communist Southeast Asian
nations to pursue closer ties with the Soviet Union.
   A joint statement said the two sides agreed to expand trade from
$40.4 million last year to $200 million a year in the future.
</TEXT>
