<1ST_LINE>b i PM-Crash-Warning     12-22 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Warning,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Airport Officials Stepped Up Pan Am Security After Tip of Possible
Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frankfurt airport officials
stepped up security at Pan Am after receiving tips earlier this
month that a bomb might be smuggled aboard one of the carrier's
jets, the airport's security chief said today.
   The official, Horst Harnstein, said the tips were ``for the
transportation of a bomb from Frankfurt heading in the direction of
the United States.''
   ``There were indications in that direction,'' Harnstein said in a
telephone interview. ``As a result, we stepped up security measures
for Pan Am.''
   ``There were solid indications that it was to be Pan Am,''
Harnstein added. AP. He said authorities first received the tip in
early December, but did not specify the source. Harnstein provided
no further information.
   Pan Am Flight 103, which crashed in pieces into a Scottish
village on Wednesday, originated in Frankfurt aboard a Boeing 727.
The New York-bound Boeing 747 that crashed took off from London.
</TEXT>
