<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Crash-IATA     12-22 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-IATA,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>International Body Says Sabotage Most Likely Explanation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Air Transport Association
believes sabotage is the most likely explanation for the crash of a
Pan Am jumbo jet in Scotland, an association spokesman said today.
   ``We were struck by the similarity of this accident and the Air
India 747 that came down in June 1985'' off the Irish coast after a
bomb exploded that had been put aboard by a terrorist, said David
Kyd, chief public relations officer for the organization.
   ``Sabotage is the most likely explanation,'' he said. ``But of
course, we have to find the black boxes that may or may not give us
additional clues and the fuselage of the aircraft has to be examined
for indications whether there was an explosion on the inside, for
instance, in the cargo hold.''
   He said the sudden loss of contact with the plane and because the
jumbo is known to be very rugged ``it would seem to us that the most
likely hypothesis is an explosion aboard.''
   Kyd said structural problems were unlikely to have been involved
in Wednesday's crash. He noted that previous accidents, such as in
the case of the ill-fated Japanese JAL airliner in 1985, have
demonstrated that 747's can stay aloft for a while even with serious
damage to the structure.
   ``A bulkhead blew out (in the Japanese crash) and they lost the
tail and a rudder but the aircraft was able to continue flying for
over 20 minutes just on the strength of the engines and the pilot's
skill to find some way of getting it down. Ultimately they crashed
into the mountains because they were unable to make it to an
emergency base.''
   Authorities said all 258 people aboard Flight 103 from London to
New York were killed as the 747 plunged in pieces into a Scottish
village. The death toll on the ground was not yet known.
</TEXT>
