<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-22 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow In The West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snowstorms moved from the Pacific coast across the mountains of
the West today as the rest of the nation enjoyed relatively tranquil
weather.
   A cold front crossing the Rockies today brought 5 to 20 inches of
snow to California's Sierra Nevada. A second storm was expected to
produce heavy snow today and a third may bring more heavy snow this
weekend.
   Winter storm warnings were in effect for California's Mount
Shasta, Siskiyou Mountains and northern Sierra Nevada, where 12 to
18 inches of snow were possible, and for higher elevations of
southwestern Oregon.
   A winter storm watch was issued for the southern Sierra Nevada
and for higher elevations of the Lake Tahoe area of Nevada.
   Snow advisories were in effect for California's northwest
mountains, south-central Oregon and parts of Idaho.
   A high surf advisory was posted for the northern coast of
California, where large ocean swells and high tides were expected to
cause dangerous surf conditions the next several days. A gale
warning was in effect for Oregon's coast.
   Snow also fell in sections of Utah, Wyoming and Colorado.
   In Utah, the heavy snow caused hundreds of accidents, but no
serious injuries were reported. Salt Lake City police logged 117
accident reports in 10 hours Wednesday.
   Clouds were over much of the nation east of the Rockies, with fog
in the Southeast. Showers and thunderstorms fell over extreme
southern Florida and rain showers developing along a cold front
moved off the mid-Atlantic Coast.
   Gale warnings were in effect for lakes Erie and Huron tonight.
   Today's forecast called for snow from the eastern Dakotas and
eastern Nebraska to much of the upper Mississippi Valley, northern
Wisconsin and Upper Michigan; rain showers from southeast Minnesota
and southern Wisconsin to the Mississippi and western lower Ohio
valleys; showers and thunderstorms in the lower Mississippi Valley;
and widespread rain along the Pacific Coast.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 30s or 40s across much of
the nation; 20s in parts of eastern Idaho, western Montana, western
Wyoming, North Dakota, northern Minnesota, Upper Michigan, and
central New England; 50s and 60s from the central California coast
to the southern Plains, Tennessee Valley and the southern Atlantic
Coast states; 70s in the Gulf Coast; and 80s in the southern half of
Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees at Limestone, Maine, and Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 71
degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 foggy; Boston 38 fair; Buffalo 29 snow;
Charleston, S.C. 57 fair; Cincinnati 32 foggy; Detroit 30 partly
cloudy; Miami 69 partly cloudy; New York 37 fair; Philadelphia 36
fair; Pittsburgh 31 cloudy; Portland, Maine 32 fair; Washington 39
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 33 cloudy; Chicago 33 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
64 cloudy; Denver 37 fair; Des Moines 30 partly cloudy; Indianapolis
30 fair; Kansas City 41 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 29 cloudy;
Nashville 48 foggy; New Orleans 62 foggy; St. Louis 34 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 37 fair; Anchorage 14 cloudy; Las Vegas 40
fair; Los Angeles 53 fair; Phoenix 46 fair; Salt Lake City 28
cloudy; San Diego 51 fair; San Francisco 49 cloudy; Seattle 37
cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 12 fair; Toronto 21 fair.
</TEXT>
