<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MinistersTrial     12-22 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ministers Trial,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toledo, Civil Rights Leaders Settle Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement to dismiss charges against 13
civil rights leaders who tried to halt a City Council meeting is a
step toward resolving a struggle with Toledo over its treatment of
minorities, some black leaders say.
   But if the city does not negotiate in good faith, other civil
rights leaders are warning of more civil disobedience.
   ``The city of Toledo and its government must learn to consult
with us prior to action or there will be continual problems with the
black community,'' said J.B. Simmons, a lawyer for the defendants.
   Mayor Donna Owens called the settlement ``a strong statement that
government will not tolerate people taking over government.''
   The settlement came Wednesday as jury selection for five of the
13 was to resume in Municipal Court.
   The city reduced the charges against the 13 from obstructing
official business charge to failure to disperse. Resisting arrest
charges against two defendants also were dismissed.
   The defendants, who included 12 ministers, pleaded no contest.
Visiting Judge John Patterson dismissed the case and ordered their
records expunged.
   Prosecutor John Madigan said he was not pressured by city
officials to reach a compromise.
   ``Sometimes it takes a court trial to figure out this isn't the
way to go,'' he said.
   The 13 were arrested for trying to stop a June 28 City Council
meeting. They were protesting the firing of a black community
development official, the re-assignment of another black, the
retirement of a third and the resignation of a fourth because of
alleged mismanagement of the housing program.
   Defendant LeRoy Williams, president of the Toledo chapter of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said the
agreement was not a retreat.
   ``It is a step forward and another phase in resolving the larger
picture,'' said Williams.
   But another defendant, the Rev. Floyd Rose, a leader of a group
of black ministers known as the Interdenominational Ministerial
Alliance, had doubts about the settlement.
   ``I'm not sure the community will understand now why we did what
we did,'' he said.
   Simmons said city officials agreed to meet with the ministers by
mid-January to try and resolve differences. He said the defendants
agreed to the settlement because it was in the best interest of the
community.
   The mayor said she has been meeting privately with civil rights
leaders to discuss issues facing blacks.
   Ms. Owens, who said she had no part in the plea agreement,
insisted that the city would not be threatened by future acts of
civil disobedience.
   ``I look at it (the agreement) as a strong statement that
government will not tolerate people taking over government, that
there are laws and those laws are to be respected by everybody,''
Ms. Owens said.
   The dispute began over the city's handling of problems in its
Community Development Department. The department's management
shuffle followed an investigation by the U.S. Department of Housing
and Urban Development that said the city's housing rehabilitation
program was deficient.
   The civil rights leaders wanted to know why the men were
reprimanded without being consulted about the problems. They also
asked for a hearing into the allegations.
   City officials rejected their requests.
</TEXT>
