<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0704EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SantaWheelchair     12-22 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Santa Wheelchair,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mom And Son Find Good Will Overwhelming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter to Santa Claus from a 10-year-old boy
who wanted an electric wheelchair for his mother has elicited
Christmas greetings and gifts from around the world _ including one
brand-new wheelchair.
   ``The Christmas spirit is incredible,'' said Denise Reusche, a
clerk at the U.S. Postal Service in Palm Springs, in a telephone
interview Wednesday.
   The Postal Service in the desert resort 110 miles east of here
annually processes about 1,000 letters to Santa each year. Normally,
workers send a letter in return.
   But when Ms. Reusche saw John F. Wonggoun's letter from nearby
Banning this year, she decided to do something more for the boy, who
along with his mother was partially disabled in a 1981 traffic
accident.
   His letter read: ``The only gift I would like is an elecric
wheelchair for my mom. She can't walk and her hands are too weak for
the one welfair (sic) gave her 2 years ago. I would love to see her
outside without help and watch me play. Can you help me with my
wish?''
   Ms. Reusche and her fellow workers contacted Fortress Scientific
Co. of Palm Springs, a wheelchair manufacturer, and it donated a
three-wheeled, motorized wheelchair for John's mother, Victoria
Coslett, 39.
   Then the workers bought a bunch of gifts for John, food for
Christmas dinner and established a wheelchair maintenance fund. They
delivered the gifts on Monday.
   Stories about John's letter were distributed worldwide by The
Associated Press.
   Ms. Reusche said in addition to the newspaper stories, the postal
workers were featured on several television and radio interviews.
   ``We had a call from New Zealand for a radio interview. A
Sunnyvale man is sending a letter of encouragement, a train set and
a gift for the mom because he had the same background. A lady in
Connecticut said a group of women was getting together to do
something for John after Christmas was over,'' she said.
   The traffic accident left Ms. Coslett with ruptured spinal discs.
John was partially brain damaged and suffers recurring seizures and
memory lapses. He also has juvenile arthritis.
   Ms. Coslett, in a telephone interview, said she was shocked by
the reaction to her son's letter.
   ``I couldn't speak. All I could do was sit there and cry. He's
done so many things, for me and for the kids out here (in the
apartment complex). If he earns money here and there, he'll go out
and buy a toy for one of the kids. He's never selfish,'' she said.
   ``Nothing has changed. He's floating on a cloud. He's happy the
wheelchair is coming and I can be out there and watch him play,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
