<HEAD>Dollar Steady in Lethargic Trading, Gold Mostly Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was holding steady in thin, lethargic
trading in Europe late this morning, with dealers in lightly staffed
trading rooms expecting little significant change in the currency
through the session.
   Gold prices were mostly higher.
   ``The market is absolutely dead this morning,'' said one foreign
exchange trader a major U.S. bank in Milan.
   She added that there also were very few commercial orders,
further reducing activity.
   ``There's not even any hard news to trade on,'' the trader said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.40 yen to a closing 124.62 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 124.73 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.7732 West German marks, up from 1.7720
   _1.4963 Swiss francs, down from 1.4980
   _6.0550 French francs, up from 6.0500
   _2.0025 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9920
   _1,305.75 Italian lire, up from 1,302.00
   _1.1995 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2012
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8040, compared with
$1.8065 Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $414.30 a troy ounce,
down from $415.75 bid late Wednesday. But at midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price
of $415.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $415.40, up from $414.60 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.51 to close at a bid $417.45.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.12 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.14.
