<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bank-Kidnapping     12-22 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank-Kidnapping,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robbers Hold Bank Official's Family Hostage, Escape With $250,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three robbers held a bank executive
and his family hostage overnight, then stole nearly $250,000 from
the bank's vaults before fleeing, authorities said.
   Police were not notified for 90 minutes until the robbers had
fled and BankAtlantic Chief Executive Officer Alan Levan found his
wife and 7-year-old daughter locked in the trunk of their
Mercedes-Benz, police spokesman Ott Cefkin said Wednesday.
   ``It seems to be very well planned, and obviously it worked very
well,'' Cefkin said. ``They were probably halfway to Mexico by
then.''
   Three men posing as a flower delivery team gained access to
Levan's Coral Gables home Tuesday evening while Levan, 40, and his
wife, Susan, 38, were out.
   The intruders held the live-in maid, Petrona Sandoval, 68, and
the Levans' daughter, Lauren, at gunpoint until the couple arrived
home shortly after midnight.
   ``They opened the door and the people were there at gunpoint,''
Bank executive Mark Wright said.
   The family was held overnight in an upstairs bedroom, then driven
30 miles north to Fort Lauderdale during morning rush-hour. Sandoval
was left behind handcuffed inside a bedroom and Levan's wife and
daughter were locked in the car's trunk during the trip.
   When Levan arrived at the bank he and Wright packed the money
into a suitcase, said Barry Deutsch, the bank's executive vice
president.
   ``This was not in the context of your normal robbery,'' he said.
``They walked in calmly. Noboby else knew what was going on.''
   Levan said the robbers, who left in his car, told him not to call
police until they called with the location of the Mercedes.
   ``I don't mean to trivialize money, but money is money,'' Deutsch
said. ``It's not the same as people. We're family here. We're just
glad everyone is safe.''
</TEXT>
