<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Lottery     12-22 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Lottery,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Richest Lottery Showers Millions On Spaniards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's richest lottery showered
Christmas cheer and billions of tax-free pesetas on jubilant
Spaniards as the annual Yuletide tradition paid out prize money
equivalent to $734 million.
   A crowd in a Madrid auditorium roared as two boys from an
orphanage sang out the number of the first prize popularly called
``El Gordo,'' (``the fat one''), a total of $159 million to 72
ticket-holders throughout Spain.
   Two hours and 45 minutes after the drawing began, the ball
bearing the winning number rolled out of the chute as millions of
Spaniards gathered in front of televisions and radios for the live
morning broadcast of the Christmas lottery begun in 1818.
   The ceremony is more popular than Santa Claus in Spain.
   Today's prizes were the richest since King Carlos III established
Spain's first lottery in 1763.
   To cope with demand this year, the state-run lottery issued 72
tickets for each of the 66,000 lottery numbers.
   Thirty percent of the lottery proceeds go straight into state
coffers. The prize money is tax-free.
   The second prize of $1 million went to each of the 72 holders of
a number bought largely by youths belonging to a soccer club in
Alcala de Henares, the birthplace of Miguel de Cervantes just east
of the Spanish capital.
   Officers and soldiers in the military government building in the
southeastern city of Valencia broke out champagne upon the
announcement of the third prize number, which paid out $526,315 to
its 72 winners. Members of an army infantry division based in
Valencia purchased most of that number.
</TEXT>
