<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JudgeDisciplined     12-22 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge Disciplined,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Says Michigan Judge Should Be Removed for Indecent
Comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY DAUBENMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court has been asked to
remove a judge from office for making sexual advances to female
defendants.
   The state Judicial Tenure Commission said in a decision released
Wednesday that Kalamazoo District Judge Arvin Davis was guilty of
misconduct in office and should be barred for life from the
judiciary because he was morally unfit and had damaged the image of
the courts. The final decision rests with the state Supreme Court.
   ``Public perception of our judicial system is directly affected
by such conduct which prejudices more than just (Davis') ability to
administer justice,'' the decision said.
   The 8-0 decision said Davis had shown he lacked moral character
needed by a judge.
   Davis, 50, declined to comment, saying, ``Any comment should come
from my attorney.'' His attorney, William Fette, did not return
phone calls made to his office Wednesday.
   The recommendation from the commission, which polices judicial
conduct, was the stiffest penalty it could suggest to the state
Supreme Court.
   The commission's order said testimony taken during a hearing on
the complaint against Davis indicated the judge had met privately
with three female defendants, asking them questions about their
sexual activity and the color of their undergarments. One said he
squeezed and fondled her.
   A court employee also testified Davis made suggestive comments to
her at a 1986 Christmas party.
   The commission rejected Davis' defense that the comment to the
court employee was intended as a joke and that he had met privately
with defendants in efforts to help them.
   Supreme Court spokesman Tom Farrell said the commission must file
its report with the court within 21 days. Davis then has 28 days to
ask for a modification or seek oral arguments before the court.
   Davis, who has been a judge since 1982, has not been on the bench
since May pending the outcome of the case but has continued to
receive his $88,000-a-year salary.
</TEXT>
