<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RanchSeized     12-22 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ranch Seized,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Seize Ranch Near President's Home After Marijuana Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAVIOTA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 105-acre ranch worth nearly $500,000 and
located near President Reagan's own ranch was seized by federal
agents after a marijuana crop was found there.
   The property, located at the exclusive Hollister Ranch
development in this Santa Barbara County community, was the 34th
seized by the Drug Enforcement Administration this year in Southern
California, said DEA spokesman Ralph Lochridge.
   Federal agents discovered 65 well-cultivated marijuana plants at
the ranch, located about 15 miles from the ranch owned by the
president, authorities said.
   ``This is part of an aggressive approach by federal and local
authorities to use the federal forfeiture law to confiscate and
forfeit the assets of drug traffickers,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert
C. Bonner.
   The ranch, seized by DEA agents, working with federal marshals
and county sheriff's deputies Wednesday, was valued at $475,000,
said Mary McMenimen, spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney's office.
   The plants, valued at $227,500, were discovered Sept. 15 when
authorities flying over the area spotted a bright patch of green,
Ms. McMenimen said.
   They were about 200 yards from the house and were irrigated from
the residence, she said.
   The property is owned by Thomas Winfield III, Sandra J. Winfield,
Dianne L. Vanderhave and Peter J. Vanderhave, Ms. McMenimen said.
   The Vanderhaves were arrested in the raid Sept. 15 and charged
with felony marijuana cultivation, said sheriff's Lt. William Lenvik.
   No information was available about the Winfields. Ms. McMenimen
said she was unaware if charges had been filed against them.
</TEXT>
