<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UConnBomb     12-22 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UConn Bomb,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Discovered in Building at University of Connecticut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STORRS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb planted at the University of
Connecticut's social sciences building was disarmed today after a
janitor discovered it in a floor ashtray, a university spokeswoman
said.
   The janitor, who was not identified, became suspicious on
noticing a device with wires sticking out of it in the ashtray. He
took it outside and summoned campus police, said spokeswoman Karen
Grava Williams.
   They in turn called the state police bomb squad, which took the
bomb to a dump about a mile away and disarmed it, Williams said. It
did not explode and no one was hurt, she said.
   ``It is an explosive device; it will not detonate now,'' she
said. ``They are planning on examining it as best they can to use it
as evidence.''
   Monteith Hall, where the device was found, and another nearby
building, the Arjona humanities building, were to be closed the rest
of the day while police used bomb-sniffing dogs to make sure there
are no other bombs in either building, Williams said.
   No one claimed responsibility for planting the device and
university officials have no reason to believe other bombs will be
found, she said.
   ``We want to take every precautionary measure to be sure there
are not and that includes keeping students out of the building,''
she said.
   Classes ended for the semester last week but a number of students
are still on campus for final exams, which run through Friday,
Williams said. A number of exams were scheduled for Monteith Hall
today, she said.
</TEXT>
