<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Crash-FBI     12-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-FBI,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said today it has
offered the services of the FBI's forensics and disaster units to
the British in connection with the crash of a Pan Am jumbo jet over
Scotland.
   The offer of assistance was being made through L. Paul Bremer,
head of the State Department's counter-terrorism office, said
Justice Department spokesman Loye Miller.
   FBI officials were meeting at headquarters in Washington to
discuss the situation and have been monitoring it, said William
Carter, a bureau spokesman.
   ``The FBI is following this matter to ascertain the facts,'' the
bureau said in a statement. ``FBI legal attaches in London are in
contact with British authorities concerning the crash of Pan
American Flight 103 in Scotland.''
   A Justice Department employee, Michael Bernstein, was among those
aboard the craft, said department spokesman Miller. Bernstein was an
attorney working in the Office of Special Investigations, the
department's Nazi-hunting unit.
   Bernstein, 36, had been in Austria negotiating a treaty that
would allow some former Nazis in the United States to be returned to
that country, said department sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Bernstein was married and had two children.
   Because Bernstein had been aboard the craft, flags at Justice
Department buildings were being flown at half-staff.

</TEXT>
