<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-Michigan 1stLd-Writethru a0504 12-22 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Michigan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Crash Support Group Turns Out to Console Pan Am Families</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to reflect official increase of toll to 259,
sted 258, delete `apparently.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A support group of relatives and friends of
people killed in the nation's second-deadliest air crash helped
console victims of a fresh grief: families of those aboard Pan Am
Flight 103.
   ``We came to offer support ... to be here when people were being
informed that their loved ones were confirmed, because we can truly
identify with these people and we know exactly what they're going
through,'' said Lisa Recker, whose brother was among the 156 people
killed in the crash of Northwest Flight 255 on Aug. 16, 1987.
   The Pan Am flight began in London and was en route to New York
when it crashed in Scotland on Wednesday, killing all 259 people
aboard.
   Some passengers were to change planes in New York and continue to
Detroit as Pan Am Flight 226, which arrived at Detroit Metropolitan
Airport at 12:15 a.m. today.
   And the news that as many as 10 Detroit-area passengers were
aboard the ill-fated London flight drew out the Northwest support
group.
   ``We live that day every day,'' Recker said. ``But we vowed as a
group that we would go on in outreach in case these nightmares every
happened again. When this happened to us, we wished somebody would
be there, somebody who could tell us the truth.''
   Recker and Betty Polec, whose daughter and son-in-law died in the
Northwest crash, said they consoled four families at the airport
Wednesday night.
   Pan Am released no names of victims by early today, but it was
learned that two Detroit-area auto executives and relatives of at
least four other Michigan families were aboard.
   James Fuller, 50, vice president in charge of Volkswagen United
States Inc., and Lou Marengo, 33, marketing director for the
Troy-based automaker, had boarding passes for the flight, Volkswagen
spokesman Tom McDonald said.
   ``We're extremely saddened and this is at the present as close to
confirmation as we have,'' Volkswagen spokesman Jay Amastoy.
   Airline employees at the airport whisked away relatives and
friends of victims to a private area as they arrived to await the
connecting flights.
   Eugene and Lelia Coleman of Southfield said their daughter,
LaWanna Thomas, was supposed to be on Pan Am Flight 55 that arrived
at Detroit Metropolitan Airport from London in the afternoon. She
wasn't on the plane.
   The Colemans then were taken by Pan Am employees to a private
room to check passenger lists. Airline officials apparently did not
confirm whether the daughter was on the flight.
   Thomas' sister, Terri Coleman, left the room grief-stricken.
   Thomas, a 21-year-old Air Force sergeant, had been stationed in
West Germany since April, said the woman's grandmother, Edith
Marshall. She was traveling with her 2-month-old son, Jonathan, a
baby that relatives had never seen, Marshall said.
</TEXT>
