<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sullivan-Views 1stLd-Writethru a0443 12-22 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sullivan-Views, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sullivan Well Qualified For HHS Post, Associates Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 2-3 with announcement expected, 2:30 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, expected to be the first
black to join President-elect Bush's Cabinet, moves easily in
Democratic as well as Republican circles, according to friends and
associates of the school administrator.
   Sullivan, 55, president of the Morehouse School of Medicine in
Atlanta, was expected to be formally announced today as Bush's
secretary of health and human services.
   He had drawn criticism from anti-abortion activists this week
after he said in an interview that women should have a right to
choose abortion. He later said he opposes abortion but would allow
it in cases of rape, incest or when the mother's life was endangered.
   Friends describe him as a political independent whose
associations with lawmakers range from rural Georgia figures to
Bush, who attended a dedication ceremony at the medical school in
1982 and invited Sullivan on a trip to Africa later that year.
   Dr. Jim Kaufmann, a friend of Sullivan's since the 1970s, said
Sullivan has been ``very close'' to Bush and his wife, Barbara, a
member of the medical school's board of trustees since 1983.
   ``He has strong Republican leanings,'' Kaufmann said. ``That
doesn't mean he's not a strong Democratic supporter. That's how it
is when you represent a school and you're trying to develop
education. He works well with everybody.''
   Sullivan had never made public statements on his views about
abortion until Bush began considering him to lead the Department of
Health and Human Services. His remarks on the subject in an Atlanta
newspaper interview Sunday _ in which he said he supports a woman's
right to seek an abortion but opposes federal funding to pay for it
_ brought an outcry from anti-abortion forces.
   Monday, Sullivan wrote a letter to The Atlanta Journal and The
Atlanta Constitution saying he is ``opposed to abortion except in
cases of rape, incest and where the life of the mother is
threatened.''
   Dr. Clint Warner, chairman of the Morehouse medical school's
board of trustees, said Sullivan's views on abortion are aligned
with those of Bush.
   ``His views are consistent with the president and, more
importantly, consistent with the law,'' Warner said. ``Dr. Sullivan
is the most qualified person in the country for that position. I
think the president holds that view, too.''
   Kaufmann said Sullivan is not a political neophyte, but has
generally steered clear of political controversies.
   He said Sullivan ``got so attached to Bush'' about four years ago
because he felt Bush would be ``a pro-education president.''
   Lee Raudonis, executive director of the Republican Party of
Georgia, said Sullivan has never actively worked with the state
party or aligned himself with it.
   ``Dr. Sullivan has been very close to the president-elect. He has
participated in some functions, but he has not been listed as an
active member,'' Raudonis said. ``He's tried to remain independent.
I don't recall that he's attended any Republican Party
fund-raisers.''
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., said Sullivan, a native Atlantan, is
widely respected in the city's mostly Democratic black community and
regularly visits Lewis' Washington office to update him on the
medical school's progress.
   ``When he's in Washington, he keeps us briefed on what is
happening _ he uses our office sort of as his office _ because
Morehouse is in the heart of the district,'' Lewis said.
   Sullivan set up many influential political contacts during his
efforts to establish the Morehouse medical program in the 1970s.
Lewis said Sullivan, on behalf of the medical school, ``made
contacts early'' with ``some of the movers and shakers in Georgia
politics,'' including Sens. Sam Nunn and Wyche Fowler as well as Tom
Murphy, speaker of the Georgia House and a powerful Democrat.
   ``If anyone can come to grips with Health and Human Services in
this time of limited resources, I think Dr. Sullivan could,'' Lewis
said. ``One thing I can say about him: he's a hard worker. He's
persistent and he's very aggressive.''
   Professionally, Sullivan is a blood specialist who has been
president of the Morehouse School of Medicine since 1981. He has
taught medicine at Harvard, Morehouse, the New Jersey College of
Medicine and Boston University, where he graduated with honors in
1958.
</TEXT>
