<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LanierSentenced     12-22 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lanier Sentenced,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Indy 500 Star Gets Life On Drug Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BENTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge sentenced former car-racing star
Randy Lanier to life in prison without the possibility of parole for
helping run a multimillion-dollar marijuana-smuggling operation.
   Before the sentencing Wednesday, Lanier, the 1986 Indianapolis
500 Rookie of the Year, tearfully told U.S. District Judge James
Foreman that the punishment would be ``cruel and unusual.''
   An attorney for Lanier said he would appeal the sentence.
   ``It is unfair and unjust to impose a sentence of life without
parole for a marijuana offense, regardless of the amount,'' said the
attorney, Robert Ritchie.
   In sentencing Lanier, Foreman said that of the 300 to 400 cocaine
cases he had presided over, invariably the defendants started out
using marijuana.
   ``You have caused a lot of heartache, and individually you've
ruined a lot of lives in this country,'' Foreman told Lanier, who
stood before the court wiping away tears. ``Look at what it's done
to you.''
   A federal jury convicted Lanier, 34, of Davie, Fla., and two
co-defendants on Oct. 4 of charges of engaging in a continuing
criminal enterprise, which carries a mandatory sentence of life, and
conspiring to distribute more than 1,000 pounds of marijuana between
1982 and 1986.
   A fourth defendant was found guilty of the distribution charges
in the 15-week trial.
   Lanier also received the maximum 40-year sentence on the
distribution charge plus five years on a third charge of conspiring
to defraud the Internal Revenue Service. He also was ordered to
forfeit $60 million in drug proceeds.
   Prosecutors contended the drug ring smuggled more than 600,000
pounds of Colombian marijuana into the United States by barge.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mike Carr urged a stiff sentence.
   ``You have before you, judge, one of the richest men in the
United States because of his dealings in drugs,'' Carr said. ``It is
now time for the court to send a message that this will not be
tolerated.''
   Convicted with Lanier on the criminal enterprise and distribution
charges were Ben Kramer, 34, of Miami, and Eugene Fischer, 48, of
Coral Gables, Fla.
   Foreman sentenced both men Dec. 5 to life in prison without
parole on the criminal enterprise charge. On the second count,
Kramer received the maximum 40 years and Fischer got 35 years.
   On Dec. 12, Foreman sentenced the fourth defendant, Kay Dee Bell
Jr., 43, of Redwood City, Calif., to 25 years in prison for
conspiring to distribute more than 1,000 pounds of marijuana.
   Lanier and Kramer, a former power-boat racer, each cleared $68
million from the operation, prosecutors said, while Fischer got more
than $31 million. The three men were forced to forfeit a total of
about $150 million.
</TEXT>
