<HEAD>Late Shah's Family Lives in U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of the late Shah of Iran, including
son Reza Phlavi II, heir to the Peacock Throne, live in the United
States nearly 10 years after the end of the shah's rule in Iran.
   An anonymous caller to The Associated Press in London who claimed
responsibility for the crash of Pan Am Flight 103 said it was in
retaliation for the United States' harboring of the shah and his
family when they were driven from Iran, as well as the downing of an
Iran Air flight by a U.S. ship in July.
   The shah was denied permanent sanctuary in the United States and,
suffering from cancer, shuttled with his family from country to
country, with stops in Morocco, Mexico, Panama and the Bahamas,
before being granted asylum in Egypt, where he died.
   The family moved to the United States in 1984. His son Reza
Phlavi, whom exiled supporters now call the Shah, lives at an estate
in Virginia, just outside Washington, with his wife, Yasmine.
   The late shah's wife, Farah, and their other children, Farahnaz,
Ali Reza, and Leila, also live in the United States.
</TEXT>
