<HEAD>`What's a Press Conference?' Asks Youth Commission's Youngest
Member</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newest member of the city's Youth
Commission certainly understands what it's like to be young. He's
only 7 himself.
   Edward Andrews _ Teddy to his friends _ was sworn in Tuesday to
the commission by Berkeley City Council member Don Jelinek, who said
the boy was a key worker in his successful bid for re-election.
   Showing a flair for ethnic politics, Teddy greeted reporters in
two Chinese dialects before the swearing-in ceremony. But he still
has a way to go in the political world; when asked by reporters how
he liked the press conference, he replied: ``What's a press
conference?''
   Jelinek's confidence remained unshaken.
   ``I decided it would make a great appointment,'' he said.
``Here's a rare opportunity to have the wisdom of someone who is
physically 7 years old but has a mental and intellectual age of
someone 10 years older.''
   The commission meets monthly and advises the City Council on
youth issues. Andrews is the youngest of about 400 commissioners who
serve Berkeley on 43 boards and commissions.
   The job really is a reward for the boy's work on Jelinek's
campaign, the councilman said.
   ``I worked with his mother and other tenants of the Carlton Hotel
on improving conditions there,'' Jelinek said. ``When the campaign
came around, his mother volunteer PM-ShahFamily 1stLd a0588 12-22 0067

