<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Crash-Plane 2ndLd-Writethru a0547 12-22 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Plane, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0547,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede LOS ANGELES</HEAD>
<HEAD>747 That Crashed Reportedly Had History That Included Cracks and
Corrosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with FAA records from Oklahoma City; change
in official toll to 259, sted 258; editing to tighten, include
possibility of sabotage.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CASEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing 747 that crashed in Scotland had
been repaired for at least 21 mechanical difficulties since 1980,
including a small inboard fire and a large crack in an upper
bulkhead, according to federal records.
   Federal Aviation Administration service records show that in
November 1987, a 16.3-inch crack near the upper part of the fuselage
bulkhead was discovered in the plane that crashed Wednesday in
Scotland with 259 people aboard. Investigators today focused on
terrorist threats to place a bomb on the jet, and officials said
sabotage seemed the most likely cause of the crash.
   The FAA report said the crack in the plane was corrosion-related,
and corrosion was noted in the plane's floor beam and other areas.
   According to records filed March 25, a leading edge slat fell off
the plane during takeoff from Karachi, Pakistan, and the slat
section was found on the runway.
   In October 1987, maintenance workers responding to a Boeing
service bulletin suggesting inspections of the plane and all similar
aircraft found severe corrosion at the rear bulkhead and on part of
the fuselage, the report said.
   A Boeing spokesman said the plane was taken out of service last
year for substantial modifications, and any structural deficiencies
observed earlier would have been corrected.
   Other service difficulties cited included a sheared nose gear
bolt, a missing pylon panel, two instances of smoke in the passenger
cabin and fire spewing from an engine pylon.
   Boeing Commercial Airplanes, which builds the 747 in Everett,
Wash., has no comment on the reports, company spokesman Craig Martin
said Wednesday night. And Pan Am spokesman Jeff Kriendler said he
could not comment because he did not have the plane's service
history.
   In Washington, FAA spokeswoman JoAnn Sloane said there have been
problems with minor cracks in 747s, and the FAA put out a directive
to have the planes inspected.
   But she said the inspections did not find much cracking. ``Those
are certainly very reliable airplanes,'' she said.
   Officials at Pratt & Whitney in East Hartford, Conn., said they
doubted their engines, which powered the aircraft, were responsible
for the crash. Company investigators were dispatched to the accident
scene.
   The 747-100, tail number N739PA, was delivered to Pan American
World Airways in February 1970 and was the 15th 747 built, said
David Jimenez, another Boeing spokesman.
   The plane had flown an estimated 72,000 hours and about 16,500
cycles, with one cycle being a takeoff and landing, said Boeing's
Jack Gamble. Jimenez said 50,000 cycles is considered high for a
commerical jetliner.
   A Pan Am 747 was one of two jets involved in the worst disaster
in commercial aviation history: the March 27, 1977, collision
between two 747s at Tenerife in the Canary Islands, in which 582
people died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Crash-Finland     12-22 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Finland,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Find No Connection Between Finland Threat and Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry said today it had
found no direct connection between a telephoned bomb threat to the
embassy and the crash of a Pan Am jetliner in Scotland.
   In a statement, the ministry confirmed the Israeli and U.S.
embassies had received several threats during the year by an Arab
resident, most recently on Dec. 5.
   The statement indicated the authorities knew the caller's
identity, and said ``the suspected phone caller has not left Finland
since he made his last threatening telephone call'' 17 days ago.
   ``In the investigation so far, no direct connection has been
found between the Arab living in Finland and the air accident in
question,'' said the statement, read to The Associated Press by a
spokesman.
   It did not elaborate on how police could be certain the threat
was not linked to Wednesday's crash, in which 259 passengers and
crew were killed. Twenty-two people also were killed on the ground
in Lockerbie, Scotland, where the plane crashed.
   A U.S. Embassy spokeswoman referred all questions to the State
Department.
   In Washington, Undersecretary of State Ronald Spiers said the
Federal Aviation Administration issued an alert after a bomb threat
was received by the Helsinki embassy on Dec. 5.
   A U.S. government source said in Washington that the threat was
made by a person claiming to belong to the Abu Nidal organization, a
radical Palestinian faction which broke away from the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   The caller said a bomb would be placed aboard a Pan Am plane and
would be carried by a woman, said the source, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
