<DOCNO> AP881222-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentPrincipal     12-22 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Principal,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Principal Learns Plenty As Student For A Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH PLATTE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like many high school students, Ivan
Kershner showed up in jeans, passed notes in class and skipped study
hall with a forged pass.
   The next day, though, Kershner buckled down to work again _ as
principal of North Platte High School.
   Kershner traded places with a student Wednesday as part of the
school newspaper's fund-raising effort, Principal For A Day. For 50
cents a chance, students bought tickets for the raffle, which was
won by senior Charles Swanson.
   Swanson showed up Wednesday in suit and tie and spent the day on
such matters as inspecting the grounds for needed repairs and
reviewing lunch policies with administrators.
   Kershner, meanwhile, struggled through Swanson's classes. He
began the day with physics but was forced to leave class early when
he was called to the principal's office and reprimanded for parking
his car in the faculty lot.
   ``Which was good because I wasn't understanding what was
happening in physics,'' Kershner said.
   Then it was on to American history, algebra, Spanish, American
government, English and orchestra. The last was a problem because
Swanson plays first-chair viola while Kershner said he plays
``25th-chair harmonica.''
   Kershner said if he were to trade places with Swanson
permanently, he would have to drop physics and orchestra and enroll
in remedial algebra.
   ``Anybody who thinks school is for kids _ implying it is easy, it
is not a job or it is not the real world _ is sadly mistaken,''
Kershner said. ``I worked hard today. I learned things I have never
known before and I was challenged.''
   ``There's an awful lot of hard work in being a student in today's
schools,'' he added. ``Kids simply are expected to know more now
than any other point in history and there is more to know now than
any point in history.''
   Swanson, too, found the principal's job harder than expected.
During the day, he discussed student tardiness and ideas for an open
campus with associate principals, observed classes, served as hall
monitor and was host at a faculty Christmas party.
   ``I'd imagine in some ways it's harder to be a student, but
altogether, I think it's harder being a principal.'' Swanson said.
``There are a lot more people to take care of and a whole lot of
responsibility. It's a tough job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
