<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-Mulroy 3rdLd-Writethru a0582 12-22 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Mulroy, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0582,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Executive, Son, Daughter-in-Law Were Aboard Crashed Jet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS graf giving address where condolences may be sent.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Mulroy, director of international
communications for The Associated Press, died along with five family
members in the crash of a New York-bound Pan Am jetliner.
   Local authorities said no survivors were found from among the 259
people aboard Flight 103 after the plane crashed Wednesday in the
village of Lockerbie in southern Scotland. More than 20 others died
on the ground, officials said today.
   Mulroy was traveling with five family members, including his
25-year-old son, Sean, and Sean's wife, Ingrid, who were residents
of Sweden.
   Mulroy's sister, Bridget Concannon, her husband, Thomas, and the
couple's son, Sean, who lived in a London suburb, also were aboard.
   Mulroy, 59, joined the AP in August 1984 after 25 years with Pan
Am, where he had been director of communications. He was a native of
County Mayo, Ireland, and maintained a second home in the land of
his birth.
   Mulroy joined the news cooperative as staff executive for
international communications. He was appointed deputy director of
communications in 1986 and director of international communications
in 1988, based in New York. In that position, he was responsible for
all AP technical operations outside the United States.
   He was born April 1, 1929, and held an associate degree in
electrical engineering from Birmingham University in England.
   ``John Mulroy had been with us only four years but his
contributions were immense,'' said Louis D. Boccardi, AP president
and general manager.
   ``He guided the streamlining of our international news and
picture communications systems during a time of accelerated
modernization. He did that with a wit and warmth that made him a
treasured member of our team.
   ``To say that we will miss him does not begin to describe our
sense of loss.''
   Survivors include Mulroy's wife, Josephine, of East Northport, on
New York's Long Island, a daughter, Siobhan, 26, and a son, Brendan,
23.
   The Associated Press said condolences may be sent to the family
home at 35 Cherrywood Drive, East Northport, N.Y., 11731.
</TEXT>
