<DOCNO> AP881222-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-Syracuse 3rdLd-Writethru a0590 12-22 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Syracuse, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0590,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syracuse Students Gather to Grieve, Saying `It Can't Be True'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th grav pvs, ``It's hard ... ,'' to
UPDATE with Gov. Cuomo ordering flags flow half-staff.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SUC1, SUC6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds clustered around Syracuse
University's chapel to share the horrible news that 38 students were
aboard a doomed Pan Am flight, listen to prayers and utter a common
refrain, ``It can't be true.''
   ``It still hasn't really hit,'' said Chris Healy, a junior from
Seaford, N.Y. He said one of his friends was among the students in a
Syracuse University program who were booked on the jetliner that
crashed Wednesday in Scotland.
   Authorities believed there were no survivors among the 259 people
aboard Flight 103, which was en route from London to New York.
   ``It's hard to think of Christmas this year. I think about the
parents, who hadn't seen their kids since August,'' Healy said as he
was joined by a group of anguished friends at Hendricks Memorial
Chapel.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo issued a statement today expressing his
sorrow and ordering flags at all state facilities be flown at
half-staff through Saturday.
   ``For all the lives lost and particularly to the Syracuse
University community, we extend our most profound and heartfelt
sympathies and our prayers for strength,'' Cuomo said.
   Elsewhere on campus Wednesday night, more than 25,000 people
attending a basketball game paused for a minute of silence and a
brief prayer by the university minister.
   Inside the chapel, about 500 mourners sat in silence and lit
candles at a prayer service led by chaplains of five faiths. The
Rev. Paul Kowalewski, a Protestant chaplain, said the ceremony
filled a need in the university community.
   ``We gathered because we needed to come together. The students
needed to demonstrate their sorrow, to be with one another,''
Kowalewski said. ``It's Christmas, they're students and young _
everything in a tragedy is built into this.''
   The 38 students were part of a group of about 250, mostly
juniors, selected for study in Europe based on their academic
standing and ability to adapt to a foreign country, said Lore Heath,
associate director of the university's Division of International
Programs Abroad.
   The program includes the cost of their flight over, but students
made their own arrangements for return travel, Heath said. The
semester's program ended Saturday.
   University Chancellor Melvin Eggers called the crash ``one of the
greatest tragedies in Syracuse University history.''
   ``This is the saddest day of my life,'' he said. ``We've lost
some of the brightest, talented, most beautiful people. It's hard to
express our sorrow.''
   Eggers said the fact that the crash may have been the result of a
terrorist act made it even harder for families and friends of the
victims.
   ``The first impact of such an event plummets us into almost
depair,'' Eggers said this morning on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show. ``But
to learn that it might have been a deliberate act is just beyond
belief, something we can't cope with.''
   Farshad Hajir of South Orange, N.J., a senior who learned that a
close friend had been returning on the Pan Am plane, said in a
cracking voice:
   ``I told her what a great experience it would be to study abroad.
I encouraged her. Then you come back to hear this. What can I say?''
   Nearby, people clustered in small huddles to seek consolation.
Pain and disbelief were evident in most faces. Friends hugged one
another and cried together.
   ``It can't be true,'' was a common refrain amid the sobs that
split the chill night.
   ``This is the mood that's all around,'' said junior Scott Meach,
pointing to emotional people around the chapel's front steps.
   ``It's really so hard to believe,'' said Meach, a resident of
West Bloomfield, Mich., who said one of his fraternity brothers was
on the jetliner. ``It helps to bring people together to share the
pain.''
   George H. Couch, a junior in geography, also came to pray for a
fraternity brother. ``The thing about this,'' Couch said, ``is that
at our age you feel so indestructible. You see it happening on
television, but don't think it will ever happen to us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
