<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Crash-Reagan     12-22 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Reagan,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Spokesman Defends State Department Warning of Airline
Threat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash-Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan today offered his condolences
to the victims of the Pan Am jet crash as his spokesman defended the
process by which the State Department warned U.S. embassies that a
bomb threat had been made against Pan Am jetliners flying from
Frankfurt to the United States.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said he could not explain
why more people had not been notified of the threat, and he
acknowleged that ``the public should be aware'' of such threats.
   ``I think that certainly will be looked at,'' Fitzwater told
reporters. ``Public notification has to be considered.''
   The spokesman said the State Department warned U.S. embassies
around Dec. 7 about a bomb threat had been made two days earlier
against Pan Am jetliners flying from Frankfurt, West Germany, to the
United States 2{ weeks before the crash of a New York-bound flight
originating in Germany.
   At his daily press briefing, Fitzwater said no information had
been discovered ``that can confirm sabotage as the cause'' of the
crash.
   The president, he said, planned to call Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher about the matter later in the day. Reagan has also
dispatched a team of U.S. officials from the Federal Aviation
Administration, the National Transportation Safety Board and the FBI
to help in the investigation, the spokesman added.
   Fitzwater said the FAA told Pan American World Airways that it
might be the target of a terrorist bombing, and that ``appropriate
police'' in various parts of the world were also told of the Dec. 5
threat.
   Asked why more people weren't warned, Fitzwater said, ``I don't
have an answer on that. There are threats like that on a continuing
basis. ... The issue is there are so many of these (threats) that
this was determined to be the appropriate level of notification.''
   But pressed as to whether the general public should have a chance
to make its own judgments about travel in regard to such threats,
the spokesman said he believed the matter would receive some
consideration.
   ``The public should be aware of the general threat,'' he said.
``Whether (there is) a press release is a thing that should be
considered.''
   ``President Reagan is deeply saddened by this tragic accident.
The president and Mrs. Reagan wish to convey their condolences to
the families of all the victims. The president has promised the full
cooperation and support of the U.S. government in this
investigation,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
