<2ND_LINE>PM-Fatal Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0557,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Killed, Three Injured in Early Morning House Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes, details, CORRECTS number of
injured to three sted four; No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire apparently started by a kerosene heater
quickly spread through a one-story home early today, killing six
children and injuring three adults, fire officials said.
   Fourteen people, mostly children, were in the home when the fire
started shortly before 6 a.m., and some escaped by jumping from
windows, said fire Capt. John Welch.
   ``The flames was coming out of those windows just like an
inferno,'' said Myrtle Bell, a neighbor. ``The kids inside were
screaming. They just couldn't get no help.''
   A man and two women were taken to Barnes Hospital where a
spokesman said the man was in critical condition and the women were
in serious condition.
   The names and ages of the victims were withheld, but Welch said
the adults injured were a man, his wife and daughter in her 20s. The
11 children, ranging in age from 1 to 19, were children of either
the couple or their daughter.
   Firefighters arriving at the scene found the four survivors in
front of the brick house on the city's near north side. Survivors
told firefighters there were children inside, but they were unable
to rescue any of the victims, Battalion Chief Frank Schaper said.
   The fire, which apparently was started by a kerosene heater in
the basement, caused extensive damage to the house and its contents,
Schaper said.
   ``The father woke up and saw one of the sons adjusting or doing
something with the heater, and then there was a flash,'' Welch said,
adding that investigators were trying to determine whether the
heater was defective.
</TEXT>
