<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0569,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed In Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with reason boy was being transported
to hospital, FAA statement, pilot's condition, victims' ages and
hometowns; CORRECTS name of company that owned helicopter. No
pickup.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAPE GIRARDEAU, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A medical helicopter taking a
7-year-old boy to the hospital crashed in heavy fog early today,
killing the boy and two medical workers and seriously injuring the
pilot, authorities said.
   The helicopter was en route from Marion, Ill., to St. Francis
Medical Center in this southeast Missouri town when it went down in
a field about 4:30 a.m., said Mary Spell, a spokeswoman for the
hospital.
   Spell said the boy was being taken to the hospital for treatment
of a broken neck and back he sustained in a traffic accident.
   Bob Raynesford, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said the final communication indicated that the
pilot, Sheldon Rudzek, had decided not to land because of the fog.
   ``The last thing on the radio was the pilot saying he was
breaking off his approach because of the fog,'' Raynesford said.
``It was pretty difficult flying.''
   Deputy Don Hanscom of the Cape Girardeau County sheriff's office
said a farmer found the wreckage, which Spell said was scattered
over a large area.
   Spell identified the dead as Karen Scherer, 26, the flight nurse,
of Cape Girardeau; Julie Hutteger, 22, a St. Francis respiratory
therapist; and the patient, James Rhodes of Marion, Ill.
   Rudzek, of Cape Girardeau, was listed in critical condition with
second- and third-degree burns over half his body and two broken
legs, Spell said.
   She said the helicopter, operated by Air Evac EMS of West Plains,
Mo., was dispatched about 3 a.m. to pick up the boy.
</TEXT>
