<DOCNO> AP881222-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1325EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Panama     12-22 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Panama,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Continue Efforts to Oust Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush pledged Thursday to pursue
President Reagan's policy of seeking the removal of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega from power in Panama.
   ``Our policy will be that Noriega must go. There should be no
misunderstanding about our policy,'' Bush told Eric Arturo Delvalle,
the ousted president whom the United States continues to recognize
as Panama's legitimate leader.
   The vice president's words were relayed to reporters by White
House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater after Bush met privately with
Reagan, Delvalle and national security adviser Colin L. Powell.
   Fitzwater said Delvalle requested the meeting because of ``rumors
and unfounded stories in Panama of a change in U.S. policy.''
   ``He was looking for assurance of steadfastness,'' the spokesman
said.
   Delvalle has lived in hiding in Panama since being deposed last
February by forces loyal to Noriega, who was indicted on
drug-smuggling charges by two federal grand juries in Florida
earlier this year.
   Fitzwater said Delvalle did not suggest any changes in policy and
there was no discussion of relaxing the economic sanctions that the
United States has applied against the Noriega-run government.
   Fitzwater said there was no discussion of the possibility of
Delvalle resigning and no discussion of possible U.S. military
action. As to the latter possibility, he would say only, ``We don't
discuss military options.''
   On Wednesday, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
appeared to rule out U.S. military force to depose Noriega, saying
that ``Panama's political crisis can be resolved only by
Panamanians.''
   Fitzwater said Reagan commended Delvalle's courage and patriotism
and promised his continued support. He said Delvalle thanked the
president and vice president for their backing.
   The spokesman described the meeting, which lasted about 15
minutes, as ``a general discussion of where we go from here.''
   Delvalle met Wednesday afternoon with Secretary of State George
P. Shultz shortly after his arrival from Panama aboard a U.S.
military jet. Neither man spoke to reporters after the meeting.
   The Washington Post reported in Thursday's editions that, during
a meeting in Panama City last week with Adm. William J. Crowe Jr.,
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Delvalle threatened to give
up his struggle against Noriega unless the United States came up
with a specific plan to remove him.
   The Post said that according to notes of the secret meeting
provided by a source, Delvalle said he saw no reason to continue
making personal ``sacrifices'' without a specific plan of action to
remove Noriega.
   The newspaper said the Dec. 11 meeting also was attended by U.S.
Ambassador to Panama Arthur Davis and the commander of the U.S.
military's Southern Command, Gen. Fred F. Woerner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Judge'sName     12-22 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge's Name,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Returns to Original Name to Stress Hispanic Heritage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What's in a name? To Judge Shannon Weatherall, who
has decided to start using her given name of Carmen Otero, a lot of
ethnic pride.
   Weatherall, 55, who has served about a decade on the bench, is
the state's only judge of Latin American heritage at the Superior
Court level.
   She is of Spanish and Mexican descent, was raised in New Mexico
and spoke only Spanish until the fourth grade, she said.
   ``One of our family served as the last territorial governor of
the state of New Mexico, and the Otero name long has been woven into
the culture of that part of the community,'' she said.
   Besides discarding the name of a former husband, she is
abandoning the first name she adopted as a student at the University
of Colorado Law School.
   ``I really got tired of answering questions about where was the
rose between my teeth and being asked to dance on the table,'' she
said. ``As an attorney, I wanted to be taken seriously.''
   She said the ``last straw'' was when she received an achievement
award from the state Hispanic Chamber of Commerce. ``I knew I had to
do something,'' she said.
   The name change has been approved by a court commissioner and
takes effect Jan. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1333EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Tanks     12-22 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Tanks,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dismantled Tanks Will Give Their Engines to Domestic Use</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union plans to recycle engines from the
10,000 army tanks being withdrawn from Europe for use in the lagging
domestic economy, the official news agency Tass reported Thursday.
   Fuel tanker trucks and cargo trailers attached to the six tank
divisions being disbanded also will be transferred to civilian use,
Tass said, quoting Maj. Gen. Yuri Lebedev of the armed forces
general staff.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the United Nations on Dec. 7
the Soviet armed forces would be cut by 500,000 soldiers in the next
two years to show the West that its intentions are defensive rather
than offensive.
   The reductions include six tank divisions on the front line with
NATO, in Hungary, Czechoslovakia and East Germany.
   Gorbachev has said repeatedly that the Soviet Union must
concentrate its resources on domestic problems. Soviet media
previously have reported plans to shift certain military factories
to the production of badly needed consumer goods.
   Last spring, a factory in Odessa reportedly began to convert
missile platforms into 80-ton construction cranes, as the Soviet
Union started dismantling SS-20 rockets under the superpower arms
control treaty signed last year.
   Lebedev denied Western charges that the reductions in Soviet
armed forces in Eastern Europe and the European part of the Soviet
Union would cover only aging, outdated tanks or only auxiliary units
to the armored divisions.
   ``Six tank divisions will be disbanded and the military hardware,
including the most up-to-date tanks, will be destroyed,'' except for
the engines, Tass reported Lebedev as saying. The article said
Lebedev emphasized that the units ``will be pulled out in full stre
ngth, with all their military hardware.''
   Lebedev also said the Soviet Union expects the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization ``to take reciprocal steps'' toward making its
armed forces truly defensive, Tass reported.
   Lebedev also said the greatest difficulty for the Soviet Union in
connection with the troop cuts will be finding housing for the
veteran servicemen. The Soviet Union has a severe, chronic housing
shortage, and most construction resources have been dedicated to
rebuilding the areas of Armenia devasted by the Dec. 7 earthquake.
</TEXT>
