<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Homeless Bjt   12-22 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless, Bjt,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Forecast is Bleak for the Nation's Homeless</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THEASA TUOHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the nation's growing number of homeless may find no room
at the shelter this Christmas, meaning home for the holidays could
be under a bridge, over a steam vent or in a cardboard box.
   Boston guarantees a bed, Arizona vows to make shelter available
by Christmas Eve, and a celebration in a heated tent is planned for
the homeless in front of the Capitol on Christmas Eve. But the
nation's capital has only 2,500 slots for the 10,000 to 15,000 with
no bed of their own.
   California Gov. George Deukmejian last month authorized counties
to continue to use armories as shelters under a program started last
year. Estimates of the number of homeless there range from 100,000
to 200,000.
   ``California may be the place of year-round sunshine in the eyes
of our Eastern friends, but when you have no roof over your head,
even a California winter can be cruel and punishing,'' Deukmejian
said.
   In New York City, the estimated number of homeless has increased
25 percent during the last year with the total estimated between
60,000 and 90,000; in Portland, Ore., the number rose 10 to 20
percent each year this decade.
   ``There's been a steady increase of about 25 percent a year that
hasn't changed in six years,'' said Keith Summa of the Coalition for
the Homeless in New York City.
   In Oklahoma City, there are an estimated 17,000 homeless and no
state or city-run shelters. In Phoenix, with 6,000 to 9,000
homeless, Mary Orton, director of Central Arizona Shelter Services,
said there are only about 1,000 beds.
   The remainder ``sleep on the streets, in parks, in their cars,
under bushes, anywhere they can,'' Ms. Orton said.
   Arizona Gov. Rose Mofford tried to make a National Guard armory
or other state buildings available for Phoenix-area homeless but was
advised she could not legally use state emergency funds to pay for
the operation.
   The governor will find some other way to make more beds available
by Christmas Eve, said Vada Manager, her press secretary.
   Christine Byrd, regional director of the National Coalition for
the Homeless in Oklahoma City said a December report from a
governor's task force put the total for the state at 35,000 and
17,000 for the city.
   Ms. Byrd said 48 percent are families, in part because of
Oklahoma's location at the nation's center. Poor families going from
the West Coast to the East or vice versa run out of gas or have car
trouble there, she said.
   The coalition estimated the number of homeless nationally at as
many as 3 million.
   Boston seems to have the distinction of being one of the few
cities where the number of homeless has not drastically increased in
the last two or three years. In both 1987 and 1988, the city's
estimate of homeless was under 3,500.
   ``Whoever needs a bed gets one,'' says Ann Maguire, executive
director of the Boston Emergency Shelter Commission. If there is no
room at one shelter, the city provides a van or police car to get
the person to a shelter with room.
   Baloney Joe's, a Portland, Ore., shelter for homeless men, is
``so full we're stacking people on top of each other,'' said Gene
Ediger of the Burnside Community Council, a private agency for the
homeless. He said the number of homeless has gone up 10 to 20
percent each year of the 1980s.
   In Philadelphia, the city has started daily cleanups of a subway
concourse where homeless people set up boxes, mattresses and
blankets. Police have not stopped homeless people from returning.
   ``Christmas is a time of enchantment, but not when you're
homeless,'' said Sister Mary Scullion, who runs a residence for
mentally ill homeless women in Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
