<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1447EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Crash-Threat 6thLd-Writethru a0617 12-22 1175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Threat, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0617,1100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embassies, Pan Am Were Warned of Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7-9th graf, A U.S., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with State
Department spokeswoman describing threat of person `unwittingly'
carrying bomb.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department warned U.S. embassies that
a bomb threat had been made against Pan Am jetliners flying from
Frankfurt to the United States 2{ weeks before the crash of a New
York-bound flight originating in Germany, U.S. officials said today.
   In addition, a Pan American World Airways official said the
Federal Aviation Administration told the airline early this month
that Pan Am might be the target of a terrorist bombing on a route
from Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Pan Am Flight 103 crashed Wednesday in Scotland, killing all 259
people aboard and more than 20 people on the ground, and U.S. and
British officials said the plane probably exploded before the crash.
The flight originated in Frankfurt with a Boeing 727. Passengers and
luggage were transferred to the 747 at London's Heathrow Airport.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater defended the State
Department notification of the embassies, but he acknowledged that
the ``public should be aware of the general threat'' as well.
   ``I think that certainly will be looked at,'' Fitzwater told
reporters. ``Public notification has to be considered.''
   Asked why there was none in this case, he said, ``I don't have an
answer on that. ... The issue is, there are so many of these
(threats) that this was determined to be the appropriate level of
notification.''
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said that on Dec. 5,
an inidentified caller told the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki that
sometime within the next two weeks ``an unidentified person in
Helsinki would unwittingly take the device to Frankfurt and
eventually onto the New York onto the U.S.-bound flight.''
   ``Pan Am had received notification from various sources that
there was the possibility of a threat against Pan American
Airways,'' said Pan Am spokeswoman Pam Hanlon in New York. ``We
immediately acted and put supplementary security procedures in
effect, not only at Frankfurt but at airports around the world.''
She declined to say what steps were taken.
   Ms. Hanlon said added precautions were taken at London and all
other major airports, with some given higher priority, but she
declined to say which airports were considered at most serious risk.
   She confirmed that one of the warnings came from the FAA in the
form of a memo but said ``for security reasons we do not circulate
them publicly.''
   At the U.S. Embassy in Moscow, a Dec. 13 circular from William C.
Kelly, the administrative counselor, had been posted on bulletin
boards.
   It read: ``Post (the embassy) has been notified by the Federal
Aviation Administration that on Dec. 5, 1988, an unidentified
individual telephoned a U.S. diplomatic facility in Europe and
stated that sometime within the next two weeks there would be a
bombing attempt against a Pan American aircraft flying from
Frankfurt to the United States.''
   It continued: ``The FAA reports that the reliability of the
information cannot be assessed at this point, but the appropriate
police authorities have been notified and are pursuing the matter.
Pan Am has also been notified.
   ``In view of the lack of confirmation of this information, post
leaves to the discretion of individual travelers any decisions on
altering personal travel plans or changing to another American
carrier,'' Kelly's circular said.
   Dennis Harter, spokesman for the State Department task force
assigned to deal with the crash, said today that notices such as the
one posted in Moscow had been sent to all U.S. missions around the
world.
   However, he also said such notices are routinely sent out to U.S.
embassies when word is received of threats against American targets,
and a warning of that nature ``would not have been viewed as
anything unusual.''
   Ronald Spiers, under secretary of state for management, told
Cable News Network that there were four U.S. government employees on
the plane, at least two who were assigned to the U.S. Embassy in
Beirut. He said the U.S. ambassador to Lebanon, John McCarthy, would
have been on the flight had he not been delayed in Cyprus.
   One U.S. source, who spoke only under the condition of not being
further identified, said the FAA issued the warning on Dec. 5 but
cautioned that it was not in a position to evaluate the reliability
of the report.
   The FAA in recent years has issued a number of similar reports
involving potential terrorist activity involving air carriers
worldwide, but it could not be ascertained how frequent such reports
are.
   FAA spokesmen declined to comment on whether such a warning was
issued.
   Another source familiar with the warning _ officially termed an
``intelligence alert'' _ said it named no specific terrorist group
but that the threat was ``Middle East oriented.''
   A former FAA official, familiar with such warnings, said that
while they are not unusual they should be considered seriously.
   ``It's more than a hint. It's a direct request to beef up
security,'' said this former official, who asked that his identity
not be revealed. He said that the frequency of such alerts is
sporadic depending on other events in the world. At times the FAA
might issue one every few months but there also might be as many as
a half dozen in two weeks.
   A Frankfurt airport official said today that security was stepped
up at Pan Am after tips were received earlier this month that a bomb
might be smuggled aboard a jet. The official, Horst Harnstein, told
The Associated Press by telephone that the tips were about ``the
transportation of a bomb from Frankfurt heading in the direction of
the United States.''
   Enku Kebede, an employee of Pan Am who works at the airline's
office in the embassy in Moscow, said the threat apparently was
delivered to American officials in Germany and was investigated by
Germany's security service. Ms. Kebede said she learned of the
threat from the memo in the embassy, not from Pan Am.
   ``A lot of people changed their reservations from Pan Am,'' she
said. She said more than a dozen customers changed their flight
plans.
   ABC News quoted FBI sources who said the threat apparently came
from what they described as ``some kind of Islamic group.'' An FBI
spokesman contacted by The Associated Press, William Carter, refused
comment.
   In London today, an anonymous caller to the AP office in London
claimed responsibility for the crash of Flight 103 and said it was
in retaliation for the downing of an Iran Air Airbus by the U.S.
Navy cruiser Vincennes in July.
   ``We, the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution, are undertaking
this heroic execution in revenge of blowing the Iran air plane by
America a few months ago and keeping the Shah's family in America.
We are very proud,'' the male caller said, then hung up quickly. The
Navy said the Iranian plane carrying 290 people over the Persian
Gulf was mistaken for an Iranian fighter.
</TEXT>
