<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Farm-Spain     12-22 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm-Spain,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain Becoming Lucrative Market, USDA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain is rapidly turning into one of the
American farmer's richest overseas markets, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   In the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30, the value of U.S. farm
exports to Spain was $848 million, up 30 percent from $652 million
in 1986-87, the department's Foreign Agricultural Service said in a
report.
   Spain's gross national product, or the sum of its goods and
services, grew 5.5 percent in 1987, the highest in Europe, and is
expected to gain nearly that much in 1988, the report said.
   The surge last fiscal year put Spain among the world's top 10
markets for U.S. agricultural exports. Leading commodities included:
soybeans and soybean meal, corn and corn gluten feed, tallow, hides,
skins, walnuts, peas, beans, lentils, seeds, yellow grease, prunes
and poultry meat.
   In addition, the report said, the United States supplied all of
Spain's imported almonds and half of its imported cattle semen.
</TEXT>
