<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndianCemetery     12-22 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indian Cemetery,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Skeleton Find Leads to Ancient Indian Cemetery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two skeletons at first thought to be the
remains of crime victims have turned out to be part of an ancient
Indian cemetery, a rare find on this part of Florida's Gulf Coast,
an archaeologist says.
   The site, which holds the remains of more than 20 Indians, was
discovered last week on a secluded gulf-front lot where a home was
being built.
   The remains are thought to be at least 400 and possibly as much
as 2,600 years old, said Sonny Cockrell, director and chief
archaeologist of the Warm Mineral Springs Archaeological Research
Project.
   He was called in after state investigators determined the
skeletons were historical in nature, not evidence of a crime.
   The site is in an area where Indian cemeteries are thought to be
rare, Cockrell said.
   Cockrell said the Indians _ adults, teen-agers and infants buried
in fetal positions _ appear to have belonged to a ``buffer society''
that was weaker than tribes that settled to the south and to the
north of it.
   One indication of that is a lack of ceremonial pottery, which
more advanced and wealthier societies used in burying their dead, he
said.
   For the last week, Cockrell and amateur archaeologists have been
digging on the spot with help from residents.
   ``We just found a nice tooth here a couple of minutes ago,'' said
residenet David Atwater. ``I keep saying I'm going to get a bottle
of glue and put it all together.''
</TEXT>
