<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryStrength     12-22 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Strength,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Size of Military Unchanged in November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The active-duty strength of the nation's armed
forces remained static last month following major reductions imposed
in fiscal 1988, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   All told, the Army, Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force reported
2,129,807 men and women on active duty as of Nov. 30, down only 298
from the Oct. 31 total.
   A year earlier, on Nov. 30, 1987, the Pentagon listed 2,174,268
uniformed personnel, or 44,461 more than on the current roster.
   The reduction was mandated in early 1988 when the Reagan
administration, facing budget cuts, decided it would rather have a
smaller military than an underequipped one. Most of the reductions
were made through changes in recruiting goals, tighter re-enlistment
standards and early-discharge incentives.
   The Navy and Marine Corps reported declines in strength during
November, while the other services reported increases.
   As of Nov. 30, the Navy said it had 585,325 men and women on
active duty, down 1,160 from Oct. 31. The Marine Corps said it had
195,937, down 924.
   The Army reported a jump in strength of 1,742 to a new total of
771,111. The Air Force said its active-duty strength climbed by 640
to 577,434 as of Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
