<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PINTLALA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush will be posting
the ``Gone Fishin''' sign yet again next week as he casts for bass
at a private lake in this Montgomery suburb, aides said.
   Bush will be the guest of Ray Scott, founder of the Bass Anglers
Sportsman Society, on Thursday. The two have fished many times since
Bush met Scott during his 1980 presidential bid and eventually
tapped him to run his campaign in Alabama.
   Bush went trout fishing during the Democratic National Convention
and surf fishing after winning the election.
   Dave Precht, editor of Bassmaster magazine, said he thinks the
vice president's interest in fishing could have a positive impact on
the sport.
   ``I'm sure it will,'' he said. ``Bass fishing has been growing
over the past two decades, I believe. It can't hurt.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LOS ANGELES _ Billy Crystal looks mah-velous as host of the
Grammy Awards, the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences
decided in selecting the comedian as emcee for the third consecutive
year.
   Crystal, a former cast member of ``Saturday Night Live'' and star
of ``Throw Momma From the Train,'' ``The Princess Bride'' and other
films, will be host of the 31st Grammy Awards show Feb. 22, it was
announced Tuesday.
   Crystal was nominated for a Grammy in 1986 in the best comedy
recording category for his single ``You Look Mahvelous.''
   CBS will air the awards presentation live from the Shrine
Auditorium.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Busey's move to the rehabilitation wing
of a hospital was described as a step forward in the actor's
recovery from a nearly fatal head injury in a Dec. 4 motorcycle
accident.
   ``This will be the final portion of his stay here,'' Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center spokesman Ron Wise said Wednesday. ``It is basically,
for a lack of a better term, to fine tune him. This is a step
forward. He will be working with weights.''
   Wise said Busey continues to show improvement and was in fair
condition. Doctors have not decided when to release him.
   Busey, 44, who has campaigned against laws to make motorcyclists
wear helmets, wasn't wearing one when he lost control of his
motorcycle and hit his head on a curb. Doctors said he apparently
suffered no brain damage.
   Busey has starred in such movies as ``The Buddy Holly Story,''
``Bear,'' ``Carny'' and ``Lethal Weapon.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father and son scriptwriting team
are accusing Bill Cosby and the producers of ``The Cosby Show'' of
plagiarism, contending that the series used parts of their rejected
script in several episodes.
   In their federal lawsuit filed last week, Henry and Daniel Shea
of Berkley contend that a script they submitted in June 1986 was
turned down but then used in fragments over seven shows broadcast
between September 1986 and November 1987.
   Representatives for the show in New York declined comment.
   The suit asks for damages of at least $25,000.
   ``We have a line-by-line comparison of the submitted script and
the dialogue from the finished shows,'' the Sheas' attorney, Joseph
Moch, said Wednesday. ``The overlapping areas are too similar, and
occur too frequently, to be coincidence.''
   In addition to Cosby, the lawsuit names members of the NBC show's
production team, including executive producers Marcy Carsey and Tom
Werner and Dr. Alvin F. Poussaint, the Harvard psychiatrist who
oversees the show's content.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Mansfield, retiring as U.S. ambassador to Japan
after 11 years in Tokyo, left for home Thursday, saying he was
satisfied that U.S.-Japan relations ``are stronger and more vital''
than ever.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi bade the 85-year-old
ambassador farewell at his residence.
   ``Much remains to be done. However, the foundation has been
laid,'' Mansfield said. ``I am confident that our governments and
our peoples have the means and the will to find the solutions that
will ensure even closer cooperation in the years to come.''
   President-elect George Bush will appoint the next ambassador to
Tokyo.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Vickery, director of the music
program for the National Endowment for the Arts in the nation's
capital, has been named president and managing director of the St.
Paul Chamber Orchestra.
   Vickery, 39, will coordinate administrative and artistic
functions of the organization, it was announced Wednesday.
   The appointment marks the culmination of a search that began with
the resignation of Deborah Borda on Sept. 29. Borda will leave Jan.
1 to become executive director of the Detroit Symphony Orchestra
Hall Inc.
   Vickery was appointed music program director of the National
Endowment for the Arts in 1987.
