<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash Bjt 2Takes 12-22 0924</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash, Bjt, 2 Takes,0953</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT
^Experts Zero In on Terrorist Bombing as Cause of Pan Am Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON23,26; XDUM9,10; LaserGraphic NY21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evidence mounted Thursday that
terrorists blew up a Pan Am jumbo jet bound for New York, killing
all 259 people aboard and at least 22 in this Scottish village that
was showered with flaming debris.
   Terrorist threats that a Pan Am jet was marked for destruction
and the Boeing 747's sudden plunge from the sky Wednesday night
prompted experts to focus on sabotage.
   Britain's top anti-terrorist official joined the British-led
investigation on Thursday.
   Transport Secretary Paul Channon announced that the plane's
flight data and cockpit voice recorders had been found.
   Officials said the jet jammed with Christmas travelers likely
exploded in the air before it plummeted from an altitude of 31,000
feet.
   Witnesses said the giant aircraft was bathed in flame before it
plowed into a hillside outside the southwestern Scotland village of
Lockerbie and bounced into the center of town, gutting dozens of
homes and raining burning metal onto cars.
   People living up to 70 miles away reported finding clothing and
Christmas cards hurled from the jet.
   An anonymous caller claimed Thursday that Iranians blew up the
plane in retaliation for the U.S. Navy's downing of an Iranian
airliner carrying 290 people in July. Tehran strongly denied
involvement.
   The flight originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, changed planes
in London and was in the air 54 minutes when it vanished from radar
screens at 7:19 p.m. (2:19 p.m. EST) on Wednesday. Authorities said
the plane was on course and weather conditions would not have
contributed to the crash.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the State Department
warned U.S. embassies about Dec. 7 about a bomb threat that had been
made two days earlier against Pan Am jetliners flying from Frankfurt.
   He said he could not explain why more people had not been
notified of the threat, and he acknowleged that ``the public should
be aware'' of such threats.
   ``I think that certainly will be looked at,'' Fitzwater told
reporters.
   No passenger list was released, but the dead included 38 Syracuse
Universty students who had been studying abroad and were returning
home for the holidays; at least six U.S. servicemen; and Bernt
Carlsson of Sweden, the U.N. commissioner for Namibia.
   The jet, which destroyed 40 houses, killed 22 people on the
ground, most of them occupants of cars pounded by wreckage, said
Desmond Park, a local official.
   The area police chief, John Boyd, said 13 adults and four
children who had been in Lockerbie when the plane crashed were
unaccounted for. Others were feared killed in five cars that were
gutted by wreckage.
   Britain's worst-ever air crash sent a wave of grief across the
country. Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher sent President Reagan her
condolences and toured the devastated village of 2,500.
   Police Superintendant Angus Kennedy told a news conference
Thursday that the bodies of 150 passengers, including three
children, had been recovered.
   U.S. Ambassador Charles H. Price II and Scottish Secretary
Malcolm Rifkind inspected the wreckage and both said they believed
there had been an explosion in the air.
   ``The aircraft clearly experienced some form of explosion,'' said
Rifkind, the Cabinet minister responsible for Scotland.
   In July, the U.S. warship Vincennes downed an Iran Air Airbus
A300 in the Persian Gulf, saying it was thought to be a hostile
warplane.
   An anonymous man telephoned The Associated Press bureau in London
and said: ``We the guardians of the Islamic revolution are
undertaking this heroic execution in revenge of blowing the Iran Air
plane by America a few months ago and keeping the Shah's family in
America. We are very proud,'' the caller said, then hung up quickly.
   The same group had also claimed responsibility last year for a
car bombing in London that wounded Amir Hussein Amir-Parviz,
chairman of the National Movement for Iranian resistance and a
former Iranian Cabinet minister under the Shah.
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi ``categorically denied any
Iranian involvement'' and expressed regret at the crash, said Iran's
official news agency.
   In Washington, a government source said the U.S. Embassy in
Helsinki, Finland, received a telephone threat about two weeks ago
from a person claiming to belong to the Abu Nidal group, a radical
Palestinian faction that has been implicated in terrorist attacks.
   The caller said a bomb would be placed aboard a Pan Am plane and
that it would be carried by a woman, said the government source, who
spoke on condiition of anonymity.
   The government source said that threat was the basis for posting
notices at U.S. embassies.
   Finland's Foreign Ministry said it had found no direct connection
between the bomb threat it received and the crash in Scotland. The
ministry confirmed the Israeli and U.S. embassies had received
several threats during the year by an Arab resident, most recently
on Dec. 5.
   The Foreign Ministry statement indicated the authorities knew the
caller's identity, and said ``the suspected phone caller has not
left Finland since he made his last threatening telephone call'' 17
days ago.
   ``In the investigation so far, no direct connection has been
found between the Arab living in Finland and the air accident in
question,'' the statement said.
   In Moscow, the U.S. Embassy last week warned American diplomats
that a bomb threat had been made against a Pan Am flight flying from
Frankfurt to the United States sometime in December. Pan Am Flight
103 originated in Frankfurt, with a different aircraft.
</TEXT>
