<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash Bjt-1stAdd   12-22 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash, Bjt - 1st Add,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT
^LOCKERBIE: different aircraft.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Frankfurt, the airport security chief said officials stepped
up security at Pan Am after receiving threats against the U.S.
airline earlier this month.
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pam Hanlon in New York said the airline was
aware of the threat and put ``supplementary security procedures in
effect, not only at Frankfurt but airports around the world.''
   She said Pan Am received a memo from the Federal Aviation
Administration about the threat and quoted the document as saying:
``The information in this bulletin is soley for the use of U.S.
carriers and airport security personnel and may not be further
disseminated without the specific approval of the director of civil
aviation security.''
   Scotland Yard said the head of its anti-terrorism squad,
Commander George Churchill-Coleman, had taken charge of the London
end of the crash inquiry.
   ``Sabotage is the most likely explanation,'' said David Kyd,
spokesman for the International Air Transport Association in Geneva.
He said structural failure was unlikely.
   Freddie Yetman, technical secretary of the British Airline Pilots
Association, agreed. ``The possibility of structural failure is
almost too remote to be considered.''
   Federal Aviation Service records showed the 18{-year-old aircraft
had 21 mechanical defects since 1980. A Boeing spokesman said the
plane was taken out of service last year for substantial
modifications, and any structural deficiencies observed earlier
would have been corrected.
   Pratt & Whitney in East Hartford, Conn., which built the engines,
said the plane could have continued to fly even if three of its four
engines had failed.
   Ariel Merari, an Israeli terrorism expert interviewed by a
British TV network, said Iranian involvement was unlikely, given
Tehran's eagerness to improve relations with the West.
   He pointed to the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command, a hard-line faction opposed to PLO leader
Yasser Arafat's attempts to project a moderate image.
   Merari said a ``very large terrorist team'' from that group was
rounded up in West Germany last month.
   ``They apparently had in mind exactly what happened now ...,''
Merari said. ``It is possible that another team like the one that
was caught was in the area and succeeded in carrying out its
mission.''
   Lockerbie's town hall was turned into a makeshift morgue as
firefighters recoverd bodies. Eight corpses lay covered on a nearby
golf course.
   Around Lockerbie, scorched pillows, lifejackets and fragments of
clothing lay scattered in gardens. Chunks of metal had sliced
through roofs and shattered windows in homes and cars.
   Charred dollar bills, a mud-spattered seatbelt, and tattered
copies of the Pan Am inflight magazine added to the melancholy scene.
   One large chunk of fuselage blasted a huge, blackened crater in a
village residential area.
   The jet's blue-and-white nose section, its Clipper name ``Maid of
the Seas'' clearly visible, landed three miles outside Lockerbie,
near a church in Tundergarth.
</TEXT>
