<HEAD>Israeli Soldier Dies of Wounds, 15 Palestinians Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli soldier died Thursday in a London
hospital from injuries he suffered trying to rescue a woman and her
children from a bus that was firebombed by Palestinians, the army
said.
   Also Thursday, troops shot and wounded 16 Palestinians in
scattered clashes in the occupied territories, Arab doctors said.
   The army confirmed nine wounded, and was checking further.
   The soldier's death raised to 14 the number of Israelis who have
been killed in the year-long Palestinian revolt against Israeli rule
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. At least 333 Palestinians also have
died.
   A military spokesman identified the soldier as 19-year-old David
Deloroza of Jerusalem.
   Deloroza was transferred to a London hospital for an operation to
replace his heart and lungs, which were severely damaged from smoke
inhalation during the Oct. 31 attack by Palestinian guerrillas near
the city of Jericho.
   Deloroza tried to save Rachel Weiss, an Israeli woman who refused
to leave the burning bus without her three small children. Mrs.
Weiss and the children burned to death.
   In the biblical town of Bethlehem, activists belonging to a
communist Palestinian faction painted slogans on walls in red
warning Christians to abide by a general strike called for Christmas
Eve.
   ``Remain home on Dec. 24,'' read one slogan. ``No Christmas
celebrations, only prayers,'' said another.
   In the West Bank's largest city of Nablus, protests erupted after
the army lifted a curfew, ending six days of restrictions.
   Six people were wounded in the ensuing clashes with troops, Arab
hospital officials said.
   Elsewhere in the West Bank, one man was wounded in Hebron and
another was wounded during an army raid of the village of Kfar
Kaddum near Nablus, doctors said.
   Scattered clashes also occured in the occupied Gaza Strip after
the army lifted a curfew from the territory's eight refugee camps.
Eight Palestinians were wounded, including a 9-year-old boy shot in
the abdomen, doctors said.
</TEXT>
