<1ST_LINE>r i AM-RedCross     12-22 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Red Cross,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Red Cross Completes Evacuation; Ambassador Also Leaves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEURBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Swiss Red Cross delegates flew home from
Cyprus on Thursday, completing an unprecedented evacuation of the
relief organization's personnel because of terrorist threats.
   Switzerland's ambassador to Lebanon also left the Middle East
nation for Cyprus on Thursday.
   Speculation grew that Palestinian radicals opposed to the PLO's
new policy toward Israel were behind the death threats against Red
Cross personnel and also behind last month's kidnapping of Peter
Winkler, the Red Cross chief delegate at Sidon in south Lebanon.
   Winkler was released Dec. 16 after being held hostage for 29
days. Foreign Minister Rene Felber said last weekend that Winkler's
captors had identified themselves as the ``Organization of Socialist
Revolution,'' a dissident Palestinian group.
   A senior official in the Foreign Ministry, Alfred Ruegg, told
Swiss radio Thursday it seemed that the same group also issued the
death threats against Winkler's colleagues in Lebanon.
   In Beirut, leaders of Lebanon's rival Moslem and Christian
governments were dismayed at the action of the International
Committee for the Red Cross.
   ``We cannot but express our regret over the evacuation,'' said
Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads the Christian military cabinet.
   Salim Hoss, prime minister of the Moslem cabinet, instructed
Lebanon's chief diplomat in Geneva, Salim Naffaa, to ``express
Lebanon's dismay and surprise at the Swiss action,'' an official
statement said.
   Michel Dufour, the chief Red Cross delegate in Lebanon, arrived
in Switzerland on a Swissair flight from Cyprus with two companions,
Michel Berger and Peter Franken.
   On an earlier ferry from Lebanon to Cyprus, they were accompanied
by Swiss Ambassador Dino Sciolli, his wife and nine other Swiss
nationals, believed to be staff from the embassy in Beirut. All
declined to talk to reporters.
   Airport officials said Sciolli did not accompany the Red Cross
delegates to Switzerland and would remain in Nicosia, Cyprus, for a
day or two before returning to Switzerland for consultations.
   Eleven other Red Cross officials arrived in Larnaca, on the south
coast of Cyprus, Wednesday and flew on to Zurich several hours later.
   It was the first evacuation because of terrorist threats in the
125-year history of the organization.
   A Swiss radio commentary said Thursday that Syrian-backed
opponents of Arafat seemed to be trying to spread doubts about his
renunciation of terrorism and to sabotage the PLO talks with the
United States, which opened last week after a 13-year ban.
   It noted that Winkler had been abducted two days after the
Palestine National Council, meeting in Algeria, declared an
independent Palestinian state and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   In Geneva last week for a special U.N. General Assembly meeting
on Palestine, Arafat followed this up with an explicit recognition
of Israel's right to exist.
   A Red Cross spokesman, Carlos Bauverd, said Wednesday that the
threats must be seen ``in the context of the situation following the
General Assembly'' but refused to elaborate.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization is an umbrella for several
groups, including Arafat's Fatah. Several PLO members, angered over
Arafat's comments, have said they would work to oust him from the
PLO leadership.
   Fifteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing and
believed held hostage in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press.
He was abducted March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
