<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Court Study,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rehnquist Names Court Study Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist on Thursday
named 15 people _ federal and state judges, lawyers and four members
of Congress _ to a committee that will study federal court problems.
   The committee, authorized in a law President Reagan signed last
month, has 15 months to conduct hearings and issue a report that is
to include a plan for the future of federal courts.
   The committee is expected to begin its work in January, according
to David Sellers, a spokesman for the Administrative Office of the
U.S. Courts.
   Rehnquist named Joseph F. Weis Jr., a federal appellate judge in
Pittsburgh, as the committee's chairman.
   The committee's other members are: Sens. Charles Grassley,
R-Iowa, and Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; Reps. Robert Kastenmeier, D-Wis.,
and Carlos Moorhead, R-Calif.; federal judges Jose Cabranes of New
Haven, Conn., Levin H. Campbell of Boston, Judith Keep of San Diego
and Richard Posner of Chicago.
   Also: Keith Callow, chief justice of the Washington Supreme
Court; J. Vincent Aprile, general counsel of the Kentucky Department
of Public Advocacy; Edward Dennis, a Justice Department lawyer; and
private practitioners Rex Lee of Provo, Utah, Diana Gribbon Motz of
Baltimore and Morris Harell of Dallas.
</TEXT>
