<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0641 12-22 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Gets New `National Unity' Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs `A coalition was ...' with 1 graf to correct
to Labor has 39 seats, sted of 40.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's rival Likud and Labor parties formed
their second successive ``national unity'' government Thursday to
meet the challenge of the more moderate PLO image and the
Palestinian declaration of independence.
   ``Developments in the international arena and challenges we are
facing require us to bridge our differences to overcome the
obstacles and dangers we face,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir told
the Knesset, or parliament, in an hour-long speech.
   The new 28-member Cabinet, led by Shamir of the conservative
Likud bloc, was presented to the Knesset for ceremonial approval.
Two Labor members and one from Likud abstained in protest.
   A coalition was necessary because neither major party won control
of the 120-member Knesset in the Nov. 1 election. Likud got 40
seats, the center-left Labor Party 39 and smaller parties the other
41.
   Similarly indecisive results in the 1984 election led to the
first coalition, in which the two major parties were equal partners.
This one is led by Likud.
   In his speech to the Knesset, Shamir called making peace the
``first and foremost objective.''
   He urged Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip to
end their year-old uprising so they and Israel can ``create
conditions for a peaceful coexistence, freedom and prosperity for
you and your children.''
   The prime minister again ruled out talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization and said negotiations should be based on the
U.S.-mediated Camp David accords of 1978, which provide for direct
talks between Israel and Jordan and the Palestinians. The PLO and
Arab nations want an international conference under U.N. sponsorship
   Labor Party leader Shimon Peres, who will be deputy premier and
finance minister, supports an international conference. He also has
recommended elections in the occupied territories to choose
Palestinians who would negotiate with Israel.
   Peres was foreign minister in the outgoing government, but Moshe
Arens of Likud has the portfolio in the new one. Holdovers include
Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin of Labor and Industry Minister Ariel
Sharon of Likud.
   Shamir urged the United States to reverse its decision to deal
directly with the PLO after Yasser Arafat, the PLO chairman,
recognized Israel and renounced terrorism.
   Israel considers the PLO a terrorist organization and Shamir said
Thursday: ``According to our knowledge it has not changed its skin,
its habits, its evil charter and the terror that it uses. We still
hope the United States will reconsider its decision.''
   Foreign policy guidelines adopted by the coalition reject
establishment of a Palestinian state in the occupied lands and call
for five to eight new Jewish settlements to be built in the there in
1989.
   The coalition agreement was signed about two hours before the
Knesset session, and toasted with wine. Asked after the ceremony how
he felt, Peres said:
   ``I am not excited. I'm worried. We have problems we are not
going to be able to solve over a glass of wine.''
   He pledged to work for reform of a complicated electoral system
that favors small parties and makes coalitions necessary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
