<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1616EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-JeanHarris Bjt   12-22 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jean Harris, Bjt,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Headmistress Hoping For Clemency After Eight Years In Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD HILLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean Harris, the school headmistress
convicted in the shooting death of her lover, Scarsdale Diet
developer Dr. Herman Tarnower, is hoping for Christmas clemency
after eight years behind bars.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo traditionally grants clemency at Christmastime
and sometimes New Year's, and friends and supporters are working
hard to make sure the 65-year-old Mrs. Harris is on the list.
   ``She tries not to think about it at all,'' said her lawyer,
Michael Kennedy. ``It's so important to her, she tries not to
concentrate on it. I think she's guardedly optimistic.''
   Mrs. Harris was convicted of murdering Tarnower, a cardiologist,
at his home in Purchase, north of New York City. Prosecutors said
she killed her lover of 14 years in a jealous rage over his romance
with a younger woman.
   The former head of the exclusive Madeira School for Girls in
McLean, Va., maintained she shot Tarnower by accident in 1980 when
he tried to stop her from committing suicide.
   Mrs. Harris, who is serving a 15-years-to-life sentence at the
Bedford Hills Correctional Facility, became eligible for clemency in
August, when she served half her minimum sentence, the unofficial
benchmark.
   Clemency commutes a sentence and allows an inmate to become
eligible for parole. Final release from prison must be granted by
the State Parole Board.
   Inmates generally have to serve their minimum term before
appearing before the Parole Board. In Mrs. Harris' case, that would
mean 1996.
   She declined a request for an interview and has not commented on
the issue. She wrote a letter applying for clemency, but it has not
been released.
   Health can be a factor in clemency approval; Mrs. Harris suffered
at least one heart attack in prison. Her age and good prison record
also may be grounds. She has been active in the Children's Center at
the prison, has taught and wrote two books.
   Cuomo's decisions on clemency are based on advice from a
three-person Executive Clemency Board, which reviews opinions from
those involved in a case. The clemency process is kept under close
wraps until a decision is announced.
   ``Each case is decided on its own merits,'' said Cuomo spokesman
Terry Lynam. ``There's no concern of public relations. If an inmate
is deserving of clemency, he or she will get it.''
   Mrs. Harris applied for clemency in 1986, but it was denied on
the ground that she had not served half her minimum sentence.
   Anne Lennox, a former professional colleague who now heads the
Jean Harris Defense Fund in Monroe, N.H., said Mrs. Harris knows to
be realistic about clemency.
   ``She's been turned down once,'' Lennox said. ``She's seen other
women in prison be turned down.''
   Last summer, Lennox's group and Harris' son began soliciting
letters and petition signatures on her behalf. As many as 10,000
letters and 25,000 signatures have been sent to Cuomo, said the son,
James Harris.
   Tarnower's sister, nieces and nephews wrote Cuomo last summer
opposing release, said the family lawyer, Roger Sirlin.
   Russell Leggett, the judge who sentenced Harris, has backed
Harris' bid for clemency. Rich Weill, a spokesman for the
Westchester County district attorney, would not say whether his
office has voiced an opinion to the governor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
