<DOCNO> AP881222-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1922EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GrainSales     12-22 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grain Sales,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets, Chinese Buy More U.S. Grain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and China have bought more
grain from the United States, including wheat sold to Beijing at
subsidized prices, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Moscow's order was for an additional 1 million metric tons of
corn for delivery under a recently extended supply agreement between
the two countries, the department announced. China bought 400,000
tons of wheat under the subsidy program.
   The latest sales by private exporting companies brought total
corn sold to the Soviets to almost 8.03 million tons in the
agreement's sixth year, which began Oct. 1. Last year, U.S. corn
sales to the Soviet Union totaled slightly less than 5.2 million
tons.
   Exporters are required to report foreign grain sales of 100,000
tons or more to the USDA within 24 hours. Smaller sales are reported
weekly.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1 million tons of
corn would be about 39.4 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.61 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $103 million.
   Although no wheat has yet been sold for 1988-89 delivery under
the pact, the Soviets have ordered 500,000 tons of soybeans and
532,500 tons of soybean meal, plus 500,000 tons of grain sorghum.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said seven export companies were
involved in the sale of 400,000 tons of wheat to China, some 14.7
million bushels having an estimated farm value of $58 million at
recent prices.
   The companies included: Cargill Inc., 90,000 tons; Central States
Enterprises, 40,000 tons; Nissho Iwai American Corp., 30,000 tons;
Bunge Corp., 40,000 tons; Tradigrain Inc., 50,000 tons; Tradecom
Inc., 30,000 tons; and Louis Dreyfus Corp., 120,000 tons.
   Sims said the sales were part of an authorized 1 million tons of
wheat announced on Dec. 7 under the Export Enhancement Program, or
EEP. With the latest sales, China now has 210,000 tons remaining
under the authorization.
   The program enables exporters to sell wheat and other designated
commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to
meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sims said the bonuses due the seven exporters for the latest deal
averaged $23.10 per ton of wheat, or about 63 cents per bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
