<DOCNO> AP881222-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1925EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC--DiabetesMortality     12-22 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC--Diabetes Mortality,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Good News And Bad News: Diabetes Mortality Is Down _ Sort Of</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. death rate from diabetes, the nation's
seventh-leading killer, dropped sharply during the 1970s but seems
to have stalled in recent years, the Centers for Disease Control
said Thursday.
   The mortality rate from diabetes as the primary cause of death
fell by an average of 4 percent each year from 1970 to 1979 _ from
21 such deaths per 100,000 people in 1970 to 14.9 nine years later,
the CDC said.
   The number of deaths caused by diabetes dropped from 38,324 in
1970 to 33,192 in 1979.
   But in the following six years, the mortality rate from diabetes
fell only slightly to 14.7 per 100,000 by 1985, the latest year for
which data are available. The number of deaths actually increased
somewhat, to 36,969.
   ``That's something we don't have an answer for,'' said Robert R.
German, a CDC diabetes specialist. ``After 1980, for some reason, it
appears to be leveling off.''
   The same pattern is evident in statistics on cases in which
diabetes was part of the diagnosis but not necessarily the primary
cause of death.
   The rate of diabetes-related deaths dropped from 75.7 per 100,000
people in 1970 to 57.7 in 1979, then went up to 59.1 by 1985, German
said. The number of deaths dropped from 137,241 in 1970 to 128,373
in 1979, then went up again to 148,284 in 1985.
   ``We're in the process of trying to determine what is going on,''
German said.
   Overall, the decline in mortality from diabetes may reflect two
factors, the CDC said: a trend away from listing diabetes on death
certificates, or an actual decline as a result of improved treatment
and longer survival for patients.
   Diabetes typically is present in older people; in 1980, 84
percent of diabetes patients were 45 or older, and 40 percent were
65 or older, the CDC said.
   The CDC report concerns diabetes mellitus, which is widely
referred to simply as diabetes.
   According to the American Diabetes Association, more than 11
million Americans suffer from diabetes, a disease caused by the
body's inability to produce or properly use insulin, a hormone
needed to convert sugar into energy.
   Complications from diabetes include blindness, heart and kidney
disease, nerve damage and gangrene that can cause loss of limbs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
