<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Honduras Exercise,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Exercises Set For Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said Thursday it had scheduled new
military exercises in Honduras in 1989.
   The first of the exercises will begin in mid-January under the
code name Ahuas Tara 89 and consist of two phases _ an engineering
road-building exercise and a so-called command post exercise.
   The engineering exercise will involve 1,924 soldiers from units
based at Fort Bragg, N.C., and Fort Riley, Kan., the Pentagon said.
The command post exercise will involve a smaller number of troops
and will focus on a test of communications and command-and-control
networks.
   The exercise schedule will extend through mid-July, the Pentagon
added.
   ``The planning for this exercise took place last year,'' the
Pentagon said in a statement. ``The timeframe was scheduled to take
advantage of the dry season to enhance the effectiveness of the
engineering work.''
