<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MiamiNewspapers-Justice     12-22 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miami Newspapers-Justice,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Investigating Revised Agreement Between Miami Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is investigating a
revised joint operating agreement involving the Miami Herald and the
Miami News, a department spokesman said Thursday.
   The preliminary investigation, which was opened Wednesday, will
delve into whether there might be a violation of antitrust laws,
Justice spokesman Mark Sheehan said.
   Sheehan declined to comment when asked whether the department
would ask that the Miami News be kept open past Dec. 31. He said
there have been instances in which ``we will ask the parties to
freeze the status quo while we sort out the facts.''
   The investigation deals with possible violations of the Sherman
Antitrust Act, Sheehan said.
   The Sherman act, among other things, prohibits anti-competitive
agreements among competitors or monopolistic conduct.
   The renegotiated joint operating agreement announced in October
calls for Cox Enterprises, which owns the News, to share in the
operating profits of the Knight-Ridder-owned Miami Herald until the
year 2021 whether the News is publishing a newspaper in Miami or not.
   The amended agreement calls for Cox to receive a lower percentage
of operating profits from the Herald than it has been receiving
since the two papers engaged in a partial merger 22 years ago.
   For Knight-Ridder, the renegotiation means being relieved of
having to cover 85 percent of the News' losses through 1996. The
revised agreement calls for Miami Herald Publishing Co. to absorb
half of the News' losses in 1989 and none after that.
   A week after the renegotiation, Cox announced it would fold the
92-year-old evening News on Dec. 31 if it is unable to sell the
newspaper.
   The Herald took over advertising, circulation and printing of the
two newspapers in 1966 under a joint operating agreement. The news
and editorial operations of the two papers remained separate.
   The chairman of Cox, James Kennedy, said in a letter to the
Justice Department last month that the News, which now has a
circulation of 48,000, had sustained losses of more than $90 million
since the operating agreement was implemented. The News circulation
in 1966 was 112,000.
</TEXT>
