<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-MiddleEast 1stLd-Writethru a0694 12-22 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Middle East, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0694,0802</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Denies Involvement in Pan Am Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 1 graf to CORRECT spelling of Abu Nidal.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's prime minister on Thursday denied
there was an Iranian role in the fiery crash of a Pan Am jet, and he
expressed regret over the incident.
   Prime Minister Hussein Musavi ``categorically denied any Iranian
involvement'' in the crash, said the official Islamic Republic News
Agency, monitored in Nicosia.
   Pan Am Flight 103, on its way from London to New York after
originating in Frankfurt, crashed Wednesday evening in the Scottish
village of Lockerbie.
   There were two claims of responsibilty: one from a litle-known,
supposedly pro-Iranian group and one from the Abu Nidal radical
Palestinian faction.
   An anonymous male telephoned The Associated Press in London,
identifying himself as from ``The Guardians of the Islamic
Revolution.'' He said the group had staged what he called a ``heroic
execution'' in reprisal for the downing of an Iran Air Airbus A300
by the U.S. Navy cruiser Vincennes in July, in which 290 people were
killed.
   The Navy said the plane had been mistaken for an Iranian fighter.
   ``We are very proud,'' the caller said before hanging up.
   As far as is known, the group surfaced only once before _ last
year in London, when it claimed responsibility for a car bombing in
which an Iranian dissident leader was wounded.
   Beyond that, nothing is known of the group, and pro-Iranian
terrorists constantly change the group names they use.
   The downing of the Iranian jet raised what Iranian President Ali
Khamenei termed ``a wave of rage'' among his countrymen and howls
for revenge. The Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini called for all-out war
against the Americans.
   But more pragmatic figures, led by Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, sought to cool tempers and turn the disaster to Iran's
political advantage.
   On July 20, the United Nations Security Council unanimously
adopted a resolution expressing ``deep distress'' over the downing _
a mild formulation aimed at avoiding a U.S. veto.
   President Reagan offered to compensate the families of the
Iranian victims as a humanitarian gesture. But the State Department
said Thursday the reparations have not been made because Washington
has rejected any scheme under which the money would be handed over
to the Iranian government. Iran insists that it handle the payments.
   It also emerged Thursday that U.S. diplomats had been warned of a
bomb threat against a Pan Am jet flying from Frankfurt to the United
States sometime in December.
   A U.S. government source in Washington said the embassy in
Helsinki received a threat earlier this month from a person claiming
to speak for Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council faction, which
has been blamed for scores of terrorist attacks over the last decade.
   In the past, Abu Nidal's renegade Palestinian group has rarely,
if ever, been known to give advance warning of its attacks, which
included the December 1985 massacres at the Rome and Vienna airports.
   But the terrorist mastermind's organization, which has bases in
Lebanon, has been expected to strike to thwart PLO chief Yasser
Arafat's peace initiative and dialogue with the United States.
   In 1974, the Palestine Liberation Organization expelled Abu
Nidal, born as Sabri al-Banna, and sentenced him to death in
absentia for trying to assassinate Arafat because of his
increasingly moderate policies.
   In Helsinki, the Foreign Ministry said it had found no direct
connection between the bomb threat and the crash. The ministry
indicated in a statement that it knew the caller, that he had made
several threats and that he had not left Finland since making his
last threat on Dec. 5.
   The U.S. Embassy in Moscow last week warned American diplomats of
the threat on a Pan Am flight from Frankfurt to the United States.
The warning left it to the diplomats' discretion whether to change
their travel plans.
   But despite the warning, U.S. State Department personnel
reportedly were on the plane. The Washington Post on Thursday quoted
an unidentified State Department spokesman as saying six members of
the department's Diplomatic Security Service, who were returning
from Beirut, were aboard.
   State Department spokesman Ben Justesen told The Associated Press
he could not confirm the report.
   In Nicosia, a non-American diplomatic source who refused to be
further identified said at least three Americans working at the U.S.
embassies in Cyprus and Lebanon were killed. The source quoted U.S.
Ambassador Bill K. Perrin as confirming that a U.S. Marine guard
from the embassy in Nicosia was on the plane.
   The domestic British news agency Press Association reported that
the initial information about the bomb threat had come from the
Mossad, Israel's intelligence service.
</TEXT>
