<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArabLeague     12-22 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arab League,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maksoud Calls for Reopening PLO Office in Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League's representative urged the
Reagan administration on Thursday to reopen the Palestine Liberation
Organization's office in Washington and to condemn new Israeli
settlements on the West Bank as illegal.
   In a year-end meeting with reporters, Clovis Maksoud said it was
``illogical'' to keep the office closed now that the administration
had begun talks with the PLO.
   The State Department, citing involvement in terrorism by
``individuals and organizations associated with the PLO,'' had the
PLO's Washington information office shuttered last December. A
subsequent U.S. move to also close the PLO mission to the United
Nations in New York was reversed in federal court.
   Last week, Secretary of State George P. Shultz concluded chairman
Yasser Arafat had renounced terrorism. Shultz recommended the
opening of a ``substantive dialogue'' with the PLO. The first talk
was held last Friday in Tunisia.
   Maksoud said what the United States did about the PLO office and
Israeli settlements on the West Bank were the two ``litmus tests''
of American policy in the Middle East.
   He predicted President-elect Bush would be ``less ideological''
than President Reagan on the Arab-Israeli conflict and that James A.
Baker III, because of his closeness to Bush, could be the most
powerful secretary of state in history.
   However, Maksoud said he did not expect a reversal of the strong
U.S. support for Israel that characterized Reagan's two terms. The
Arab envoy said he hoped for ``a modification of American policy.''
   Looking to 1989, Maksoud said ``this is the year of challenge.
This is the year that we will see either reconciliation or
confrontation'' in the area.
   Maksoud said the opening of U.S. talks with the PLO was not a
``breakthrough'' and did not call for the ``euphoria'' expressed in
some Arab quarters.
   On the other hand, the Arab League official said, fears expressed
in Israel were ``contrived paranoia'' designed to undercut the U.S.
move.
   He said U.S. officials, meanwhile, were ``a little bit on the
defensive unecessarily'' in warning the PLO that the dialogue would
be suspended if terrorism recurs.
   Maksoud said the officials were acting ``as if they've done
something wrong, but necessary.''
   The Arab envoy began with a statement of ``deep sorrow and
regret'' that a Pan American World Airways jumbo jet had crashed in
Scotland on Wednesday, killing at least 279 people.
   An anonymous caller to The Associated Press office in London on
Thursday claimed responsibility for the crash and said it was in
retaliation for the downing of an Iranian airliner by the U.S. Navy
in July and for keeping the family of the late shah of Iran in the
United States.
   Maksoud said if the crash was not the result of malfunction ``it
has to be condemned without qualification.''
   On another subject, the Arab League representative questioned
U.S. statements that Libya was on the verge of full-scale production
of chemical weapons and that Reagan had not ruled out taking
military action.
   Maksoud said it was ``not true'' that Libya was producing
chemical weapons.
   ``This atmosphere of creating a focus on Libya as a scaepgoat may
be an attempt, directly or indirectly, by the Israelis to shift from
the central challenge of the peace offensive that the PLO and the
Arabs are undertaking,'' Maksoud said.
   He said the U.S. accusation that Libya was on the verge of
full-scale production ``might give a prior pretext for those who
want to strike at an Arab country in order to prevent the maturing
of the moderating developments that are taking place in the Arab
world as a result primarily of the Arab-PLO dialogue.''
</TEXT>
