<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TreeMemorial     12-22 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tree Memorial,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ohio Woman Wants To Save Vietnam Tree Memorial In Minnesota</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman has launched a drive to save a
Minnesota man's dream of planting a tree for each of the 58,000
Americans killed and missing in the Vietnam War.
   ``We can't allow what Vietnam veterans are trying to do to be
destroyed,'' said Terry Thompson of Geoffrey Steiner's Veterans
National Living Memorial. ``Geof's forest is a symbol.''
   Thompson, who is not a veteran, started the drive to save the
100-acre memorial after she read that the land will be sold at a
foreclosure sale Jan. 4 unless about $400 in back taxes and the
$5,400 balance on a bank loan are paid off.
   Steiner, a 39-year-old Vietnam veteran, has spent eight years
planting about 35,000 trees on the land in Cushing, about 100 miles
northwest of St. Paul. Last year, Newsweek magazine cited him as one
of 50 American heros.
   Steiner said he paid $23,000 in cash for the land in 1980 after
selling his home in Minneapolis. In 1984, he used the property to
secure an $8,000 bank loan.
   Thompson, a resident of Dayton, Ohio, brought up the issue at her
local chapter of the Vietnam Veterans of America, where she works as
a volunteer legislative coordinator.
   The group not only voted to donate $500 but also authorized
Thompson to send letters to 400 other chapters representing about
35,000 members.
   ``We don't have that much time,'' Thompson said Wednesday. She
said she's motivated by the belief that the forest will be good for
Vietnam veterans.
   ``The Vietnam War was a different kind of war that involved a
type of fighting that so psychologically affected the vets,'' she
said. ``These guys have to be brought out of their shells.''
   Steiner, a Marine who served in Vietnam in 1967-68 and was
wounded during the Tet offensive, said he ``felt fantastic'' when
Thompson told him about her campaign to save the forest. ``I was
ready to give up totally,'' he said.
   He said those affected by the war say they are thankful for
Washington's Vietnam Memorial but like his forest idea because it is
a living memorial.
   ``POWs can come home and walk through the forest with their
families and say somebody cared enough to plant these trees in their
honor,'' Steiner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
