<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Spain-Lottery 1stLd-Writethru   12-22 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Lottery, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0642,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christmas Comes Early For Just A Lucky Few Thousand</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `The $10.5 ...' to CORRECT third prize figure
to $37.9 million; PICKS up 12th graf: ``These army...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers, civilians, secret agents and
soccer players all split an eye-popping $734 million pot Thursday in
the world's richest lottery, making Christmas much merrier for
thousands of Spaniards.
   Millions nationwide bought tickets or shares of tickets in the
wildly anticipated Yuletide drawing. The total pot _ 83 billion
pesetas _ made it the richest since King Carlos III established
Spain's first lottery in 1763.
   A ball bearing the winning first-prize number rolled out of a
chute Thursday morning while the nation tuned into television and
radios for the drawing.
   A crowd inside a Madrid auditorium roared as two boys from an
orphanage sang out the number for the $159 million first prize _
popularly called ``El Gordo,'' or ``the fat one.''
   To cope with demand this year, the state-run lottery issued 72
tickets for each of the 66,000 lottery numbers. So each ticket
holder with the winning first-place number _ 21,583 _ stands to
receive $2.2 million.
   But tickets were $219 each, and many Spaniards purchased shares
ranging as low as 87 cents, spreading the tax-free winnings around.
   The first prize was spread widely among hundreds of people who
bought tickets in Barcelona, Madrid, Lugo, Gijon and other towns
throughout Spain.
   The second prize paid $1 million to each of the 72 tickets
bearing the number 32,694. Half of those tickets were bought by
members and friends of the Avance soccer club in Alcala de Henares,
just east of the Spanish capital.
   The other half was spread among thousands of other residents of
the same town, including dozens of paratroopers and soldiers
stationed there.
   ``We're all (peseta) millionaires here,'' one smiling Alcala
paratrooper told Spanish Television as he jumped up and down.
   The $37.9 million third prize went to members of an army division
that once tried to overthrow the government.
   ``These army guys can really smell out money,'' said Gen. Juan
Anton of the Maestrazgo infantry division in eastern Valencia.
   The Maestrazgo division took an active part in a an abortive coup
attempt against the Spanish government staged by paramilitary Civil
Guards on Feb. 23, 1981.
   Each of the 72 third-prize tickets is worth get $526,315.
   At the Maestrazgo division, 116 military police, 17 intelligence
officers, 40 officers and unit chiefs and numerous soldiers shared
$10.5 million, while soldiers and civilians at the armed forces'
regional headquarters in Valencia shared another $8.4 million.
   The total value of all tickets sold was $1.5 billion, with 30
percent of that going directly into government coffers.
</TEXT>
