<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-Libya 3rdLd-Writethru a0677 12-22 0915</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Libya, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0677,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Won't Rule Out Force Against Chemical Arms Plant</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with Libya denial after 11th graf, ``Reagan
said;'' CORRECTS number of killed and injured in 25th graf, ``U.S.
warplanes''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration is ``extremely concerned''
about Libya's chemical weapons factory and hasn't ruled out using
military force against it, President Reagan's spokesman said
Thursday.
   ``The president was quite clear that military action is an
option. We're not ruling it out,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said in answer to reporters' questions about a comment
Reagan made in a television interview.
   The United States ``is extremely concerned about production
facilities in Libya ... which we believe can produce enormous
quantities of chemical weapons,'' Fitzwater said.
   Asked if a U.S. strike against the facility is under
consideration, the spokesman said, ``I'm not saying it's our
intention. ... We will not rule out options.''
   Reagan, in an interview taped for broadcast Thursday evening on
ABC-TV, said military action against the site has been discussed by
the United States and its allies.
   ``Well, let me say that's a decision that has not been made
yet,'' Reagan said in the interview, portions of which were
broadcast on ABC's ``World News Tonight'' Wednesday.
   `` We're in communication with our allies and with NATO forces
and all, and we're watching very closely that situation but even if
I had made a decision, I couldn't ....''
   David Brinkley, who conducted the interview, then broke in to
say: ``You wouldn't want to tell it now.''
   ``No,'' Reagan responded.
   Asked whether military action had been discussed with the allies,
the president said, ``We are discussing with them, and we want to
pin down completely so that there is no question, but that that's
what it is ... a plant that he is building and one of tremendous
size.''
   Reagan said the United States knows where the factory is, but he
did not disclose the site.
   Meantime Thursday, Libya reiterated its denial that the facility
is a chemical weapons plant and declared its ``full commitment to
all international conventions'' on such arms, the official news
agency JANA reported.
   It said that the Reagan administration's aim was to blunt the
development of Arab societies and ``to this end it will market all
the excuses it can find to mislead and trick world public opinion.''
Libya contends the plant produces pharaceuticals.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that the
United States believes the plant ``can produce enormous quantities
of chemical weapons.''
   Answering questions Thursday after announcing Cabinet
nominations, President-elect Bush said his administration also would
be committed to seeing that Libya does not develop a chemical
warfare capability.
   Bush said he hoped U.S. allies or other countries in the Middle
East could help stop development of chemical weapons, but ``very few
of them have any influence whatsoever over Mr. Gadhafi (Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi).''
   He added: ``This is is a matter of real concern to us, and yes,
we all ought to be committed to seeing that that plant not be
committed to spread further destruction.''
   Clovis Maksoud, the Arab League's representative here, said it
was ``not true'' that Libya was producing chemical weapons.
   ``This atmosphere of creating a focus on Libya as a scaepgoat may
be an attempt, directly or indirectly, by the Israelis to shift from
the central challenge of the peace offensive that the PLO (Palestine
Liberation Organization) and the Arabs are undertaking,'' Maksoud
told reporters.
   He said the U.S. accusation ``might give a prior pretext for
those who want to strike at an Arab country in order to prevent the
maturing of the moderating developments that are taking place in the
Arab world as a result primarily of the Arab-PLO dialogue.''
   The Washington Post has quoted intelligence sources as saying the
factory is in a large complex 35 miles southwest of Tripoli. The
complex reportedly includes a plant intended to produce aerial bombs
and canisters to carry poisonous gas. The sources also said it is
guarded by Soviet-made missiles.
   A senior administration official told the Post that military
action was one of several options that had been discussed, but it
``is not under active consideration.''
   More than 100 countries will represented in Paris on Jan. 7-11 to
discuss enforcement of the 1925 Geneva Convention outlawing poison
gas and other chemical weapons. Secretary of State George Shultz
will represent the United States at the conference, which was
proposed by Reagan.
   Fitzwater said he did not know whether the option of military
force against the site will be raised at the conference, but he said
the complex ``is representative of the kind of problems'' that will
be dealt with at the meeting.
   U.S. warplanes bombed Libya in 1986 in retaliation for the
terrorist attack on a West Berlin disco where two U.S. servicemen
and a Turkish woman were killed and more than 200 soldiers and
others were injured.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the
United States has been consulting for several months with its allies
in an effort to withhold from Libya the technology needed to make
the chemical weapons plant operational.
   She said Japan, West Germany and other governments had been asked
not to give Libya any help.
   Japan has assured the United States that it has stopped work on a
metallurgical plant in Libya that had been linked to the chemical
weapons plant, she said, and ``we believe they have stopped.''
</TEXT>
