<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1928EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Apparel-Homework     12-22 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apparel-Homework,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Department May Lift Final Ban on Apparel Work at Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With President-elect Bush's apparent support,
the Labor Department is looking at lifting the last of its
prohibitions against industrial homework in the garment industry,
officials said Thursday.
   The department last month _ two days after Bush's election _
announced it was lifting bans on work in the home in five apparel
fields effective Jan. 8. The move potentially would cover an
estimated 50,000 to 75,000 workers.
   But in what became a major showdown within the Reagan
administration between Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin on the one
hand and officials in Bush's office and the White House budget
office on the other, the department continued the ban in the women's
apparel industry for the time being.
   The last week of October, according to Labor Department
officials, Mrs. McLaughlin received a letter from Bush saying, ``I
look forward to the next step,'' referring to women's apparel.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said in an interview Thursday she told Budget
Director Joseph Wright on Tuesday she intends to issue a notice of
proposed rulemaking and schedule hearings in February on the women's
apparel ban before leaving office next month.
   ``My intention all along was to go with a two-tier approach,''
she said. ``Because women's apparel was more controversial, the idea
was to do more of a negotiated rulemaking there after getting six or
eight months experience with the others.''
   The bans on garment industry homework were imposed 47 years ago
to combat widespread exploitation of immigrants and other low-wage
workers. Getting rid of the prohibitions has been a priority of
Reagan and Bush's vice presidential task force on deregulation for
nearly eight years.
   The administration succeeded in 1984 in removing the ban on
knitted outerwear, but unions effectively blocked the lifting of the
prohibitions in the six other fields through the courts.
   However, two days after the election, the Labor Department
published new regulations effectively allowing homework on gloves
and mittens, embroideries, buttons and buckles, handkerchiefs and
some jewelry. That left only women's apparel still entirely under
the prohibitions after Jan. 8.
   The International Ladies Garment Workers Union, which represents
about 170,000 of the estimated 500,000 workers in women's apparel,
said Wednesday it will file suit next week to block the Jan. 8
regulations.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said she had hoped to ``negotiate'' a rulemaking
between ILGWU President Jay Mazur and industry officials to also
remove the ban on women's apparel homework.
   However, other officials _ including Bush's counsel, C. Boyden
Gray, and former White House Budget Director James A. Miller III _
wanted apparel homework included in the proposal last month,
according to several sources.
   Gray did not return a telephone call seeking comment Thursday.
   Allan McMillan, a deputy assistant labor secretary in charge of
enforcing the homework regulations, said the department was still
looking at several options that could stretch out the time before
the ban is removed on women's apparel.
   ``Clearly, the demographics show that worker flexibility is
something we need to achieve,'' he said. ``The question is how we
balance that with effective enforcement (of federal labor
standards). It's my hope we will be able to conclude this process
fairly quickly.''
   Susan Cowell, a vice presdent of the Ladies Garment Workers, said
the union had anticipated a renewed attempt to remove the homework
ban in women's apparel.
   ``The sense we had always gotten was that Bush was very much a
part of this initiative,'' she said. ``Without a ban, there is no
hope of enforcing the Fair Labor Standards Act in this industry.''
   What makes enforcment difficult and violations of minimun wage
and other labor standards common, she said, is the mobile nature of
the industry and its domination by tens of thousands of small
contractors typically employing between 10 and 50 workers each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1956EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbandonedFamily     12-22 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abandoned Family,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Wander From House to House After Abandonment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six youngsters who scrounged for two weeks
for a place to live after being abandoned by a drug addict mother
have been split up among foster homes and friends, according to
authorities, who want to reunite them.
   ``Anytime we can help a family, we certainly will go the extra
yard to try to do that,'' said Norman Reim, a spokesman for the
state Division of Youth and Family Services. ``The goal is to get
them in a permanent home.''
   The six _ four children ages 11 to 16, two with children of their
own _ told police they wandered for a place to live after their
37-year-old mother left them.
   ``They was going from building to building, door to door,'' said
32-year-old Gabriel Rosa, the oldest daughter's boyfriend and father
of her 2-month-old son, who took the family into his one-bedroom
apartment. ``That's a shame.''
   The Camden Housing Authority had threatened to evict Rosa because
the youngsters were unauthorized to live in the apartment, he said.
   Not knowing what to do, the children called police.
   Detectives took the children to police headquarters. After
meeting Tuesday with a social worker, the family was separated.
   ``It's bad for kids to be without a home and struggling from
house to house,'' said Reim, who declined to comment specifically
about the case. ``Certainly, in this business, we've seen it all.''
   Thirteen-year-old Cassandra Wilson and her brother, James Wilson,
11, were placed in foster homes. Rosa's girlfriend, Joanne Victor,
16, and their son moved in with him. Patricia Wilson and her
7-week-old son moved in with friends at the housing project.
   Police searched for the family's mother, Sandra Wilson. The
children said their troubles began about two years ago when their
mother started smoking cocaine.
   Although the family's house was heavily damaged in a June fire,
the family continued to live there, using candles and kerosene
heaters. But after the gas was shut off for non-payment in November,
the youngsters moved out.
   They said their mother left them at the end of November, taking
her welfare check. Three days later, they said, she came back and
took $405 in cash from the family and left again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
