<DOCNO> AP881222-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1804EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AirForceCrash     12-22 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Force Crash,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Jet Crashes, Pilot Ejects Safely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Air Force pilot ejected safely from
his A-10 attack jet Thursday, just moments before it crashed into a
field, officials said.
   The pilot, Lt. Frank Cavouti of Garden City, N.Y., was ending a
training mission and approaching for a landing at the Royal Air
Force base in Alconbury, when the crash occurred, said an Air Force
spokesman.
   It was the second crash of a twin-engine Thunderbolt jet in
Europe in two weeks. A third A-10 crashed on Dec. 8 in Tracy, Ariz.
   Cavouti was being held for observation at a military hospital.
His jet crashed several miles west of this central English village
and about 60 miles north of London, said the spokesman, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Witnesses said it appeared the pilot was trying to miss this
village and hit the open field.
   Tony Woolsenhomes, 53, of the nearby village of Earith, said he
watched Cavouti's jet circle for about 30 minutes and ``knew it was
in trouble. It seemed to me he was circling to look for somewhere
away from the village to put the plane down.''
   The spokesman said a board of officers would investigate the
incident.
   He said Cavouti was assigned to the 10th Tactical Fighter Wing at
Alconbury. The aircraft was carrying ``dummy bombs and practice 33mm
ammunition,'' he added.
   The A-10, a jet designed to support troops by hitting enemy tanks
and other ground targets, is an older model plane designed to be
highly maneuverable at low speeds and low altitude and to carry a
lot of bombs and ammunition.
   Thursday's crash came two weeks after an A-10 slammed into the
West German city of Remscheid, killing five and injuring dozens.
   The Remscheid crash prompted the United States and its NATO
allies to agree to suspend all A-10 flights over West Germany until
Jan. 2. The suspension was ordered as West German political parties
and public interest groups increased their demands for an end to
low-level flight training in West Germany.
   On the same day as the Remscheid crash, an A-10 crashed near the
heart of the Tohono O'Odham Indian Reservation, about 80 miles west
of Tuscon. The pilot ejected safely.
   The Thunderbolt first flew in 1975 and became operational with
the Air Force in 1977. The plane is no longer in production, but the
Air Force has more than 700 of them in its inventory.
   Statistically, the A-10 over time has been the safest fighter or
attack plane now in the inventory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
