<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1959EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-SovietComedy     12-22 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Comedy,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Movie To Look At Capitalist's Venture In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOODBRIDGE, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two screenwriters _ one American, one
Soviet _ are betting that capitalists and communists alike can find
humor in a comedy about a U.S. businessman's efforts to open a chain
of fried chicken restaurants near Moscow.
   Jeremy Leven of Woodbridge and Valentin Chernyck have been
struggling for four weeks to overcome differences in language and
culture and create the first draft of the script to ``No Money Down
in Zagorsk.''
   Chernyck and director Alexander Pankratov, who joined the
screenwriters and their translator two weeks ago, and from Mosfilm,
the largest of 17 film studios in the Soviet Union.
   The film will tell the story of a near-bankrupt capitalist, Peter
Washington, who is induced by the Soviets to go to a village north
of Moscow to open a chain of restaurants called Chicken Heaven.
   ``It's 100 percent a comedy, but it deals with what really would
happen if an American capitalist came over to a Soviet village that
was struggling financially and was under the gun to become
profitable,'' Leven said. ``There are problems and we don't hide
them _ bad materials, materials they can't get.
   ``In the end, capitalism absolutely blows up in his
(Washington's) face,'' Leven said. Filming will begin by July, he
said.
   Chernyck won an Academy Award in 1980 for ``Moscow Does Not
Believe In Tears,'' which was voted best foreign language film.
Leven wrote the screenplay for the movie ``Creator'' and the book on
which it was based.
   Leven said outside investors will put up at least $5 million,
while the Soviets will put up at least an equivalent sum. Leven said
he has not yet lined up a major studio to distribute the film in the
United States.
   ``It should be a very extraordinary film because we want it to
play in both countries simultaneously, without changes,'' said Leven.
   Soviet studios have recently gained greater independence but
remain dependent on government financing of production and
distribution, said Vladimir Padunov, a professor at Wheaton College
in Norton, Mass., and an authority on the Soviet film industry.
   Chernyck said one difficulty in writing the screenplay was a
different in approaches to humor. ``Our jokes and humor are not so
fast as American humor. When Jeremy told us a joke, we would start
laughing after five minutes,'' he said.
   The film will be in both English and Russian, with no dubbing or
subtitles, but characters will usually speak no more than a sentence
or two, so that viewers can figure out the meaning. Much of the
humor will be visual, Leven said.
   In one scene, Leven said, the American and a Soviet counterpart
become covered in mud and are ushered into a tiny bathroom to
undress. The two are left standing naked, face-to-face.
   The Soviet, Igor, looks at Peter and shrugs to show he is
unimpressed, then says: ``America.''
   Peter looks back and shrugs, to show he, too, is unimpressed, and
says: ``Russia.''
   Igor then says in Russian, ``No big deal.''
   Peter nods back, ``No big deal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
