<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmileOrder     12-22 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smile Order,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Tells Officers to Smile More</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year, the deputy police chief
ordered his officers to stop telling people to have nice day.
   Now he wants them to shed their ``Dragnet'' image and put on a
happy face.
   In his New Year's message to the 39-member department, Richard
Mears said a smile ``makes people feel good, and it may even
preclude an attack of ulcers.'' A smile also can defuse a hostile
situation and comfort the distressed, he said.
   Last year's message urged officers to clean up their language and
advised them to can ``Have a nice day'' farewells, especially when
handing out tickets.
   Mears admitted he has mellowed over the years from his
``just-the-facts-ma'am'' approach to law enforcement.
   He cautioned officers, however, not to smile at inappropriate
times _ such as when ``you arrest someone you know is going to jail
for a hundred years.''
   ``Smile when irate citizens are screaming in your face, but don't
smile when seconds later you're winding the cuffs to them,'' Mears
advised.
</TEXT>
