<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1825EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Threat-Precedent     12-22 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Threat-Precedent,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am Bomb Warning Recalls Similar Incident in 1986</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disclosure that a caller had warned that
someone would unwittingly carry a bomb aboard a Pan Am flight from
Frankfurt to New York recalled a similar incident involving an
Israeli airliner in 1986.
   Jordanian-born Nezar Hindawi was condemned on Oct. 24, 1986, to a
45-year sentence for handing booby-trapped hand baggage to his
pregnant Irish girlfriend as she prepared to board the flight on
April 17 that year.
   An El Al guard found the bomb as the woman, Ann-Marie Murphy,
passed through security. British officials said the bomb consisted
of three pounds of Czechoslovakian-made plastic explosive hidden
behind a luggage panel and likely would have killed all 375
passengers aboard the EL Al Boeing 747. Murphy told officials she
had no knowledge of the bomb, and she was not charged.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Thursday that on
Dec. 5 an anonymous caller told the U.S. Embassy in Finland that a
Pan Am flight would be bombed.
   She said ``an unidentified person in Helsinki would unwittingly
take the device to Frankfurt and eventually onto the U.S.-bound
flight.''
   However, the department's top counterterrorism official said in a
television interview that it was still not clear whether Pan Am
flight 103 had fallen victim to terrorism, and that authorities
frequently received detailed threats that turned out to be false.
   ``In fact, ever since this method was tried and thwarted on an El
Al plane in London two years ago, we've had a number of times people
come to us saying that someone in an unsuspecting way is going to
carry a bomb on a plane. So it's not unusual to have that kind of
specificity in a threat,'' L. Paul Bremer told Cable News Network.
   Mrs. Oakley said the caller told embassy officials that the
individuals who would provide the device would have ties to Abu
Nidal, leader of a radical Palestinian faction.
   Another source said the caller claimed the bomb would be carried
by a woman.
   The Finnish Foreign Ministry said in a statement Thursday that an
Arab resident had made several bomb threats during the year, most
recently on Dec. 5, but that ``in the investigation so far, no
direct connection has been found between the Arab living in Finland
and the air accident in question.''
   The statement said authorities knew the caller's identity and
that he had not left Finland since Dec. 5.
   The sentence handed down in the El Al case in 1986 was the
longest ever in a British court.
   During the trial, the prosecution presented evidence that Hindawi
entered Britain in late January 1986 on a Syrian diplomatic passport
with a false name, and that his visa applications had been endorsed
by Syrian foreign ministry officials.
   The prosecution presented evidence that Hindawi, then 32, was
acting in concert with Syria for a group called the Jordan
Revolutionary Movement. He allegely received help from the chief of
Syrian Air Force intelligence, Gen. Mohammed Khouli, an aide to
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Murphy testified during the trial, breaking into tears and
accusing the defendant of intending to kill her and their unborn
child. The baby, a girl, was born in July.
   After the bomb was discovered, Hindawi fled to the Syrian
Embassy, where prosecutors said he met with Syrian Ambassador Loutof
Haydar. Hindawi then was taken to a Syrian safe house in London,
where Syrian Embassy employees cut and dyed his hair. However, he
fled in fear and turned himself in to police.
   The incident prompted Britain to sever diplomatic ties with Syria
and other members of the European Common Market to impose trade and
diplomatic sanctions against that nation in October 1986. The
measures were lifted the following July after Western officials
concluded that Syria had curtailed its support for terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1826EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0665 12-22 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Says Plenum Remarks May Be `Signal' to Solidarity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with parliament considering
economic reforms, Solidarity adviser praising party shake-up. PICKS
UP graf 5 pvs, ``In the ...'' Edits thereafter to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa expressed satisfaction Thursday
with Communist Party statements on apparent willingness to change
the labor union system, but said he wants Solidarity legalized
before talking with officials.
   ``It is a signal (from the party), but we are saying once again
that without Solidarity, without relegalizing Solidarity, there is
no possibility of agreement,'' Walesa told The Associated Press from
his home in Gdansk.
   At a meeting Wednesday of the party Central Committee, Polish
leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski replaced six hard-line Politburo
members with seven younger pragmatists and prominent party liberal
Stanislaw Ciosek.
   Solidarity adviser Andrzej Stelmachowski said, ``As a first step
it was a very positive one because the group of hard-liners seems to
be far weaker now than before. Therefore the climate for further
steps ... is far better.''
   In another effort to accelerate reforms, parliament Thursday
considered a package of bills that would change the Polish economy
dramatically.
   If passed, the bills will allow anyone to start a private
business, liberalize foreign investment in Poland, reform banking
and permit free exchange of zlotys for foreign currency.
   Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula introduced the package as
the basis ``for freedom, equality and competition in the economy.''
   ``The duty of the socialist state is to assure people equal
opportunity. ... Further possibilities should depend on their
individual achievements. This is the only way one should understand
justice,'' he said.
   At the party meeting Wednesday, Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F.
Rakowski praised Walesa's recent statements and said he judged the
Solidarity leader a reliable and moderate partner for talks.
   In the clearest signal that the party may lift its seven-year ban
of the independent trade union, Rakowski told the committee to poll
local party members on Walesa and Solidarity, which was crushed by a
1981 military crackdown and outlawed the following year.
   Rakowski told them to return their answers at the 230-member
body's next session, in mid-January. ``Your answer ... will decide
about what we will do. And what we do will decide the future of
socialism in Poland,'' he said.
   However, he also asked the opposition to come to the negotiating
table without conditions.
   ``We are saying clearly that we desire together with the OPZZ
(official unions) and moderate leaders of former Solidarity to
discuss the future _ different from the present _ model of the trade
union movement.''
   Walesa said it was ``a pretty far-reaching statement and we hope
that we are thinking about the same thing. To see whether this is
so, we still have to conduct direct talks. ... We want it formulated
in a clearer manner.''
   He warned the party should ``remember that the working people are
at the limits of their endurance. Just listen to what people are
saying in the shops. What's in store for us is dangerous if we don't
solve the most significant problems.''
   Walesa said a chicken costs $6 while some people earn only $54 a
month, so ``it is a drama.''
   ``If nothing is done by spring, then we won't be able to do
anything at all,'' he said. ``The people have had enough.''
   The opposition movement has united behind Walesa's call for
legalizing Solidarity before it will take part in proposed talks on
economic reforms and greater democracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
