<DOCNO> AP881222-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1835EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Palestinians-Deport     12-22 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palestinians-Deport,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Strikes Down Portion of McCarran-Walter Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Thursday struck down
portions of a 1952 law allowing the government to deport aliens for
espousing anti-American beliefs, saying the provisions violate
immigrants' free-speech rights.
   U.S. District Judge Stephen V. Wilson also threw out an exception
to a 1987 law that recognized free speech rights for all immigrants
in deportation proceedings but members of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   Wilson said Congress already has passed a powerful array of laws
dealing with terrorism and his decision would not ``significantly
deplete the government's arsenal in combating terrorism.''
   The ruling came in a two-year-old case involving seven Jordanians
and a Kenyan who were arrested, held without bail and subjected to
deportation proceedings under the McCarran-Walter Act. A federal
immigration judge released them and the government eventually
dropped McCarran-Walter proceedings against all but two, although it
sought deportation of the others on technical grounds.
   A government attorney said Wilson's ruling would be appealed.
   Wilson on struck down sections of the 1952 McCarran-Walter Act
providing for deportation of an alien who advocates _ or is
affiliated with a group that espouses _ world communism,
dictatorship or unlawful destruction of property.
   ``The ideological provisions of the McCarran-Walter Act do not
withstand First Amendment analysis,'' he said.
   He said the McCarthy-era statute was ``overbroad'' and could
cause deportation for something as simple as wearing a political
button.
   He cited the landmark 1969 decision in Brandenburg vs. Ohio, in
which the U.S. Supreme Court held that the government can only
prohibit speech directed toward inciting imminent lawless action.
   The judge also ruled that the PLO exception to the 1987 Foreign
Relations Authorization Act violated guarantees of due process and
equal protection under the law.
   ``In this case, the government is trying to stifle certain ideas
from entering our society from certain aliens,'' the judge said.
``Our society, however, was built on the premise that only through
the free flow of ideas can our nation grow and prosper.''
   The Arab-American Anti-Discrimination committee had sued the
Justice Department on behalf of the immigrants, and the battle was
joined by the American Civil Liberties Union and the Center for
Constitutional Rights, based in New York.
   One of the original defendants, Khader Hamide, 34, called the
decision a victory for Arab and Palestinian immigrants.
   ``We feel as a community now we can speak our minds on the
Palestinian issue,'' Hamide said. ``We can speak our minds on the
uprising on the West Bank and in Gaza and express our opinions
freely without the fear of being put in jail.''
   David Cole of the Center for Constitutional Rights said the
judge's ruling on the PLO exception to the 1987 law means that
``Congress cannot make politically motivated distinctions in
providing First Amendment rights to aliens.''
   Paul Hoffman, of the ACLU, noting the government's decision to
appeal, said the case would most likely be decided by the U.S.
Supreme Court.
   ``When it is decided, I think it will be one of the handful of
major First Amendent cases that have ever come down in this
country's history,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KinseyInstitute     12-22 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kinsey Institute,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University Asks Kinsey Institute Director To Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana University has asked the
director of the Kinsey Institute, an internationally known sex
research center, to resign, the institute confirmed Thursday.
   The university requested June Reinisch's resignation in a letter
written Monday by Morton Lowengrub, dean of the College of Arts and
Sciences. Lowengrub cited concerns about the quality of research
during Reinisch's six years as director and about her management
ability.
   Reinisch said Wednesday that opponents ``have yet to come up with
one stitch of evidence to support any of their claims.''
   The institute, which was founded in 1947 by Alfred C. Kinsey, is
affiliated with and financed largely by Indiana University but is a
separately incorporated entity. University officials do not have the
authority to fire Reinisch, who reports to a 10-member institute
board.
   Lowengrub said in his letter that university officials, including
President Thomas Ehrlich, were convinced that the institute ``has
not satisfied the university's reasonable expectations with regard
to the quality of its research'' under Reinisch's leadership.
   He said the opinion was based on a review committee's study.
   Lowengrub could not be reached by telephone Thursday, and a
spokeswoman said the dean would have no comment on the Kinsey
situation.
   Five university faculty, including Lowengrub, sit on the Kinsey
board, which met Wednesday. The board issued a statement Thursday
saying it was studying the review committee report and would not
comment until it was done.
   Some board members, however, strongly supported Reinisch.
   ``I think she's doing an excellent job,'' said Kinsey trustee
Sherry Hackett, president of The Ultimate Experience Inc. of Beverly
Hills, Calif.
   Mrs. Hackett blamed the attacks on Reinisch, 45, on sex
discrimination, jealousy and ``pardon me, stupidity.''
   David Hendin, another trustee and vice president of United
Features Syndicate, which distributes Reinisch's ``The Kinsey
Report'' column, also supported Reinisch and said the criticisms
would not have surfaced had she been male.
   Eugene Eoyang, also a trustee and a professor of East Asian
languages, said in a written response to the review committee's
report that it was biased, incomplete and flawed by poor review
techniques.
   ``If June Reinisch has not spent as much time as she should have
on her research, it's because she has been promoting the institute
indefatigably in other ways,'' Eoyang wrote.
   The review committee's report said the institute was in crisis.
   ``Over the last five years, relatively little has resulted from
its endeavors, the research library and collections have continued
to deteriorate, the institute has become progressively more isolated
from the Indiana University faculty, and it has been beset by nearly
continuous personnel problems,'' the report said.
   Reinisch, a tenured professor in the university's psychology
department, said she would not comment further until the institute's
trustees finished their review of the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
