<DOCNO> AP881222-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2011EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-HumanRights     12-22 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Human Rights,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Asks Bush to Raise South Africa at Economic Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush was asked by a U.S. human
rights organization Thursday to give priority to ending apartheid in
South Africa when he attends his first economic summit of Western
leaders.
   The New York-based Lawyers Committee for Human Rights urged the
new Bush administration to undertake ``a major diplomatic effort ...
in support of comprehensive multilateral sanctions against South
Africa.''
   It said this should be at the top of Bush's agenda at the annual
Western summit of the seven richest democracies in Paris next
spring. The other countries are France, Britain, Japan, West
Germany, Canada and Italy.
   Tougher sanctions against white-ruled South Africa were among the
main recommendations in a report advocating that the United States
take advantage of what it called ``historic opportunities (for) ...
innovative foreign policy initiatives to advance the cause of
international human rights.''
   The 54-page report has been delivered to the Bush transition
group in Washington, said the Lawyers Committee, a public interest
law center working to promote international human rights and
protection of refugees. It is headed by former federal Judge Marvin
E. Frankel.
   Other recommendations:
   _Continued linkage between U.S. trade concessions and the right
of people to leave the Soviet Union, with consideration for a
one-year grant of such concessions if the emigration rate continues
to rise and Soviet exit procedures are relaxed.
   _A ban on the use of U.S. anti-terrorism aid funds for training
foreign police against insurgent forces.
   _Support of legislation narrowing the grounds for exclusion or
deportation of immigrants or U.S. visitors on the basis of beliefs,
affiliations or activities protected by the constitution for
American citizens.
   _Liberalized standards for U.S. political asylum.
   _Requiring the Soviet Union to end screening of foreign
journalists' reporting and to guarantee access to non-government and
private groups before U.S. agreement to a Soviet-proposed 1991
humanitarian conference in Moscow.
   _U.S. support for the creation of human rights departments in the
multilateral development banks.
   _Creation of a new senior position of undersecretary of state for
human rights.
</TEXT>
