<HEAD>John Paul Receptive to Meeting with PLO Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II is receptive to a meeting
with Yasser Arafat if it can be arranged when the PLO chairman
visits Rome on Friday, Vatican sources said.
   There has been no official confirmation of a Vatican audience,
but Italian news reports said Thursday the Palestine Liberation
Organization's Rome office had requested one.
   The Vatican sources, speaking privately, noted that John Paul
granted Arafat an audience in 1982 and Vatican officials met with a
ranking PLO official, Farouk Kaddoumi, last February.
   Israel and Jewish groups condemned the 1982 audience. In an
account of the meeting, the Vatican said the pope called for a
Palestinian homeland, respect for Israel's security and an end to
terrorism.
   Arafat is touring Europe seeking support for an international
Middle East peace conference and the independent Palestinian state
proclaimed Nov. 15.
   In Yugoslavia, which Arafat visited Wednesday, the official news
agency Tanjug said Thursday the ``state of Palestine'' would
establish an embassy in Belgrade. It is believed the PLO mission in
Belgrade will be elevated to embassy level with an ambassador in
charge.
   Italian officials have said Arafat will meet with Premier Ciriaco
De Mita and Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti on Friday.
   Italy is the first NATO member on Arafat's European itinerary. He
conferred with Andreotti during a stopover in Rome on Nov. 2.
</TEXT>
