<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Steele,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film, TV Star of `F Troop' Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Steele, who appeared in more than 150
motion pictures but may best be remembered as the pint-sized Trooper
Duffy on the ``F Troop'' TV series, died Thursday of heart failure.
He was 82.
   Steele died at St. Joseph Medical Center, said hospital
spokeswoman Gail Foy.
   Born Robert North Bradbury Jr. in Pendleton, Ore., on Jan. 23,
1906, Steele began his screen career at age 14 with his twin
brother, Bill, in ``The Adventures of Bob and Bill,'' a series of
short documentaries.
   Steele went on to appear in more than 150 films, including silent
movies.
   The list includes ``Davy Crockett at the Fall of the Alamo,''
1926; ``The Cowboy and the Outlaw,'' 1929; ``Doomed at Sundown,''
1937; ``Of Mice and Men,'' 1940; ``The Great Train Robbery,'' 1941;
``Rio Bravo,'' 1959; ``Requiem for a Gunfighter,'' 1965; ``Hang 'Em
High,'' 1968; ``Rio Lobo,'' 1970; and ``Something Big,'' 1971.
   Steele is survived by his wife, Virginia.
   Ms. Foy said a cremation was planned.
</TEXT>
