<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     12-22 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Commission Meets In Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four-party Working Commission on Cambodia met
Thursday to discuss withdrawal of Vietnamese troops, the crux of a
five-point plan proposed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, unofficial
leader of the rebel movement.
   In Bangkok, Thailand, guerrilla leaders and officials of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations ended a two-day meeting to
prepare for peace talks with Vietnam. Thailand, Indonesia, the
Philippines, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei are members of the
regional organization.
   Li Zhaoxing, a spokesman for China's Foreign Ministry, said in
Beijing ``it is imperative for Vietnam to show its sincerity,'' by
pulling out, and repeated China's demand for international
supervision of the withdrawal.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978 and has said it will
remove all occupation forces by 1990. It claims to have taken out
50,000 soldiers this year, which it says is half the total, but
China and other nations say most of the withdrawals were merely
troop rotations.
   The Working Commission was formed last month to seek a political
solution. It includes representatives of the government Vietnam
installed in Phnom Penh, the capital; the Khmer Rouge, whose
government the invaders overthrew, and guerrilla groups led by
Sihanouk, Cambodia's former ruler, and by Son Sann.
   Cambodian government delegate Hor Nam Hong demanded at the
Thursday meeting that Sihanouk's plan include an end to guerrilla
activity, an idea opposed by the Khmer Rouge and the other two rebel
groups. The plan now provides for a withdrawal timetable accompanied
by dismantling of the Vietnamese client government and the Khmer
Rouge exile regime.
   Sihanouk also has rejected Hong's proposal that subcommittees be
created to examine the plan in detail.
   The session ended after Hong withdrew to consult with his
government and no date was set for the next meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
