<DOCNO> AP881222-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Summit     12-22 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Summit,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Leaders Cement Persian Gulf Peace, Support Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Gulf Cooperation Council ended a
summit meeting Thursday, pledging to consolidate the Iran-Iraq peace
drive, safeguard freedom of navigation in the Persian Gulf and seek
an international conference on the Palestinian question.
   The six member nations endorsed Saudi-sponsored talks between the
Soviet Union and Afghan rebels amid speculation that oil giant Saudi
Arabia was moving toward resuming diplomatic ties with Moscow after
a 50-year break.
   Attending the four-day summit were King Fahd of Saudi Arabia,
Sultan Qaboos of Oman, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah of Kuwait,
Sheik Khalifa bin Hamad Al Thani of Qatar, Sheik Zayed bin Sultan Al
Nahyan of the United Arab Emirates and Sheik Isa bin Salman Al
Khalifa of Bahrain.
   They stressed their resolve to strengthen collective defense
capabilities and boosted economic integration plans with a ``Manama
Declaration'' calling for speeded-up efforts toward a gulf common
market.
   In a closing communique read by council Secretary-General
Abdullah Bishara of Kuwait, the group said it backed efforts by U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to promote a peace treaty
between Iran and Iraq to formally end their 8-year-old war. Iran and
Iraq agreed to a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in August.
   The summit appealed for world support for an international
conference on the Palestinian question to pave the way for a lasting
Arab-Israeli peace and an independent Palestinian state. It said the
Palestine Liberation Organization must take part in such a
conference.
   The Gulf Cooperation Council was formed mainly as an economic
alliance eight months after the gulf war broke out in September
1980. But the conflict prompted efforts for military integration as
well.
   Among steps approved by the council in its drive for a gulf
common market was one entitling a citizen of any member nation to
own shares in companies in another member country.
   The six leaders requested an Arab League foreign ministers'
conference in a new push to end Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war.
   They expressed support for Egypt's reinstatement into the
22-member Arab League, nearly a decade after Egypt's membership was
suspended to protest its 1979 peace treaty with Israel.
   The leaders pledged to abide by oil production quotas agreed by
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries in November, to
take effect Jan.1, and urged other OPEC member states to observe
their quotas.
   Saudi Arabia, the Emirates, Qatar and Kuwait belong to the
13-member cartel. Bahrain and Oman do not, but all six depend on oil
revenues.
   The summit ``affirmed the necessity of cooperation between OPEC
and other oil producers outside the organization, considering that
stability of (oil) prices in a collective responsibility.''
   Runaway overproduction by some OPEC members in recent months has
driven oil prices below OPEC's benchmark level of $18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
