<HEAD>Syracuse University Grieves Loss of 35 Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Britain-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos SUC7, LaserColor SUC8</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas lights went out Thursday night,
and anguished Syracuse University students hugged at memorial
services to ``embrace the pain'' of losing 35 classmates in the
crash of a Pan Am jumbo jet.
   ``I don't know how to describe it when somebody dies. It hurts
and you can't help,'' said Lisa M. Blake, a sophomore from
Baldwinsville, N.Y. ``I want to bring them back.''
   The Syracuse students were among 258 people who died when the New
York-bound Boeing 747 crashed into dozens of homes in the Scottish
village of Lockerbie Wednesday night, killing another 22 people on
the ground. Authorities are investigating the possibility that a
terrorist group planted a bomb aboard the jetliner.
   Syracuse Mayor Tom Young ordered the city's Christmas lights
turned off Thursday night in memory of the crash victims and asked
residents to do the same.
   Two memorial services were held Thursday at Hendricks Memorial
Chapel for students and faculty. A prayer vigil was held Wednesday
night that drew more than 600 people, and 25,000 people attending a
university basketball game paused for a minute of silence and a
brief prayer.
   At one of Thursday's services many participants had red, puffy
eyes and few failed to join in the hugging after the service.
   ``The only way to look forward is to embrace the pain and
acknowledge it as a part of life,'' drama professor Geri Clark said
as she emerged from the chapel.
   ``If you avoid the pain, it goes inside and it destroys you,''
said Clark, who knew several students killed in the crash.
   At one service, Rev. Paul Kowalewski told about 400 people they
were not alone in their grief.
   ``When one person dies we are all diminished. It is like when a
finger is severed, the whole body hurts,'' said Kowalewski, the
university's Protestant chaplain.
   ``You can be consoled because Christ is crying with us. Christ
grieves, too,'' he said.
   English instructor Donna Marsh sat teary-eyed over a stack of
graded final exams she was returning to students.
   ``It's just horrible. I'm fine but I feel horrible for the
parents and the families,'' said Marsh, who taught a composition
course to Kesha Weedon, one of the victims.
   The university tried to take a business-as-usual approach and
finish the final two days of examinations before recessing for a
three-week holiday break.
   University Chancellor Melvin Eggers issued a memo to faculty
asking them to be ``sensitive and understanding'' to students too
distraught to take their tests.
   ``They will be given exams only if they are prepared,'' said
Eggers.
   Marsh and Clark said none of their students had asked for
additional time for their final exams.
   ``I don't know how anyone could keep their mind focused now,''
said Mike Gacek, a senior from Bristol, Conn., who finished his
exams Wednesday and later learned a fraternity brother was on board
Flight 103.
   Gacek said he was staying away from the Sigma Alpha Epsilon house
because it was ``a pit of sorrow.''
</TEXT>
