<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to restore dropped cycle designator</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anti-Government Rebels Burn Lawmaker's Home, Kill Guard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels stabbed an unarmed guard to
death at a government lawmaker's home after setting the house ablaze
in postelection violence, a police spokesman said Thursday.
   Rebels of the People's Liberation Front, the main Sinhalese
extremist group, also burned two post offices in Matara, said the
spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing regulation.
   The attacks Wednesday followed Prime Minister Ranasinghe
Premadasa's victory in Monday's presidential election. Premadasa, of
the governing United National Party, defeated Sirimavo Bandaranaike
of the Sri Lanka Freedom Party.
   The raiders attacked the home of Dayananda Wickremasinghe near
Matara, 85 miles south of Colombo. Wickremasinghe was not at home.
   When house guard R. Vedamataya tried to intervene, he was stabbed
and his body set on fire, the spokeseman said.
   Sinhalese militants were accused of killing more than 430 people
in the past month in trying to disrupt the presidential polls and
were blamed for 15 additional deaths on election day.
   The Front had called for an election boycott. It says the
government conceded too much in a July 1987 peace accord aimed at
ending the 5-year-old insurrection by separatist guerrillas from the
minority Tamil community.
   Sinhalese form 75 percent of the island's 16 million people.
Tamils make up 18 percent and accuse the Sinhalese of discriminating
against them in jobs and education.
   The Sun newspaper quoted Premadasa on Thursday as saying he has
given Sinhalese militants 10 days to give up violence and join in
the democratic process.
   ``Please make up your mind soon. You have another chance of
joining the democratic process at the forthcoming parliamentary
elections,'' Premadasa was quoted as saying. ``I am available for
any consultation with a view to arriving at a practical solution.''
   Premadasa will be sworn in as president Jan. 2. General elections
are scheduled for Feb. 15.
