<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Crash-SecurityStudy     12-22 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Security Study,1st Ld-Writethru,a0724,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAO Says FAA Can Do More to Improve Foreign Airport Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 2 with revised Pan Am passenger total</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration cannot run
mock weapons through foreign airports to test security, as it does
in the United States, but it can do more to help make the airports
safer, a congressional study said Thursday.
   The study was made public by the General Accounting Office was
released a day after a U.S.-bound Pan American World Airways
jetliner exploded and crashed in Scotland, killing all 258 people
aboard and at least 22 people on the ground.
   Investigators were focusing on a telephoned threat made against
flights on the route two weeks ago.
   The FAA, which has imposed fines totaling $2.6 million against
dozens of U.S. airlines for safety lapses over the last six months,
uses undercover agents to smuggle fake weaponry aboard planes at
American airports. But it conducts far less aggressive inspections
abroad.
   The agency, in a report released last year, said that 20 percent
of mock weapons and bombs smuggled onto planes at U.S. airports went
undetected, with results varying widely among the 28 airports
checked. FAA officials say more of the fake weapons are now spotted
by improved airport security.
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, agreed with the FAA
that it could not conduct such testing at foreign airports because
``of sovereignty concerns and possible danger to inspectors.''
   Kenneth M. Mead, GAO associate director, said the study looked
into FAA inspections at five foreign airports considered likely
terrorist targets. He declined to identify them but said they did
not include either Frankfurt or London.
   Mead said the study was not released because of the Pan Am crash
but had been scheduled for release Thursday, 15 days after it was
sent to the House subcommittee on government activities and
transportation, which requested it.
   Raymond Salazar, FAA director of security, said the report was
``fairly complimentary'' of what the agency was doing abroad, but he
conceded it identified areas that need more attention.
   FAA inspectors check foreign airports with on-sight inspections
and interviews with local officials, the study said. It recommended
that the aviation agency require its inspectors to analyze tests
conducted by foreign officials at their own airports.
   ``We believe the FAA could enhance the overall security
assessment process by requiring inspectors to make some analysis of
host country test results,'' the report said.
   It also said the FAA has failed to notify the State Department of
training needed for foreign airport personnel under the
Anti-Terrorism Assistance Program. In fiscal 1987, the program
trained 3,000 people in 46 countries and provided $2.8 million worth
of equipment to 18 countries, according to the report.
   The FAA uses two-person teams to inspect foreign airports,
spending from three to five days at each, depending on the airport's
size.
   A 1985 law requires the secretary of transportation to notify a
foreign country when the FAA concludes that security is lax at one
of its airports.
   In 600 inspections of 200 airports during 1986 and 1987, the FAA
found only two occasions where the country had to be formally
notified that it was not meeting international standards, the report
said.
   In 1986, the secretary issued public notice that the Manila
International Airport was unsafe. At the other airport, which was
not identified, safety was upgraded within 90 days and no public
notice was given, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
