<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Crash-BombTheories     12-22 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Bomb Theories,1st Ld-Writethru,a0742,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Small Bomb Could Bring Down Jumbo Jet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 4 with revised Pan Am passenger count</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As investigators centered on sabotage as the
cause of a Pan Am jumbo jet disaster, aviation experts said Thursday
a crash could be caused by a relatively small bomb if the blast
damages a plane's sensitive control systems.
   ``Depending on where a bomb is placed, even a relatively small
explosive device can fatally cripple an aircraft. We're not talking
about the kinds of explosive force you would need to cripple a
tank,'' said John Mazor, a spokesman for the private Air Line Pilots
Association.
   Kenneth Plunkett, a representative of the Aviation Safety
Institute, agreed, noting that ``it's not the size of the bomb, it's
where it is placed.''
   Both Mazor and Plunkett stressed that they had no first-hand
details about what caused the crash of Pan Am Flight 103 in Scotland
Wednesday. All 258 people aboard the Boeing 747 jetliner were
killed, along with 22 people on the ground in the village of
Lockerbie.
   The New York-bound flight had originated in West Germany and U.S.
officials said Thursday that American embassies had issued travel
warnings about a recent threat that a Pan Am Frankfurt-to-New York
plane would be the target of a bomb.
   Aviation experts noted that the widely scattered wreckage,
witness reports of a flash of light from the jet when at a high
altitude and its sudden disappearance from radar at 31,000 feet all
tend to support the sabotage theory.
   Mazor said aircraft in flight are extremely vulnerable.
   ``Aircraft have to be designed to balance the two considerations
of structural strength versus weight,'' he said. ``Even an aircraft
designed to structural standards which are well above adequate for
normal flying operations and minor problems is not going to be
anywhere near strong enough to withhstand the effects of any
decent-sized explosive device. They just aren't made to withstand
that kind of thing.''
   ``You don't even have to blow off a major piece of the aircraft's
structure to cripple it,'' said Mazor. ``If a bomb severs some major
or important electrical wiring, or hydraulic lines or cables, you
could lose your ability to control the airplane.''
   Plunkett agreed, speaking for the safety institute, a private
organization based in Worthington, Ohio, which has studied
airline-related issues since 1972.
   ``The biggest problem is the concussion pressure the bomb
causes,'' he said. ``If the plane was at 31,000 feet, it was
pressurized. If a bomb goes off and punctures the outside skin of
the plane, that would cause an explosive decompression of the cabin
and the entire aircraft.''
   ``When that happens, the entire cabin fills with a mist or a
cloud caused by the swift change in pressure,'' he said. ``It might
take a little longer to affect the cockpit, but the cockpit would be
affected.''
   ``Normally, an explosive decompression sends a plane into an
immediate, steep dive,'' he explained.
   ``Another possibility is that if there was a bomb, the plane went
out of control,'' he said. ``Depending on where a bomb is located,
the explosion might cut cables or wiring and you would lose the
ability to control the plane.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
