<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Crash-Threat 2ndLd-Writethru a0716 12-22 0932</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Threat, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0716,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am, U.S. Government Issued Warnings After Threats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to reflect Pan Am's revised passenger total</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan American World Airways stepped up security
at key airports, and U.S. embassies issued travel warnings after a
threat two weeks ago that someone would ``unwittingly'' carry a bomb
aboard a Frankfurt to New York flight, officials said Thursday.
   While other causes have not been ruled out, the investigation
into Wednesday's crash of Pan Am Flight 103 is focusing on the
possibility of sabotage.
   The Boeing 747 jetliner crashed into a Scottish farming town,
killing all 258 aboard and at least 22 people on the ground. The
flight originated in Frankfurt, West Germany and, after a plane
change in London, was en route to New York when it disappeared from
radar.
   Aviation experts cautioned Thursday that it was too early to
pinpoint a cause of the crash but said the widely scattered
wreckage, witness reports of a flash of light from the jet when at a
high altitude and its sudden disappearance from radar at 31,000 feet
all tend to support the sabotage theory.
   Government and airline industry officials acknowledged that they
received a threat in early December that Pan Am might be a target of
a terrorist attack. The Federal Aviation Administration issued an
``intelligence alert'' on Dec. 5 warning that there might be a
bombing attempt against a Pan Am flight from Frankfurt, West Germany.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said that on that day
an anonymous caller told the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki that ``an
unidentified person in Helsinki would unwittingly take the device to
Frankfurt and eventually onto the U.S.-bound flight.''
   Another source said the caller claimed the bomb would be carried
by a woman.
   Mrs. Oakley said the caller targeted Pan AM and told the embassy
that individuals who would provide the device have ties to Abu
Nidal, leader of a radical Palestinian faction.
   The Finnish Foreign Ministry said in a statement Thursday that an
Arab resident had made several bomb threats during the year, most
recently on Dec. 5, but that ``in the investigation so far, no
direct connection has been found between the Arab living in Finland
and the air accident in question.''
   The statement said authorities knew the caller's identity and
that he had not left Finland since Dec. 5.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the State Department
warned embassies of the threat two days after it first was made and
also notified Pan Am and ``appropriate police'' in various parts of
the world.
   Flight 103 started in Frankfurt with a Boeing 727. Its passengers
and their luggage were transferred to a Boeing 747 and joined by
other passengers at London's Heathrow Airport for the flight to New
York. The crash occurred an hour after departure from London.
   Mrs. Oakley said British authorities also were notified of the
threat, but in London a spokesman for Heathrow Airport, Frances
Aldridge, told reporters, ``I can say categorically that we have not
heard of this.''
   Pamela Hanlon, a Pan Am spokeswoman, said in New York: ``Pan Am
had received notification from various sources that there was the
possibility of a (terrorist) threat. ... We immediately acted and
put supplementary security procedures in effect, not only at
Frankfurt but at airports around the world.''
   She confirmed one of the warnings came from the Federal Aviation
Administration, but defended the airline's decision not to further
disclose the potential for danger, citing a portion of the memo that
directed the information to be ``solely for the use of U.S. carriers
and airport security personnel and may not be further disseminated
without the specific approval of the director of civil aviation
security.''
   The FAA in its alert said it was not in a position to evaluate
the reliability of the report, which named no specific terrorist
group, although it said the threat was ``Middle East oriented,''
according to sources, who spoke on the condition that they not be
identified.
   According to government sources, the alert was sent to airline
security officers, airport officials and specifically to Pan Am
because the airline was mentioned in the threat. The alert also went
to the State Department.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said the agency had no comment on the
reported alert.
   A former FAA official familiar with such warnings said that while
such alerts are not infrequent, they are expected to be taken
seriously. ``It's more than a hint. It's a direct request to beef up
security,'' said the former official.
   As a result of the alert, airport officials at Frankfurt also
stepped up security earlier this month, according to Horst
Harnstein, an official at the airport.
   The State Department, meanwhile, warned its embassies of the
possible threat and at some embassies, including the one in Moscow,
an advisory was placed on employee bulletin boards.
   ``The FAA reports that the reliability of the information cannot
be assessed at this point, but the appropriate police authorities
have been notified and are pursuing the matter. Pan Am has also been
notified,'' William C. Kelly, the administrative counsel at the
embassy in Moscow, wrote in the advisory posted there.
   ``In view of the lack of confirmation of this information, (the
embassy) leaves to the discretion of individual travelers any
decisions on altering personal travel plans or changing to another
American carrier,'' the memo continued.
   State Department officials said at least four of those killed in
the Pan Am crash were government employees including two assigned to
the U.S. Embassy in Beirut.
</TEXT>
