<DOCNO> AP881222-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1937EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Crash-WarningResponsibility 2ndLd-Writethru a0731 12-22
0913</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Warning Responsibility, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0731,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. May Make Public Terrorist Threats in Future</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to reflect Pan Am's revised passenger total</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said Thursday that it
was re-examining its policy against public disclosure of terrorist
threats against commercial airliners, such as the one that was made
against Pan Am two weeks ago but disclosed only to diplomatic
personnel.
   Pan Am flight 103, originating in Frankfurt, West Germany, with a
change of plane's at London's Heathrow Airport, crashed in Scotland
on Wednesday, killing all 258 people aboard and more than 20 on the
ground.
   U.S. embassies around the world and Pan Am officials were
informed about the threat against the airliner by an Arab resident
of Helsinki. But no word went out to the general public.
   ``I think that certainly will be looked at,'' presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said as controversy swirled over the
government's policy not to inform the public of terrorist threats
involving U.S. carriers.
   Fitzwater acknowledged that ``the public should be aware'' of
such threats. ``Public notification has to be considered.''
   President-elect Bush said that if there was ``hard evidence''
that a specific flight was threatened or that the threat could not
be averted, the public should be warned.
   But he warned against giving ``undue attention to what the
terrorist wants to call attention to.''
   ``So often its best to handle these matters by aborting a
threat,'' Bush said.
   Until now, the policy has been for the State Department to pass
on information about terrorist threats to the carriers through the
Federal Aviation Administration and to the airports.
   ``It's then up to the airlines to take the precautions that they
deem are necessary for the security of their flights,'' State
Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said.
   Pan Am spokeswoman Pam Hanlon in New York said the airline
received a memo from the Federal Aviation Administration about the
threat and quoted the document as saying: ``The information in this
bulletin is solely for the use of U.S. carriers and airport security
personnel and may not be further disseminated without the specific
approval of the director of civil aviation security.''
   Private lawyers said Thursday that the fact that the U.S.
government and Pan Am were both aware of the bomb threat could raise
liability problems for the airline, but probably not for the
government.
   ``It's a difficult area, but if the government notifies the
airline in question, I think the government position is justified,''
said Lee Kreindler, a New York lawyer who specializes in aviation
accident cases.
   Asked what an airline's obligation is once it has been notified
of a specific threat, Kreindler said ``It's a tough situation. ...
They don't have to stop operating or stop flying, but certainly they
have a duty to meticulously inspect.''
   He said that in other instances of terrorism involving air
travel, lawsuits have focused on airline security precautions.
   The prior notification on U.S. embassy bulletin boards ``is going
to raise an interesting question for the other passengers who were
not members of the State Department staff: Whether they should have
received similar notice from Pan Am,'' said George N. Tompkins Jr.,
a lawyer specializing in defending airlines in accident cases.
   In Washington, officials were bombarded with questions about the
government's policy after powerful evidence emerged pointing to an
explosive device as the cause of the crash of Pan Am flight 103.
   Bush said individual threats had to be evaluated. ``I've found
with some experience in the intelligence business enormous numbers
of suggestions that there is going to be some terroristic action and
most of them never materialize,'' said Bush, a former director of
the CIA.
   Mrs. Oakley said that on Dec. 5, an unidentified individual
telephoned the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki and said that there would be
a bombing attempt within two weeks against a Pan Am aircraft flying
from Frankfurt to the United States.
   The conduit would be an ``unwitting'' passenger who would take
the device from Helsinki to Frankfurt and then board a U.S.-bound
flight, she said.
   Mrs. Oakley said dozens of threats are received each day and all
are taken seriously. L. Paul Bremer, who heads the State
Department's counter-terrorism office, said there have been 87 calls
similar to the Helsinki call over the past three months.
   But the Dec. 5 call, apparently from a tipster, appeared to be
taken more seriously than most others. Many U.S. embassies were
apprised of the threat, including the American mission in Moscow,
where a notice of the threat was posted on a bulletin board.
   Ronald Spiers, the State Department under secretary for
management, suggested that chaos would result if the government
reacted to each terrorist threat.
   ``One of the kind of problems you face is overkill,'' Spiers
said. ``You get a lot of these threats; people tend to get bored
with it.''
   ``We try to be responsible. We try to make sure that everybody
who is possibly involved receives this information. But we're not
the airlines ourselves,'' he said.
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Dan Howard said no posting of the
warning was made at the various U.S. military commands around the
world.
   ``The only explanation that I have been able to get is that there
are many of these notices sent out in the course of the year and
they are not generally posted,'' Howard said.
   He said at least six U.S. military personnel were aboard the Pan
Am flight.
</TEXT>
