<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0640 12-22 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0640,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scottish Town Feels Numb As Crash Impact Sinks In</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs to lower figure of those aboard plane to
258; Pan Am says a flight attendant was counted twice. PICKS up 4th
pvs ``It is beyond...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XDUM15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corpses were strewn on a golf course
and children played beside twisted airplane wreckage Thursday in
this village scarred physically and emotionally by the Pan Am crash.
   Residents recalled whooshing noises and tremendous flames as the
stricken Boeing 747 jumbo jet roared low overhead, spewing pieces
over the rolling countryside and finally crashing in fragments
across their streets and houses Wednesday evening.
   All 258 people aboard Pan Am Flight 103 from Frankfurt to New
York, via London, died and as many as 22 people were killed on the
ground, some in cars hit by wreckage, officials said. The number of
people on the plane was lowered when it was found that an airline
employee was counted twice.
   ``It is beyond one's comprehension,'' murmured Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher, who toured the village. ``It is beyond one's
imagination. ... You have to come here to see it and to realize.''
   A long, deep crater tore a black scar along a row of houses.
Other homes, drenched in flaming aviation fuel, were gutted.
   Survivors comforted each other, felt lucky to be alive, and tried
to clean up some of the mess in the town of 2,500 people.
   In a yard next to the main street lay the cover of one engine,
but the fence and adjacent building were undamaged. Children
bicycled around a chunk of fuselage, and the grocer boarded up his
shattered store front.
   Scorched pillows, lifejackets and fragments of clothing lay
scattered in gardens. Chunks of metal, some as small as coins and
others two feet in diameter, had sliced through roofs and shattered
windows in homes and cars.
   Charred dollar bills, a mud-spattered seatbelt and tattered
copies of the Pan Am inflight magazine added to the melancholy scene.
   Lockerbie's town hall became a makeshift morgue as firefighters
recovered remains strewn about town. Eight bodies lay on a
neighboring golf course, covered in tarpaulins and guarded by police.
   Four miles outside town, the nose cone of the blue-and-white
jumbo jet was tipped on its side in a muddy field.
   ``There'll be no Christmas this year as far as Lockerbie is
concerned,'' said Bobby Scott, a builder who had just finished work
Wednesday night when he heard the explosion.
   He dashed out to see the jet heading toward the gas station, and
watched the disaster unfold yards from him.
   The plane was breaking up as he saw it come over a hill about 200
yards from the main street that runs through the town of mainly
two-story stone shops and houses.
   ``There were flames everywhere and pieces dropping off the plane
and it just kept going,'' said Scott, 30, who escaped unscathed.
   ``I was very, very lucky. Many of us here were,'' he said. ``I
think all of us just think so much of all those Americans who were
on that plane.''
   Nora Pickersgill, 60, was out playing bingo when her house was
damaged by wreckage.
   ``Normally, I would have been in,'' she said as she swept up
shattered glass. ``I still can't believe what happened. It just
isn't the sort of thing that happens to you, just not the sort of
thing that happens in a quiet place like this.''
   In Sherwood Park, the worst-hit street, two houses were
demolished and their occupants feared dead. Pieces of fuselage were
embedded in gardens.
   Ronald Miller, 74, was watching television and his wife, Jane,
was in the kitchen getting a glass of water when the home they had
bought six months ago was turned into a ball of flame and partially
demolished.
   ``I heard a huge whoosh,'' said Miller. ``I thought it was a
low-flying military plane. I ducked down, then the window fell in
and I was shot head first into the television set.''
   The Millers rushed outside and were saved. Now Miller, a retired
plasterer, clutched a plastic bag containing a shaving set he had
just bought, and sat with his wife in a cafe on the main street.
   Miller's head was badly cut, but otherwise they were uninjured.
   Outside, police put up barriers for the arrivals of Prince
Andrew, the Duke of York, and Mrs. Thatcher.
   ``We've lost everything,'' Miller said, ``things we can never
replace, our home and a lifetime's possessions.''
</TEXT>
