<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Crash-Investigation 1stLd-Writethru a076rt 12-22 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0764,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrorist Threat Looms Large in Crash Investigation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs with Pan Am lowering figure of those on
plane to 258; saying a flight attendant was counted twice. PICKS up
3rd pvs: The flight originated ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators on Thursday began to reconstruct the
final hours of Pan Am Flight 103, giving special attention to
threats of a terrorist attack.
   The chief of Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist branch opened an
investigation of the London stopover of the Boeing 747 that crashed
Wednesday night in southern Scotland, killing all 258 on board and
22 on the ground. The number of those on the plane was lowered when
Pan Am discovered it had counted a flight attendant twice.
   The flight originated with a Boeing 727 in Frankfurt, West
Germany, and continued as a Boeing 747 from London, en route to New
York.
   The U.S. State Department said an anonymous caller said Dec. 5
that a bomb would be planted on the flight from Frankfurt, West
Germany to London. U.S. officials said warnings were issued to its
embassies.
   According to British authorities, word never reached Heathrow
Airport.
   ``I can say categorically that we had not heard of this. ... We
were definitely unaware of any threat,'' said airport spokesman
Frances Aldridge.
   On Thursday, an anonymous caller to The Associated Press in
London claimed an explosive had been planted aboard Flight 103 in
revenge for the downing of an Iranian airliner by the U.S. Navy in
July.
   The sabotage theory focused on the transfer of luggage between
the Boeing 727 that flew the Frankfurt-London leg, and the Boeing
747 that took off for New York.
   Experts said such switchovers could pose security risks, because
a passenger could leave the flight in London while sending deadly
cargo on to New York.
   Pan Am's baggage-checking system is intended to ensure that every
person who checks baggage boards the aircraft, airline spokesman
Harold Kosel said in Frankfurt.
   Asked whether a passenger might have disembarked in London while
sending luggage on to New York, Kosel said, ``I think it's out of
the question.''
   Hans Neusel, state secretary at West Germany's Interior Ministry,
said Thursday night the West German Federal Criminal Office ``was in
continuous, close contact with Scotland Yard for the immediate relay
of information to us.''
   Neusel told West German TV ``we don't believe there are any soft
spots in security'' at Frankfurt airport.
   But David Learmont, an editor of the industry magazine Flight
International, said in London that ``I think they can be very
confident, but I don't think anyone can be totally sure.''
   Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency, reported that
54 million pieces of luggage move through Heathrow in a year.
   Pan Am operates two daily non-stops to the United States from
Frankfurt, as well as Flight 103.
   In Washington, the State Department's counterterrorism office
offered FBI forensics and disaster units to assist British
authorities. ``I would think we would probably use our own,'' said a
Department of Transport spokesman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Government and industry officials said it seemed clear that the
Boeing 747 had broken apart in flight, strewing blazing wreckage
over the Scottish village of Lockerbie and surrounding hills, and
that the most likely causes were an explosive device or structural
failure.
   Such a sudden catastrophe would be consistent with flight
controller reports that the cockpit sent no distress call as the
plane, having reached cruising altitude of 31,000 feet, disappeared
from radar.
   ``Speculation is not evidence,'' said Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher, during a visit to the crash scene. ``We are systematically
searching the evidence and the hills around.''
   The devices that record flight data and cockpit conversations
were recovered, and a multinational investigation was taking shape.
   Donald Cooper, chief inspector of the air accident investigation
branch of Britain's Department of Transport, had overall charge of
the probe.
   Under international agreement, a Department of Transport
spokesman said, the United States was entitled to participate,
through the National Transportation Safety Board. Experts also also
expected from the Boeing Co. and from Pratt and Whitney, which
manufactured the engines.
   George Churchill-Coleman, commander of Scotland Yard's
anti-terrorist branch, opened an investigation that was expected to
focus on the 65 minutes between Flight 103's arrival at Heathrow on
Wednesday night and its departure for New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
