<DOCNO> AP881222-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Bus     12-22 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Bus,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Plunge in Andes Kills 21; Guerrillas Bomb Rail Bridge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus loaded with Christmas travelers careened
off a highway in the Andes on Thursday and tumbled down a 100-foot
ravine, killing at least 21 people and injuring at least 12, police
said.
   In the same area, Maoist guerrillas from the Shining Path
movement blew up part of a railroad bridge close to the 15,700-foot
summit of the highest standard-gauge railroad in the world,
according to police.
   They said the two incidents were not connected, though they took
place hours apart and both occurred outside Casapalca, a town 60
miles east of Lima lying in a key transportation corridor linking
the coast with the highlands.
   Police said the bus death toll could grow.
   They said a preliminary investigation indicated recent heavy
rains caused a rockslide at a curve in the highway.
   Surviving pssengers and police said heavy fog obscured visibility
and contributed to the pre-dawn crash.
   The privately owned bus was bound from Cerro de Pasco to Lima, a
distance of 120 miles, and carried about 45 passengers, police said.
   Shining Path guerrillas exploded dynamite around midnight
Wednesday that heavily damaged girders of the rail bridge, police
said. No trains were in the area and no one was hurt. Officials said
rail traffic would be suspended for days for repairs.
   The Shining Path, Peru's biggest and most violent guerrilla
group, has attacked and disabled rail links dozens of times in its
eight-year insurgency.
   In Lima, attackers believed to be pro-Cuban guerrillas fired a
mortar shell that failed to explode at offices of the state mineral
marketing firm Minpeco. Police said they recovered the mortar from a
nearby park.
   Guerillas also bombed two suburban department stores, breaking
windows, officials said.
   No one was hurt in the attacks.
   Police said the Tupa Amaru Revolutionary Movement, a small rebel
band that endorses a Cuban-styled Marxism, probably carried out the
Lima attacks.
</TEXT>
