<DOCNO> AP881222-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PolygamistClan 2ndAdd a0795 12-22 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Clan, 2nd Add, a0795,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>COALVILLE, Utah: Addam Swapp</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In addition to the second-degree murder charges, jurors were
instructed that they could consider convicting Jonathan Swapp and
Singer on lesser charges including manslaughter and negligent
homicide.
   The jury had begun deliberating Monday night following nine days
of testimony from 51 prosecution and seven defense witnessses,
including Addam Swapp and Jonathan Swapp.
   Prosecutor Creighton Horton told jurors that the defendants
deliberately embraced a course of confrontation that led to House's
death. Defense attorneys countered that clan members, while
well-armed, never intended to hurt anyone and feared police were
looking for an excuse to kill them.
   House was killed and Addam Swapp seriously wounded in a firefight
that ended the standoff at the clan's Marion farm. The compound was
surrounded by an army of 100 FBI-led police Jan. 16, hours after
Addam Swapp, claiming divine inspiration, bombed a Mormon chapel.
   Prosecutors had maintained that Addam Swapp ``basically declared
war on the church, state and nation'' when he bombed the chapel.
   The trial concluded the second of two prosecutions against clan
members. In May, the three and Vickie Singer, the mother of John
Timothy and Addam Swapp's two wives, were convicted of federal
violations in the standoff, which followed the bombing of the chapel.
   In those crimes, Addam Swapp was sentenced to 15 years, John
Timothy Singer and Jonathan Swapp to 10 years and Vickie Singer to
five years.
   Addam Swapp testified in the latest trial that his family's
battle with society had really begun in 1979 when polygamist
patriarch John Singer was gunned down by police during at arrest
attempt at the same farm where clan members barricaded themselves
last January.
   Police said Singer, who had clashed with authorities over his
refusal to send his children to public schools or teach a
state-approved curriculum at home, was shot to death when he pulled
a gun on officers sent to arrest him. Singer's family maintained he
was shot in the back, but a federal judge dismissed a $110 million
wrongful-death suit filed by Mrs. Singer.
   The maximum penalty for second-degree murder is five years to
life in prison. For manslaughter, the maximum term is zero to five
years, and for negligent homicide one year in jail and a $2,500 fine.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
