<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2006EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-Americans 1stLd-Writethru a0732 12-22 1109</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Americans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,1134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives Of Victims Grieve, Try To Cope</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Syracuse University ...,' to UPDATE with
number of victims now put at 258 aboard the plane. INSERTS 3 grafs
after 6th graf, ``I believe ...,' with details about military
personnel and Justice Department lawyer killed; INSERTS 2 grafs
after 11th graf pvs, `Fenton read ...,' with info on first officer,
Detroit airport scene.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Matthew Trento still held his ticket for Pan Am Flight 103 when
he arrived home, safe and sound, one of the lucky ones.
   Trento, a senior at Syracuse University in New York, lost three
roommates on Flight 103, which crashed Wednesday in Scotland on its
way to New York from London. His mother had booked him on another
flight, five hours earlier.
   ``I was sitting there looking at my ticket after the flight went
down,'' Trento, 22, said. ``It really just made me wonder.''
   Syracuse University officials said 35 students in their Division
of International Programs Abroad in London were booked on the Boeing
747. All 258 people on board were killed, and authorities said
sabotage may be the cause.
   The holiday miracle of a missed flight came to a few, too few,
others.
   ``I believe in guardian angels. ... I'm so thrilled that he's all
right, ... it's going to be such a great Christmas,'' said Jackie
Richardson of Ironton, Ohio, whose son, Robert, a Navy machinist's
mate, took an alternate flight.
   Other military families were not as lucky. The Army said there
were at least eight soldiers and five of their dependents aboard
Flight 103, while the Air Force said three of its personnel and five
of their dependents were on the plane. One of those killed, Army
Sgt. Lloyd David Ludlow, 41, was traveling to Hutchinson, Kan., for
the funeral of his sister.
   ``It's hard for me to understand. The boy never did a thing wrng
in his life. The sunlight has been taken out of a lot of people's
lives,'' said George Williams of suburban Baltimore, whose son,
First Lt. George W. ``Jordy'' Williams, 24, was aboard Flight 103.
Williams, who was stationed near Frankfurt, West Germany, missed his
intended flight because of a traffic jam and made a connection with
the Pan Am flight.
   Also affected was the Justice Department, where flags were
ordered flown at half-staff in memory of Michael Bernstein, an
attorney for the Office of Special Investigations, the department's
Nazi-hunting unit. Bernstein, 36, married and the father of two, had
been in Austria negotiating a treaty that would allow some former
Nazis in the United States to be deported to that country, the
Justice Department said.
   ``It's not just a headline in the paper. This makes us long all
the more for the Christmas message to come through, peace on earth.
We obviously don't have it yet,'' Roman Catholic Bishop Anthony
Bosco of Greensburg, Pa., said Thursday after learning that two
Seton Hill College students _ Beth Ann Johnson, 21, of Greensburg
and Elyse Saraceni, 20, of Crabtree _ were on the jet.
   Janet MacQuarrie, the wife of the pilot of the jetliner, said
Thursday she planned no funeral for her 55-year-old husband, James,
but asked Americans to observe a moment of silence at 1 p.m. on
Christmas Day for the crash victims.
   Skip Vaught, also a pilot, and John Fenton, longtime friends of
the MacQuarrie family of Kensington, N.H., spoke with reporters at
Town Hall.
   Asked if they had discussed the dangers of terrorism, Vaught
said, ``Naturally, all pilots talk about this sort of thing, but we
do our jobs.''
   Fenton read the request by Mrs. MacQuarrie that donations be sent
to the New England Home for Little Wanderers in Boston, where her
husband spent time as an orphaned youngster.
   First Officer Raymond R. Wagner, 52, of Pennington, N.J., was
remembered by his church's former pastor, the Rev. Walter Coats, as
``a person who accepted his job as a pilot in a very serious manner.
... If I could have ever chosen which pilot would fly my plane, I
would have chosen Raymond Wagner.''
   At Detroit Metropolitan Airport, the final destination of Flight
103, families of Michigan-bound passengers, including two executives
of Troy-based Volkswagen United States Inc., learned the grim news.
Families of some of the 156 victims of a Northwest Airlines crash at
the airport two years ago consoled the grieving.
   At Syracuse University on Wednesday night, 500 people gathered at
a chapel, where chaplains of five faiths led a prayer service.
   ``We gathered because we needed to come together. The students
needed to demonstrate their sorrow, to be with one another,'' said
the Rev. Paul Kowalewski, a Protestant chaplain. ``It's Christmas,
they're students and young _ everything in a tragedy is built into
this.''
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo issued a statement Thursday expressing
his sorrow and ordering flags flown at half-staff through Saturday.
   ``For all the lives lost and particularly to the Syracuse
University community, we extend our most profound and heartfelt
sympathies and our prayers for strength,'' Cuomo said.
   Elsewhere on campus, more than 25,000 people at a basketball game
Wednesday night paused for a minute of silence and a brief prayer.
   ``This is the saddest day of my life,'' said University
Chancellor Melvin Eggers. ``We've lost some of the brightest,
talented, most beautiful people. It's hard to express our sorrow.''
   In North Adams, Mass., news that Wendy Lincoln, 23, would not be
coming home stunned many in the community of 16,500, said Mayor John
Barrett 3d. ``The Christmas presents are under the tree and of
course she won't be home,'' he said.
   Ms. Lincoln, a Syracuse University student, was on Flight 103,
according to the school.
   Her family had planned to meet her at John F. Kennedy Airport in
New York with a rented limousine as a special holiday touch. ``(Mrs.
Lincoln) had taken the day off and was all excited to pick up her
daughter,'' Barrett said.
   Another victim, Jim Pitt, 24, of South Hadley, Mass., had planned
to fly home directly from Germany, where he was studying, but at the
last minute decided to fly with a friend to London first, his family
said.
   Pitt called home and left a message that he would be on the Pan
Am flight, his mother, Sallie Hughes Pitt, said.
   She said Pitt was a champion fencer and a poet who wrote long
letters home regularly.
   ``He would call me up and say, `How're you doing, Mom? I was
thinking about you today.' He did that just last week and said he
was looking forward to coming home,'' she said.
</TEXT>
