<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Factory     12-22 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Factory,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Denies U.S. Charges It Built Chemical Weapons Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Libya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya on Thursday denied U.S. charges that it built a
chemical weapons plant and declared its ``full commitment to all
international conventions'' regarding such weapons, the official
news agency JANA reported.
   The statement from the People's Bureau for Foreign Liaison,
Libya's foreign ministry, was issued after President Reagan said the
United States and its allies were discussing military action against
the plant.
   The radical North African Arab nation has said repeatedly that
the factory produces pharmaceuticals. JANA said earlier Thursday
that Libyan doctors, nurses and pharmacists are planning a sit-in at
the plant in a move apparently intended to discourage any attack.
   Libya has ``repeatedly denied all misleading U.S. claims,'' said
the People's Bureau statement, according to the agency, monitored in
Rome and London.
   It said the Reagan administration's aim was to blunt the
development of Arab societies and ``to this end it will market all
the excuses it can find to mislead and trick world public opinion.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday the United
States believes the plant ``can produce enormous quantities of
chemical weapons.''
   The Washington Post quoted intelligence sources as saying the
plant is 35 miles southwest of Tripoli and includes facilities for
producing bombs and canisters to carry poisonous gas.
   The subject of chemical weapons will be taken up next month at a
convention of more than 100 countries in Paris called to discuss
enforcement of the 1925 Geneva Convention outlawing chemical arms.
   Libya on Thursday accused the United States of trying to ruin the
Paris convention and divert attention from its own chemical weapons
stocks.
   ``While categorically denying all the American allegations, Libya
reaffirms its full commitment to all international conventions and
treaties concerning chemical weapons,'' the statement said.
   JANA's earlier dispatch, which quoted unidentified ``senior
medical sources,'' did not say when the sit-in at the plant would
begin.
   ``Those sources also said that this noble civilized
accomplishment (the plant) will never be destroyed except over the
dead bodies of us _ the doctors, pharmacists and nurses,'' it said.
   The United States bombed Libya in 1986 in strikes that killed at
least 100 people in retaliation for a terrorist attack on a West
Berlin disco that killed two U.S. soldiers and a Turkish woman and
wounded 229 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
