<DOCNO> AP881222-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2011EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Crash-FBI     12-22 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-FBI,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sessions Says FBI Joining Pan Am Crash Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI will help Scotland Yard investigate
the cause of a Pan Am jet crash in Scotland that killed all 258
people aboard, FBI Director William Sessions said Thursday.
   Sessions said he had reports of ``a number of calls'' taking
responsibility for the disaster that killed everyone on the plane,
along with 22 residents of the Scottish village of Lockerbie, where
it crashed Wednesday.
   Some callers claimed association with terrorist organizations,
Sessions said at a news conference. He declined to say if Pan
American Flight 103 _ en route from Frankfurt, Germany, to New York
_ was the target of terrorism.
   But David Kyd, spokesman for the International Air Transport
Association in Geneva, said structural failure of the plane was
unlikely.
   ``Sabotage is the most likely explanation,'' Kyd said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the State Department
warned U.S. embassies earlier this month about a bomb threat made
against Pan Am jetliners flying from Frankfurt to the United States.
   Bomb experts with the FBI will visit the crash site and assist
with a technical investigation at Scotland Yard as well, Sessions
said. Britain's top anti-terrorism official, Commander George
Churchill-Coleman, also joined the investigation Thursday.
   Fitzwater said he couldn't explain why more people were not
notified of the threat, and Sessions said actions following the
threat will be evaluated.
   The authority for the FBI action, Sessions said, comes from
federal law allowing investigation abroad in cases of destruction of
U.S. aircraft or when Americans might be victims of terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2057EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary     12-22 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Puts Off Key Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament, with a big agenda and a
newfound propensity for debate, decided on Thursday to postpone
debate until next month on landmark new laws recognizing formation
of political groups independent of the Communist Party.
   The laws are part of the communist government's ``package plan
for democracy,'' which calls for adoption of a new constitution and
a separate law on new political parties before parliamentary
elections in 1990.
   The new laws were the ninth item on a 15-point agenda adopted
when this parliamentary session opened Tuesday. It was the third
meeting in three months of what was once a rubber stamp legislature
in session just 12 days a year.
   Speaker Istvan Stadinger said earlier that the 383-member
Parliament would take an unprecedented Christmas recess and
reconvene on Jan. 10 to conclude business if the agenda was not
completed by Friday.
   Debate this week centered on economic issues, including the 1989
budget and modification of the East bloc's first personal income
tax, introduced Jan. 1.
   Struggling with a $17 billion foreign debt and a stagnating
economy, Hungary has embarked on comprehensive economic reforms. It
introduced market forces, invited foreign investment, cut subsidies
to money-losing firms and taxed personal incomes.
   Following a recent trend for deputies to engage in genuine
debate, more than 40 deputies asked to speak on the budget this week.
   Pressure from deputies caused a vote to be postponed on a
proposed modification of the personal income tax law until another
compromise could be worked out.
   The laws on association and assembly have been long awaited and
much debated in Hungary, where over the past year dozens of
independent groups have developed. Many have highly political
platforms and want to put up candidates in 1990 elections.
   According to drafts published this week, the laws will recognize
the basic right of citizens to assemble and associate, and determine
registration procedures and regulations for independent groups. The
ruling party is the Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
