<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-22 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Moves Through Rockies; Storm Racks West Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front moving through Colorado Thursday brought winds
gusting to more than 140 mph along the Rockies' front range and
triggered heavy thunderstorms in parts of Texas, Oklahoma and
Missouri.
   Meanwhile, another western storm moved into the Pacific Coast
states, bringing heavy rain and high surfs to the California
coastline and snow in the mountains.
   Mount Evans, west of Denver, reported the strongest wind gust
Thursday _ 141 mph, said weather service forecaster Dan Leszcynski.
He said instruments on atop the mountain recorded zero as the high
temperature.
   ``You're probably looking at minus 160 or so wind-chill,'' he
said.
   Other wind gusts behind the cold front were 123 mph near Fort
Collins and 78 mph near Wellington, Colo. An avalanche warning was
in effect for the entire Colorado mountain region because of the
winds and fresh snowfall.
   The same cold front brought thunderstorms from east-central Texas
across eastern Oklahoma into southwest Missouri.
   Freezing rain slickened roads in eastern Iowa and northwest
Illinois. Light snow fell from north-central Nebraska across central
and northeastern South Dakota, with 1 to 4 inches' accumulation
expected.
   Farther west, a separate storm system brought heavy rain and
ocean swells of 15 to 25 feet along the northern and central
California coast. Snow continued to fall in the mountains of
California, where Happy Camp got up to 24 inches in 24 hours and
Trinity River Conservation Camp got 18 inches in the same period.
The heavy snowfall closed numerous mountain roads, including
Interstate 5 near the California-Oregon border.
   Heavy rain over the already-saturated San Francisco Bay area
produced local street flooding and mudslides. Many northern
California towns had more than an inch of rain in a 12-hour period
ending at 1 p.m. EST, including Ross, with 2.52 inches; Gasquet, 2
inches; Shasta Dam, 1.85 inches; San Rafael, 1.40 inches; Soquel
Creek, 1.38 inches; and Berkeley, 1.11 inches.
   Winter storm warnings were issued for the Mount Shasta, Siskiyou
region, the Northeast Plateau and the Sierra Nevada mountains in
California, as well as Nevada's western mountains and higher
elevations of southwest Oregon.
   Elsewhere, Joplin and Columbia, Mo., got 1.64 inches and 1.14
inches of rain, respectively, in the six-hour period ending at 1
p.m. EST. Snowfall during the same six-hour period included 4 inches
at Burns, Ore., and 1 inch at International Falls, Minn.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 11
degrees at Loring Air Force Base near Limestone, Maine, to 84
degrees at McAllen, Texas. The morning low for the nation was 2
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo.
   Friday's forecast called for more showers and thunderstorms from
the central Gulf Coast across the central and southern Appalachians,
the eastern Ohio Valley, the upper Great Lakes and the central and
middle Atlantic Coast states to southern New England, with freezing
rain over northeast New York and parts of Vermont. Snow was
predicted over the northern Rockies and western parts of the central
Rockies. Rain also was forecast along the central and northern
Pacific coasts.
   High temperatures should be in the teens and 20s from central
Montana and western Wyoming across the northern Plains and the upper
Mississippi Valley to western upper Michigan, and over much of
Maine. Highs in the 30s and 40s should extend from the northern and
central Pacific Coast, the northern half of the southern Plateau,
much of the central and southern Rockies, the central Plains, Iowa
and northern Missouri, the Great Lakes and the central and northern
Appalachians to the Middle Atlantic Coast and much of New England.
Readings in the 70s should stretch over south-central and southeast
Texas, the Gulf Coast, northern Florida and southern Georgia, and
warming into the 80s in southern Florida. Highs in the 50s and 60s
should be the rule elsewhere.
</TEXT>
