<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-Angola     12-22 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-Angola,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Congratulates Castro</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
congratulated Cuban President Fidel Castro on the accord signed at
U.N. headquarters Thursday granting independence to South-West
Africa, the official Cuban news agency said.
   Gorbachev called the accord an important step foward toward peace
and security and praised the Cubans' ``heroic help'' in the fight
for independence, according to a Prensa Latina dispatch monitored in
Mexico City.
   Cuban troops went to Angola in 1975 to help its Marxist
government fight guerrillas and invading South African troopers.
   The accord signed by South Africa, Cuba and Angola establishes
the independence of Africa's last colony, South-West Africa, also
called Namibia, to begin April 1. It calls for the phased withdrawal
of the 50,000 Cuban troops now in Angola.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since capturing it from Germany in
World War I.
   The Angolan state news agency ANGOP meanwhile reported on
Thursday that troops killed 53 guerrillas in clashes across Angola
in the last week.
   The report, monitored in Lisbon, Portugal, said troops freed 126
civilians and seized military hardware in clashes in six provinces
Dec. 14-21.
   ANGOP said government forces suffered nine fighters killed and 21
injured and said rebels from UNITA _ the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola _ killed 15 civilians and wounded 23 in
attacks on villages.
   No independent confirmation of the report was available.
   UNITA, backed by the United States and South Africa, is not party
to the accord and has vowed to persist in its 13-year war against
the Marxist government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
