<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2120EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-22 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serbian Politician Blasts Multiparty System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Serbian politician assailed
plans to establish independent political parties in Yugoslavia's
liberal northern republic of Slovenia, newspapers reported Thursday.
   ``Those who demand that the Communist Party divest itself of
power ... are trying to turn the party into a debating club and to
push the party off the political scene,'' said Vjislav Micovic,
according to a report in Politika daily.
   Micovic, a leader of the Serbian Socialist Alliance and close
associate of Serbian party chief Slobodan Milosevic, was quoted as
saying purported party reformers are ``offering us stale old forms
of multiparty political organization.''
   Two Slovenian groups have announced plans to set up independent
parties in Yugoslavia's most westward-looking republic, where
authorities have adopted an unprecedented degree of tolerance.
   The Social Democratic Party is to hold its founding conference
Dec. 27 and the Slovenian Democratic Union is to be established Jan.
10.
   Although top Communist Party and government officials in Slovenia
have said the formation of the new parties would be ``damaging,'' no
other measures seem to have been taken to prevent the gatherings.
   The Slovenian and Serbian leaderships have been at odds since
Milosevic's hard-line faction came to power last year and are
sharply divided over ways to overcome Yugoslavia's economic and
social crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
