<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2126EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Crash-Counterterrorism     12-22 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Counterterrorism,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top State Department Official Says Cause Of Crash Unknown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diploamtic Wrtier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department's chief counter-terrorism
official said Thursday night that not enough is known to conclude
that sabotage caused Wednesday's crash of a Pan Am jumbo jet with
258 people aboard.
   ``We don't know if this is a terrorist attack,'' L. Paul Bremer,
U.S. ambassador at large for counter-terrorism, said in an
Associated Press interview regarding the crash in Scotland that also
killed 22 people on the ground.
   Bremer said at least three groups claimed responsibility for the
crash after it occurred, but he said, ``That's not unusual. There
are often claims after an event like this.''
   A caller identifying himself with the Guardians of Islamic
Revolution, a group that supports Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini, telephoned the AP in London.
   Another caller who said he was with the Islamic Jihad, a Moslem
fundamentalist group, called a television network in New York, while
a third claim was made by the Ulster Defense group, Bremer said.
   So far, he said, none has proved to be connected to the crash.
   He noted that the Federal Aviation Administration ``has pretty
good reporting about very heavy winds at this altitude, up to 200
knots in the jet stream. So it's premature to assess this as
sabotage.''
   Still, Bremer said, ``You certainly want to rule this out. Until
we look at the `black box' and forensic evidence, we should hold our
cool.''
   So far, Bremer said, ``there is very little you can determine.''
   Meanwhile, Bremer said, an investigation is continuing on a call
to the U.S. embassy in Helsinki two weeks ago claiming the radical
Palestinian Abu Nidal group planned to sabotage a Pan American
jetliner on the way from Frankfurt, West Germany, to New York.
   As a result, Bremer said, U.S. embassies in Europe and FAA
officials were advised to alert airlines and security personnel to
upgrade security in both Frankfurt and London.
   A total of 105 such advisories were issued in the last three
months, an average of about one a day, Bremer said. Many of them
followed tips that seemed more serious than the Helsinki call, he
said.
   In ``many, many cases'' of sabotage, the U.S. official said, ``we
find out who did it. But it takes time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
