<HEAD>With Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a thumbnail sketch of Samuel Skinner,
who was named Thursday by President-elect Bush as his Cabinet
secretary for the Department of Transportation.
   
   Skinner is 50 years old, married and the father of two.
   He received an undergraduate degree in accounting from the
University of Illinois in 1960 and a law degree from DePaul
University in 1966.
   He is currently a senior partner in Chicago office of the Sidley
& Austin law firm.
   Since 1984 Skinner has served as chairman of the Regional
Transportation Authority of Northeastern Illinois.
   Skinner also served as an assistant U.S. attorney in Chicago from
1968-1975 and was appointed U.S. attorney in Chicago by Gerald Ford
in 1975 when then-U.S. attorney James Thompson was elected governor
of Illinois.
   He was appointed to President Reagan's Commission on Organized
Crime in 1983.
   He served as the state chairman in Illinois for Bush's
presidential campaign in 1980 and 1988.
   Skinner was a two-time recipient of the Justice Department's
Outstanding Service Award.
</TEXT>
