<2ND_LINE>BC-Sullivan-Thumbnail,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a thumbnail sketch of Dr. Louis W.
Sullivan, who was named Thursday by President-elect Bush as
Secretary of Health and Human Services.
   
   Sullivan is 55 years old, married, a father of three and a native
of Atlanta.
   He graduated with honors both from Morehouse College in 1954 and
from Boston University Medical School in 1958.
   Sullivan is the first black appointed to the Bush Cabinet.
   He has served as the president of the Morehouse School of
Medicine since 1981 where he oversees a faculty and staff of about
100.
   He also has taught medicine at Harvard and Boston universities,
the New Jersey College of Medicine and Morehouse.
   Dr. Sullivan, a blood specialist, has written or co-written more
than 60 articles on blood chemistry and diseases, directed national
research on sickle cell anemia and is former president of the
Foundation for Minority Health Professions.
   He holds a seat on the National Executive Board of the Boy Scouts
of America and is active in the Atlanta chapters of the American Red
Cross and the American Cancer Society.
</TEXT>
