<DOCNO> AP881222-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DukakisInterview     12-22 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Interview,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Won't Judge Bush Yet, But He Applauds Some Moves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although he says it's too early to judge
President-elect George Bush, Michael Dukakis tentatively gave the
man who trounced him in the Nov. 8 election credit Thursday for
showing signs of moderation on Central America.
   ``If that's the way the new administration begins, then I think
that's hopeful,'' the governor said in an interview with The
Associated Press, his first since immediately after the presidential
election. ``Once you get elected, you can't talk about reading your
lips. You've got to get serious.''
   Seated in his Statehouse office, Dukakis _ who held one press
conference immediately after his loss to assess the campaign _
refused to review the campaign in detail, saying he preferred to
focus on the future.
   But the Democrat also declined to tip his hand about his plans
when his current term as governor runs out in 1990.
   ``It's much too early. At this point, I'm decompressing, working
hard on what's happening here, enjoying a certain amount of normalcy
in my life,'' Dukakis said.
   After a week's vacation in Florida, Dukakis appeared relaxed and
reflective, more interested in his state's budget problems than in
the national agenda he touted before losing to Bush 54 percent to 46
percent.
   ``There's not much sense in re-running the campaign. I mean, we
did some things well, we did other things not so well,'' he said.
``It wasn't successful. Obviously, I'm disappointed. Lots of people
are disappointed. We worked very hard. But I don't think it's
something to dwell on.''
   Dukakis, who had never waged a national campaign before, said his
biggest surprise was the change that overtook him immediately after
the Democratic National Convention in July.
   ``You're spending half your life on the plane,'' he said. ``The
rest of the time it's a combination of the press and the Secret
Service that makes it very difficult for a guy like me, who loves
public life because of the contact you have with people and the
chance to talk. You can't do anymore. Everything you do is a kind of
massive public event.''
   Asked to evaluate Bush's initial appointments and policy
statements, Dukakis said it was too early to draw conclusions.
   However, the governor, who has attacked President Reagan's
Central America policies, said he was pleased by reports that Bush
has decided not to ask Congress immediately for renewed support for
the Contra rebels in Nicaragua and that Bush hopes to forge a
bipartisan consensus and involve Latin leaders.
   ``I think it's the right policy,'' Dukakis said. ``When I met
with him I strongly urged him to do that. I said I think the present
policy is a failure.''
   Dukakis said he would give Bush ``a good six months to a year''
before he would criticize the new president.
   ``Obviously, he's got massive budget and deficit problems. Every
day there's another story saying it's worse,'' he said, citing
saving and loans troubles, farmers' home mortgages and other
budgetary woes.
   ``These are all things that had been deferred. ... He's got to
deal with them,'' Dukakis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
