<DOCNO> AP881222-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PolygamistTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0790 12-22 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0790,a0795,a0800,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polygamist Clan Members Convicted on Reduced Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines urgent series, ADDS six grafs after 6th graf, `The
jury had...' with reaction from widow, clan members, picks up 7th
graf pvs `Prosecutor Creighton...'; ADDS one graf after 14th graf
pvs `The maximum...' to include sentencing date, no pickup. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three members of a polygamist clan were
convicted Thursday on reduced charges ranging from manslaughter to
negligent homicide in the shootout death of a law officer that ended
a 13-day siege of the clan's compound.
   The jury found clan patriarch Addam Swapp, 27, guilty of
manslaughter and his brother, Jonathan Swapp, 21, guilty of
negligent homicide. Their brother-in-law, John Timothy Singer, 22, _
who actually fired the shot from his wheelchair _ was convicted of
manslaughter.
   All three were charged with second-degree murder in the Jan. 28
slaying of Utah Corrections Lt. Fred House, who was gunned down
during a botched arrest attempt as he was directing attack dogs
toward the Swapp brothers. The ensuing firefight ended a 13-day
police siege of the clan's rural, northern Utah farm.
   Jurors deliberated 25{ hours before returning the verdicts in 3rd
District court. The jury got a late start Thursday when Judge
Michael Murphy amended his instructions to allow jurors to consider
lesser charges against Addam Swapp.
   In addition to the second-degree murder charges, jurors were
instructed that they could consider convicting Jonathan Swapp and
Singer on lesser charges including manslaughter and negligent
homicide.
   The jury had begun deliberating Monday night following nine days
of testimony from 51 prosecution and seven defense witnessses,
including Addam Swapp and Jonathan Swapp.
   Ann House, the slain officer's widow, issued a statement saying
she attended the trial to better understand her husband's death.
   ``I know there is sympathy for people who are young, socially
isolated and therefore limited in experience and maturity,'' she
said. ``But when there is planned and continued violence that
results in the death of a police officer, these people can't be let
off easily.''
   Clan members were generally upbeat about the verdicts.
   ``The judge did a fair job,'' said Charlotte Singer Swapp, who
along with her sister, Heidi, is wife to Addam Swapp. ``I'm glad I
got a chance to hug him (Addam Swapp) and that he got to hug the
children,'' she said, referring to Murphy's allowing the clan
patriarch to hold his young sons before being led away.
   Charlotte Swapp said she and Anne Swapp, Jonathan's new bride,
hoped the Swapp brothers would be incarcerated at the same federal
prison so the two wives could share a home nearby.
   Heidi Swapp said that while the trial was fair ``in man's eyes,''
she still prayed for a miracle.
   Prosecutor Creighton Horton told jurors that the defendants
deliberately embraced a course of confrontation that led to House's
death. Defense attorneys countered that clan members, while
well-armed, never intended to hurt anyone and feared police were
looking for an excuse to kill them.
   House was killed and Addam Swapp seriously wounded in the
firefight that ended the standoff at the clan's Marion farm. The
compound was surrounded by an army of 100 FBI-led police Jan. 16,
hours after Addam Swapp, claiming divine inspiration, bombed a
Mormon chapel.
   Prosecutors had maintained that Addam Swapp ``basically declared
war on the church, state and nation'' when he bombed the chapel.
   The trial concluded the second of two prosecutions against clan
members. In May, the three and Vickie Singer, the mother of John
Timothy and Addam Swapp's two wives, were convicted of federal
violations in the standoff.
   In those crimes, Addam Swapp was sentenced to 15 years, John
Timothy Singer and Jonathan Swapp to 10 years and Vickie Singer to
five years.
   Addam Swapp testified in the latest trial that his family's
battle with society had really begun in 1979 when polygamist
patriarch John Singer was gunned down by police during at arrest
attempt at the same farm where clan members barricaded themselves
last January.
   Police said Singer, who had clashed with authorities over his
refusal to send his children to public schools or teach a
state-approved curriculum at home, was shot to death when he pulled
a gun on officers sent to arrest him. Singer's family maintained he
was shot in the back, but a federal judge dismissed a $110 million
wrongful-death suit filed by Mrs. Singer.
   The maximum penalty for second-degree murder is five years to
life in prison. For manslaughter, the maximum term is zero to five
years, and for negligent homicide one year in jail and a $2,500 fine.
   Judge Murphy scheduled sentencing for Jan. 20 and ordered the
trio returned to Salt Lake County Jail in Salt Lake City, 40 miles
to the west, until then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
