<HEAD>Two Men Hold Up Armored Car, Escape With Millions Of Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLIFTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men wearing police uniforms held up an
armored car behind a bank building Thursday and got between $3
million and $5 million in cash, police said.
   The armored car, owned by the Coin Depot Corp. of Elizabeth, was
robbed about 9 a.m. behind the First Fidelity Bank, said James
Knights, a spokesman for the FBI's Newark office.
   The car was dropping off money, said police Capt. James Territo.
   The men tied up the car's three occupants, put them in the back
of the vehicle and drove to an industrial park, where police found
the employees, Knights said. The suspects then switched vehicles and
drove away, Knights said.
   The armored car employees, who were not identified, were found
unharmed after police received a telephone call alerting them that
the car was at the industrial park, Territo said.
   Police were looking for two men who fled in a white van.
   ``We're taking inventory of what was left,'' Territo said. ``They
left coins, which they probably didn't take because of the weight.''
</TEXT>
