<2ND_LINE>AM-Perry Event,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Perry Power Restored Following Radioactive Gas Leak In Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERRY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electric output at the Perry Nuclear Power
Plant was restored to 100 percent Thursday following a seven-hour
decrease prompted when slightly radioactive gas leaked into a
building, a spokesman said.
   Lee Bailey, a spokesman for Cleveland Electric Illuminating Co.,
which runs the plant, said no radioative gas was released into the
atmosphere.
   Three plant workers were exposed to radioactivity but were
checked out and reported fine following Wednesday night's leak,
Bailey said.
   He said power was cut to 70 percent at the plant about 10 p.m.
Wednesday when an alarm disclosed an elevated level of radioactivity
in a building. Full output was restored about 5 a.m. Thursday.
   A leak was found in a seal on a 6-inch pipe that carries
radioactive gas to charcoal filters, Bailey said.
</TEXT>
