<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-VanGogh     12-22 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Van Gogh,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Tycoon Says He Bought World's Most Valuable Painting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businessman Alan Bond said Friday he was
the anonymous buyer of the world's most valuable painting, Vincent
Van Gogh's ``Irises,'' but kept the purchase secret for a year
because he had nowhere to hang it.
   Bond, who won the America's Cup challenge in 1983, said he bought
the oil painting at a Sotheby's auction in New York in November 1987
for a record $50 million but kept the picture under wraps until he
found a place secure enough to satisfy insurers.
   News reports said Bond spent the past year building the most
secure art gallery in Perth, and possibly in all of Australia.
   Bond, who has extensive media and brewery interests, displayed
the painting to reporters on the 49th floor of the R&I Tower,
Perth's tallest skyscraper.
   Since the purchase, Bond said he had received offers for the
masterpiece ``significantly in excess'' of what he paid.
   The Dutch impressionist master painted ``Irises'' in 1889 while
he was in a French asylum.
   Van Gogh is the world's best-selling artist. Five of his
paintings are among the 10 that have fetched the highest prices at
Christie's and Sotheby's auction houses.
   At the time of the sale, Sotheby's said they sold ``Irises'' to
an anonymous buyer for $53.9 million.
</TEXT>
