<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Crash-ThreatPrecedent 2ndLd-Writethru a0789 12-22 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Threat Precedent, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0789,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am Bomb Warning Recalls Similar Incident in 1986</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS headline to correct</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disclosure that a caller had warned that
someone would unwittingly carry a bomb aboard a Pan Am flight from
Frankfurt to New York recalled an attempt to bomb an Israeli
airliner in 1986.
   Although cause of the Pan Am crash Wednesday in Scotland had not
been determined, investigators were examining terrorist threats and
evidence that the plane exploded in the air before its crashed,
killing 280 people, 258 of them on the plane and the rest on the
ground.
   Jordanian-born Nezar Hindawi was condemned on Oct. 24, 1986 to 45
years in prison for handing booby-trapped hand baggage to his
unwitting pregnant Irish girlfriend as she prepared to board an El
Al flight on April 17 that year.
   An El Al guard found the bomb as the woman, Ann-Marie Murphy,
passed through security. British officials said it consisted of
three pounds of Czechoslovakian-made plastic explosive hidden behind
a luggage panel and likely would have killed all 375 passengers
aboard the EL Al Boeing 747.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Thursday that on
Dec. 5 an anonymous caller told the U.S. Embassy in Finland that a
Pan Am flight would be bombed. She said ``an unidentified person in
Helsinki would unwittingly take the device to Frankfurt and
eventually onto the U.S.-bound flight.''
   However, the department's top counterterrorism official said in a
television interview that it was still not clear whether Pan Am
flight 103 had fallen victim to terrorism, and that authorities
frequently received detailed threats that turned out to be false.
   ``In fact, ever since this method was tried and thwarted on an El
Al plane in London two years ago, we've had a number of times people
come to us saying that someone in an unsuspecting way is going to
carry a bomb on a plane. So it's not unusual to have that kind of
specificity in a threat,'' L. Paul Bremer said in an interview on
Cable News Network.
   Mrs. Oakley said the caller told embassy officials that the
individuals who would provide the device would have ties to Abu
Nidal, leader of a radical Palestinian faction.
   Another source said the caller claimed the bomb would be carried
by a woman.
   The Finnish Foreign Ministry said in a statement Thursday that an
Arab resident had made several bomb threats during the year, most
recently on Dec. 5, but that ``in the investigation so far, no
direct connection has been found between the Arab living in Finland
and the air accident in question.''
   The statement said authorities knew the caller's identity and
that he had not left Finland since Dec. 5.
   The sentence handed down in the El Al case in 1986 was the
longest ever in a British court.
   During the trial, the prosecution presented evidence that Hindawi
entered Britain in late January 1986 on a Syrian diplomatic passport
with a false name, and that his visa applications had been endorsed
by Syrian foreign ministry officials.
   The prosecution presented evidence that Hindawi, then 32, was
acting in concert with Syria for a group called the Jordan
Revolutionary Movement. He allegedly received help from the chief of
Syrian Air Force intelligence, Gen. Mohammed Khouli, an aide to
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Hindawi's former fiancee, Miss Murphy, testified during the
trial, breaking into tears and accusing the defendant of intending
to kill her and their unborn child. The baby, a girl, was born in
July.
   After the bomb was discovered, Hindawi fled to the Syrian
Embassy, where according to the prosecution he met with Syrian
Ambassador Loutof Haydar. Hindawi was then taken to a Syrian safe
house in London, where Syrian embassy employees cut and dyed his
hair. However, he fled in fear and turned himself in to police.
   The incident prompted Britain to sever diplomatic ties with
Syria, and other members of the European Common Market imposed trade
and diplomatic sanctions against that nation in October 1986. The
measures were lifted the following July after Western officials
concluded that Syria had curtailed its support for terrorism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
