<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Benjamin ADV03   12-22 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Benjamin, ADV 03,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adv 03</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Jan 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A $20 Million Movie Dropped Into His Lap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A old friend happened to drive by Richard
Benjamin's house and drop a $20 million movie in his lap.
   At least that's the way Benjamin tells how he became involved
with ``My Stepmother Was an Alien,'' the year-end release starring
Dan Aykroyd and Kim Basinger. It helps that the old friend was Jerry
Weintraub, founder of the ``instant major'' film company, Weintraub
Entertainment.
   ``Jerry drove down my street one day as I was getting into my
car,'' Benjamin relates. ``He stopped me and said, `I got this
script. You got to do it. I'm not going to take no for an answer.'
   ``It's hard to say no to Jerry. I thought that when somebody
pulls you over, gets out of a car and stands on a street corner,
that's the way you should make a deal.''
   Benjamin had already read a half-finished version of
``Stepmother'' two years before and had admired it.
   ``There's something terrifically real about a little girl saying
to her dad, `But she's from another planet!' And the dad saying,
`Now she's going to be your new mother. Tell me you don't like her
cooking, but don't tell me she's from another planet.' There's
something psychologically right about that,'' he said.
   Benjamin signed on as director. Having directed ``My Favorite
Year,'' ``City Heat,'' ``Racing With the Moon,'' ``The Money Pit''
and ``Little Nikita,'' he now entered the whole new world of special
effects.
   ``John Dykstra and his company, Apogee, that did the special
effects are awesome because they can do anything,'' he said. ``They
would say, `Here's what we think it should be. But what would you
like? This spaceship could be anything you want. The characters can
be anywhere you want them.'
   ``You had to use your imagination, and then you had to be
responsible to that imagination because they could execute it.''
   Aykroyd entered the project early. A ``Saturday Night Live''
alumnus, he is part of the new breed of film comedy actor.
   ``They work fast, and they don't like to do a lot of rehearsal,''
Benjamin observed. ``Neither does Kim, so that was all right.
   ``When we started, Dan said, `Do you want me to put anything else
in, or do you just want the words in the script?' I said, `If you
want to say something, just say it.' I used to keep the camera
rolling at the end of a scene and just let him go. A lot of that
stuff is in the movie.''
   Although he doesn't appear in ``Stepmother,'' Benjamin did a lot
of acting on the set. The reason: he had to portray the special
effects that would be inserted later.
   ``The actors were looking at me with a stick that said `Ship,' ''
explained the director. ``I said, `Now this thing is coming out of
the stars! It's beautiful! It's magnificent! It's awesome!' Then
there are these great superbeings in the sky, and I'm standing on a
ladder doing them.''
   Except for a few gray hairs, Dick Benjamin at 49 still possesses
the preppie look he first displayed in ``Goodbye, Columbus.'' New
York-born, he attended the famed High School for the Performing
Arts, then studied drama at Northwestern University, where he met
his wife, Paula Prentiss.
   After establishing himself in Neil Simon plays (``Barefoot in the
Park,'' ``The Odd Couple,'' ``Star Spangled Girl''), Benjamin made
his film debut in ``Goodbye, Columbus.'' He also appeared in another
Philip Roth story, ``Portnoy's Complaint,'' as well as ``Catch 22,''
``Diary of a Mad Housewife,'' ``Westworld'' and ``Love at First
Bite.''
   He started directing in school and liked it, but his acting
career took over. As a film actor, he repeatedly complained to
Prentiss about mistakes his directors made.
   Her response: ``You ought to put up or shut up.'' Her agent, Phil
Gersh, helped him make the transition.
   ``Yes, I miss acting,'' Benjamin admitted. ``I'd like to do it
again. But it takes at least a year and a half to prepare and direct
a movie, so I just can't find the time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Jan. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
