<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:EriktheViking ADV06   12-22 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Erik the Viking, ADV 06,0645</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, Jan 6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Claudia: Photos available showing Rooney, Jones and Robbins
^Comic Plunder, Viking-Style</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHEPPERTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a soundstage west of London, Mickey
Rooney is sporting a fur shawl, a shaggy white wig _ and a scar on
his forehead.
   It's only makeup, explains the sprightly actor, who's a bit fuzzy
on the details of the script. ``Somebody whacked me, I think, with a
club or a stick or a bat.''
   Rooney, 68, who is in London repeating his starring role in the
Broadway musical ``Sugar Babies,'' picked up a six-day contract to
star among a band of medieval thugs in ``Erik the Viking,'' a $15
million movie which will be released by Orion Pictures next summer.
   The author and director, former Monty Python trouper Terry Jones,
also plays the role of King Arnulf.
   Tim Robbins, the acclaimed sidekick of last summer's hit film
``Bull Durham,'' is the adventurous Erik, on a quest to graduate
from barbarian to nice guy. Rooney plays his grandfather, singer
Eartha Kitt is the soothsayer Freya and John Cleese, another former
Python, is Erik's nemesis, Halfdan the Black.
   The movie is based on a collection of 28 stories about the
fictional Erik which Jones wrote for his young son, Bill.
   Jones, 46, will be remembered by Python fans as the black-haired
one who would play plump old matrons with shrieking voices. With the
breakup of the troupe, he has gone on to directorial fame with
``Personal Services.''
   He says his latest film is less a children's story than an
extension of the ``Indiana Jones'' sagas, which combine comedy,
fantasy and adventure.
   ``It's the kind of thing I would enjoy seeing,'' said the
Oxford-educated Welshman, who was busy on the set one recent day
marshaling characters with Pythonesque names such as Sven the
Berserk, Ulf the Maddeningly Calm and Lief the Lucky.
   Jones was shooting the final scene in which the Dark Ages, the
so-called Age of Ragnarok, come to a triumphant end with the sudden
emergence of the sun _and enlightenment for Erik.
   The setting is the Vikings' home village of Valhalla in Norway, a
community marked by constant winter and warfare. The film begins
with a rape followed by plenty of the kind of bloodshed and
dismemberment familiar to Python addicts.
   Jones knows he is courting outcry from campaigners against screen
violence, but says, ``There's violence in life. I don't think that's
what corrupting. When people glory in violence I get disturbed.''
   The film spent four weeks on location in Malta creating an
enchanted island called Hy-Brasil, but a decision was made against
location shooting in Norway in favor of studio work.
   Rooney was eager to make clear he isn't taking his role too
seriously.
   ``It's a lot of fun being with John Cleese and Terry,'' he said
in an interview. ``I haven't even read the script; I don't know
anything about it. I like good humor; I'm a guy that loves good
humor.
   ``And I love the money.''
   Producer John Goldstone said that unlike the Monty Python skits,
the Viking movie is a real story with a beginning, a middle, and an
end. Goldstone first worked with Jones in 1974 on ``Monty Python and
the Holy Grail,'' which cost just 229,000 pounds (then about
$535,000).
   ``Erik the Viking'' is the last of three films made by Python
alumni in the past 12 months. Cleese's ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' was
a summer box-office hit, and Terry Gilliam's ``The Adventures of
Baron Munchausen,'' has just opened in West Germany to mixed reviews.
   ``We'd like to have three successful films,'' said Jones, ``but
one mustn't count one's chickens.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Jan. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
