<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:Cooney ADV30   12-22 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Cooney, ADV 30,0669</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, Dec 30 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>London's Longest-Running Comedy Prepares For Broadway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ray Cooney's ``Run for Your Wife,'' the
longest-running comedy on the London stage, is Broadway-bound after
six years on the West End.
   ``It's so readily acceptable; that's what people relate to,''
Cooney, 56, said of his farce about a bigamous taxi driver.
   ``It can be summed up so simply,'' he said. ``People can
understand the dilemma of an innocent guy who, because he didn't
have the heart to say no, has got two wives.''
   Cooney last went to Broadway with his 1967 London hit ``Not Now,
Darling,'' but it closed after just six weeks.
   ``Run for Your Wife'' starts previews at New York's Virginia
Theater Feb. 22, opening March 7, after a tryout stint Jan. 17 to
Feb. 19 at the Coconut Grove Playhouse in Miami.
   Cooney directs and stars alongside Paxton Whitehead, an alumnus
of the hit Broadway and London farce ``Noises Off.''
   After such successes as ``Move Over, Mrs. Markham,'' co-written
with John Chapman, ``Two Into One'' and ``Wife Begins at Forty,''
Cooney believes he is ready to try Broadway again.
   ``My plays are pure situation,'' he said. ``There are no local
jokes.''
   ``Run for Your Wife'' has been slated for Broadway for years, and
Cooney has directed it in productions in New Jersey with David
McCallum, in Baltimore with Bob Dishy and at Oakbrook, outside
Chicago.
   But Cooney said only now had talent and script meshed properly.
Under a special agreement with the American actors' union, Equity,
three British actors will appear in the play for four months on
Broadway, at which point the five Americans completing the New York
line-up will transfer to the London production at the Criterion
Theater.
   While emphasizing his play is a farce, Cooney said ``Run for Your
Wife'' had a darker underside.
   ``My farces are really inverted tragedies,'' said Cooney, a
London-born carpenter's son who left school when he was 14 to become
an actor.
   ``If the story of this bigamist had been written by Tennessee
Williams, it would be a tragedy,'' said Cooney, pointing out that
his twice-married cabbie has committed a criminal offense for which
he could go to jail.
   ``If you're going to write a pure, for want of a better word,
farce, I think it does need to have tragedy at its core.''
   ``Run for Your Wife'' will be one of several farces on Broadway
this season. Neil Simon's ``Rumors'' surmounted mixed reviews to
become a smash hit at the Broadhurst Theater.
   Ken Ludwig's ``Lend Me a Tenor,'' an American comedy which ran
successfully in London, opens at the Royale Theater the night before
``Run for Your Wife.''
   Cooney said the best farce has a strong basic plot.
   ``All my plays take place in real time and usually start at quite
a high dramatic point. There's a lot at stake (for the characters)
in them.''
   Because he's wearing a triple cap, the play's budget is $600,000,
unusually low for Broadway. It breaks even at 36 percent of capacity
and, with full houses, can recoup its investment in just six weeks.
   ``If Broadway's going to have plays produced there, everybody's
got to chip in,'' said Cooney, who is forgoing all royalties for a
share of the profits.
   Regardless of whether ``Run for Your Wife'' runs, Cooney's next
play is ready to go. ``It Runs in the Family'' is a comedy about an
adolescent who at age 18 discovers his father's true identity.
   He said the play, to open on the West End next fall, was ``at
heart, a drama.''
   ``I just happen to write these plays because I see the funny side
of the dramas around us,'' he said. ``I have a feeling there's
enough depressing news when I switch the TV on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri Dec. 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
