<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv23   12-22 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 23,0780</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday Dec. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Former IBMer Determined to Put UNC Business School On Map</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Business Analyst John Cunniff is on vacation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former IBM Corp. Vice Chairman Paul Rizzo
wants to put the business school at the University of North Carolina
at Chapel Hill on the map, and even has hired a public relations
firm to help promote the school.
   ``This school ... has been able to attract quality students
without promoting itself,'' he said. ``This no longer works. When
our students come here, one of the first things they want to know is
our placement record.''
   When he became dean of the school, Rizzo said his top priority
was to make the school a vital cog in the state's business
community. But as any successful executive knows, first things first.
   ``If we're going to compete, we need to play the game,'' said the
1950 graduate of UNC who lined up in the same backfield as Charlie
``Choo Choo'' Justice on the Tar Heel football team. ``We don't want
to be second-rate.''
   Rizzo was impressed with the faculty when he took the job in
September 1987. At the same time, he understood why some had left.
   ``With all of the problems of a state university, including the
bureaucracy and underfunding, we have still managed to build a high
quality faculty,'' he said in a recent telephone interview from his
office in Chapel Hill. ``We're in danger of losing them.''
   Rizzo said money was only one reason why talented professors were
leaving the school for other opportunities. That's why he is the
chief proponent of a plan to construct a new home for the business
school at a cost of between $20 million and $30 million.
   ``We've got a major-league faculty with a bush-league facility,''
he said. ``A new building would be practically and symbolically very
important.
   ``Just like a good medical school, a business school can't be
successful without significant clinical activity,'' he said. ``Other
business schools may be too lavish, but if we're going to conduct
programs with the corporate world, we need adequate facilities.''
   Despite those obstacles, the business school recently was ranked
No. 8 in the country in a poll of 3,000 MBAs conducted by
BusinessWeek magazine.
   Rizzo has put his stamp on the school's curriculum, giving it
what he described as a ``global perspective.''
   ``A globalization of the curriculum is not unique to this
business school,'' he said, explaining that any reputable business
school could not ignore the study of international business in the
late 1980s.
   The school also has introduced the International Executive
Series, a program which brings in business leaders from such
countries as Japan and the Soviet Union, as well as prominent
American corporate executives who have worked overseas.
   The first lecture last month was given by Kenichi Ohmae,
management director of McKinsey & Co. of Tokyo. The subject: ``Do
Trade Deficits Really Matter in a Global Economy?''
   Other speakers include V.F. Lishchenko of the Academy of Sciences
of the U.S.S.R. in Moscow; S. Parker Gilbert, chairman of Morgan
Stanley Group Inc.; Johnson & Johnson Chief Executive Officer James
Burke; IBM Corp. Chairman and CEO John Akers; and John Welch,
chairman of General Electric.
   Rizzo wants to encourage more faculty and students from the
business school to work and study abroad, and he wants to bring in
more foreigners to teach and study at the school.
   ``The impact of culture on business is important,'' he said.
``Just learning the language is not enough. We need to develop an
appreciation for the things we don't understand because we lack the
cultural background.''
   For example, he said, the conversation at a business lunch in
some European countries may focus on music or literature, not the
latest leveraged buyout or stock tip.
   ``It's easy to pick up the phone and do business in this country
because we speak the same language,'' Rizzo said. ``Building
relationships in other countries can be difficult. We need people
groping and struggling to do business effectively in the foreign
marketplace.''
   The school's reputation seems to be improving, as evidenced by
its move up in the BusinessWeek rankings from the top 15 last year
to the top 10. In addition, a Washington, D.C., public relations
firm, Peabody Fitzpatrick Communications Inc., is hard at work
promoting the international lecture series among other projects.
   ``To be this good, given all the drawbacks we have, is
remarkable,'' Rizzo said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday Dec. 23</NOTE>
