<DOCNO> AP881222-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:DisneyMusic ADV28   12-22 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Disney Music, ADV 28,0889</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Dec 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Disney Music With a Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney's animated features and G-rated
movies were always a sure thing for parents: They didn't have to
worry about what their children would see.
   But Hal Willner's record of Disney songs should probably carry
the label Parental Guidance Advised.
   Willner has produced ``Stay Awake,'' an album featuring
arrangements of tunes from Disney movies by such musicians and song
stylists as Ringo Starr, James Taylor, Sinead O'Connor, Los Lobos
and Yma Sumac.
   ``Your memories of Disney films are usually very wholesome,''
said Willner. ``You remember the sweetness. But these are very
dramatic movies. `Bambi' has every element: birth, death, happiness,
fear. It's amazing.
   ``These films do show the dark side of life.''
   And just to prove his point, the 32-year-old Willner has given
``Stay Awake'' a generous mix of happy and sad songs. Along with
Aaron Neville's upbeat ``Mickey Mouse March'' and Garth Hudson's
sunny ``Feed the Birds'' (``Mary Poppins'') are Tom Waits' eerie
``Heigh Ho (The Dwarfs Marching Song)'' and a chilling version by
O'Connor of ``Someday My Prince Will Come,'' both from ``Snow White
and the Seven Dwarfs.''
   ``I have heard other Disney tributes,'' Willner said, ``but no
one was exploring that other stuff.''
   ``Stay Awake'' is Willner's fourth compilation record. His others
include ``Amarcord Nino Rota,'' which paid tribute to the man who
scored many of Federico Fellini's films; ``That's the Way I Feel
Now,'' a collection of Thelonius Monk songs, and ``Lost in the
Stars,'' the music of Kurt Weill.
   He did not intend to make a series of compilation LPs, but his
inspiration seemed to run in that direction. Attending a concert of
Monk's music at Carnegie Hall, he was so bored by how the great
jazzman's songs were being played he decided to put together a
tribute of his own.
   Willner's decision to make the ``Stay Awake'' record also came
about spontaneously. He had purchased an anthology back in the
mid-1970s, played it for about a week and then put it away.
   But the album remained on his shelf, and when he started thumbing
through his collection in search of another project, ``angel voices
sang,'' he said, as he came upon the Disney record.
   Finding artists wasn't a problem, since he had made broad
contacts through his previous records. The trick was fitting them
together in a coherent album. So opening with Ken Nordine's ``Hi
Diddle Dee Dee'' (``Pinocchio'') and finishing up with Ringo Starr
crooning ``When You Wish Upon a Star'' (``Pinocchio''), Willner
takes his listeners through a bumpy ride on ``The Wonderful World of
Disney.''
   The performers were selected from around the world. From Los
Angeles came Bonnie Raitt, who sings ``Baby Mine'' (``Dumbo'') with
the funk group ``Was (Not Was).''
   ``Don Was' son had the copy of the Dumbo soundtrack,'' Willner
said. ``We sat around his house one night and kicked around the
names of singers we liked a great deal, and Bonnie was one of them.''
   Willner got Van Dyke Parks and Harry Nilsson to visit Starr in
England and persuade the ex-Beatle to sing on the record.
   ``One of the first guys I thought of was Ringo,'' Willner said.
``I remembered `Goodnight' from the (Beatles') `White Album.' It's
not a conventional singing voice, but it works.''
   O'Connor's appearance on ``Stay Awake'' (``Mary Poppins'') came
about when Willner visited Dublin at the end of 1987.
   ``I saw her on television and I went, `Aaaah.' I thought, `Boy,
would that be great if she could do `Prince Will Come.'''
   And to Willner's surprise, O'Connor readily agreed, completing an
acoustic version of the song in one take.
   Back in the United States, he recruited the Minnesota-based rock
group The Replacements, who performed a stomping version of
``Cruella De Ville'' (``101 Dalmatians'').
   ``We got in touch with them. They were on and off the record
three times, but at the last minute, they decided it was a cool
project.''
   In New York, Willner got Suzanne Vega through A&M Records, which
issued ``Stay Awake,'' and met James Taylor at a party.
   ``He got up and sang this old ballad and it was so beautiful. And
I talked to him and told him about the record. I always did like
James Taylor's voice.''
   Taylor sang ``Second Star to the Right'' (``Peter Pan'') and the
list goes on and on: jazz singer Betty Carter covering ``I'm
Wishing'' (``Snow White''); R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe, 10,000 Maniac's
Natalie Merchant and the Roches combining on ``Little April Shower''
(``Bambi''); Nilsson singing ``Zip-A-Dee-Doo-Dah'' (``Song of the
South'').
   ``I had to stop the record sometime,'' Willner said. ``You can't
keep recording forever.''
   But Willner can keep making records. Next might be a tribute to
the late composer, pianist and orchestra leader Duke Ellington. But
fans will have to be patient.
   ``Producing leaves you open to ulcers because you have to get the
best performance possible,'' the producer said. ``I love the final
product, but the process is very hard emotionally. It's an average
of one every two years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
