<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0563</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street giant Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has
agreed to plead guilty to six federal felony counts and pay a record
$650 million fine to settle the biggest securities fraud case in
history.
   Company spokesman Steven Anreder said Wednesday that Drexel's
board of directors ``concluded that this settlement is in the best
interest of our firm and our employees.''
   The settlement capped more than two years of intense
investigation into the financial inner dealings of the nation's
fifth-largest investment firm, which has played roles in some of the
biggest corporate takeovers of the decade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has indicted Paul A. Bilzerian, a
well-known takeover speculator accused of lying to the government
and illegally hiding stock in connection with four
multimillion-dollar transactions in 1985 and 1986.
   The St. Petersburg, Fla.-based Bilzerian, who became head of the
defense contractor Singer Co. last February after a $1.06 billion
takeover fight, was indicted Wednesday on 12 counts of fraud.
   Bilzerian immediately denied wrongdoing and blamed the indictment
on what he called overzealous prosecutors seizing on the growing
concern about corporate takeovers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income rose strongly in
both November and October after adjusting to exclude distortions
from surges in farm subsidies and auto workers' bonuses, the
government reports.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that income fell a slight
0.2 percent in November to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
$4.18 trillion, following a jump of 1.7 percent in October, the
biggest in a year.
   Excluding the one-time distortions, personal income rose 0.6
percent in November and 0.8 percent in October, both significantly
stronger than the inflation rate during that time.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has unveiled its
new tax forms with the news that, unlike last year, the forms
feature few changes.
   IRS officials said Wednesday that 101 million Americans should
begin receiving their forms by next week.
   IRS officials said taxpayers will be able to use their 1987 tax
returns as a guide to filing out the new forms.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover guru Henry Kravis is asking the Japanese
for help in financing his firm's record $24.53 billion buyout of RJR
Nabisco Inc., and is making a sales pitch for the ``junku bondos''
to be issued as part of the deal.
   Kravis, principal of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., and
representatives from Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. met for about two
hours Wednesday with 240 investment bankers and institutional
investors in Tokyo.
   In a separate development, a congressional panel revealed it has
launched a broad investigation into the Nabisco buyout, and the
adequacy of securities laws in handling such deals.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. Chairman Philip L. Smith, who
arrived at the food and restaurant giant less than four months ago,
could depart nearly $8 million richer under the pending takeover by
Grand Metropolitan PLC.
   The British conglomerate is expected to take control of Pillsbury
early next year and release Smith.
   Smith's tenure was dominated by Pillsbury's unsuccessful battle
against Grand Met's hostile takeover attempt, which ended Sunday
with Pillsbury accepting a negotiated offer of $5.7 billion, or $66
a share.
</TEXT>
