<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government ran up a $29.0 billion
budget deficit in November, 7.4 percent bigger than the red ink
recorded a year earlier.
   The Treasury Department said Wednesday that revenue of $64.4
billion last month was $7.4 billion higher than a year earlier, but
spending rose an even heftier $9.4 billion to $93.4 billion.
   But for the first two months of the 1989 fiscal year, which began
Oct. 1, the budget gap was 2.4 percent lower than the same period in
fiscal 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of Johnson Matthey PLC, the world's
largest platinum refiner, have brushed aside suggestions that the
company acted improperly in failing to disclose that it knew of Ford
Motor Co.'s plans to develop platinum-free catalytic converters.
   The refiner also reiterated on Wednesday its previous bullish
forecast for platinum demand.
   The forecast had buoyed the market before Ford Chairman Donald
Peterson's announcement of the converter last Wednesday sent
platinum prices crashing the following morning.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission, bowing
to the will of Congress, has extended to 24 hours a day its ban on
sexually explicit broadcasts, though one commissioner said she had
``serious doubts'' about the constitutionality of the new rule.
   Radio and television broadcasters and free-speech advocates have
said they will challenge Wednesday's change, which was ordered by
Congress as part of an appropriations package earlier this year.
   The new rule is to take effect 30 days after it is published in
the Federal Register.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are descending upon stores across the
country in last-minute Christmas shopping forays, which is good news
for retailers looking for an eleventh-hour sales boost.
   But it's also bad news _ for consumers who are discovering that
some of the items they want are out of stock.
   ``We're definitely having a rush here,'' Kristine King, a
spokeswoman at Macy's in the Houston Galleria, said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They stand up, they sing, they flicker on and off.
   Ingenuity and high technology have led to some unusual Christmas
cards, which retailers say are a big hit with Japanese holiday
shoppers this year.
   Take, for example, the card that unfolds into an upright
Christmas tree, complete with blinking red lights and a two-tune
repertoire of ``Rudolph the Red-nosed Reindeer'' and ``Santa Claus
Is Coming to Town.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly Wednesday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials slipped 1.43 points to 2,164.64.
   The dollar fell in light, uneventful trading. Gold prices rose
slightly.
   Bond prices edged higher.
   Platinum futures prices rose; coffee futures gained; grains and
soybeans were higher; cattle futures advanced while pork futures
were mixed; energy futures were mixed; and stock-index futures
retreated.
</TEXT>
