<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     12-22 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personal Incomes Up Strongly After Adjustments</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with Commerce Department November durable goods
orders report scheduled for 8:30 a.m. EST release.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income rose strongly in November and October,
the government reported, but financial markets shrugged off the news.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that personal income fell
a slight 0.2 percent in November to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $4.18 trillion, following a jump of 1.7 percent in October,
the biggest in a year.
   However, the October figure was distorted by surges in farm
subsidies and auto workers' bonuses, the agency said. Excluding
those factors, personal income rose 0.6 percent in November and 0.8
percent in October, both significantly stronger than the inflation
rate.
   The department also said personal consumption spending, which
includes everything except interest payments on debt, rose 0.6
percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $3.32 trillion last
month after a robust 1.0 percent gain in October.
   The numbers were in line with expectations and had little effect
on financial markets. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average, down 6.61 on Tuesday, slipped another 1.43 points to
2,164.64.
   Bond prices and interest rates were little changed.
   ``It looks like 1988 is going out with a bang,'' said Robert
Brusca, an economist with Nikko Securities Co. International Inc. in
reference to the income and spending report.
   But Brusca said the new statistics were likely to displease the
Federal Reserve Board, which has been raising interest rates in an
attempt to slow the economy.
   The Fed's goals are to slow inflation and to cool domestic
consumer demand so manufacturers can produce enough exports to
whittle the U.S. trade deficit.
   With spending rising faster than income in November, the personal
savings rate _ savings as a percentage of after-tax income _ dipped
to 4.3 percent from 5.2 percent in October. Economists say one way
to curb the trade deficit is to increase Americans' savings.
   Disposable, or after-tax, income declined 0.3 percent in November
following a 1.7 percent gain a month earlier. It was the first
decline since April.
   Wages and salaries, key components of personal income, were up
0.4 percent to a $2.52 trillion annual rate in November following a
large 1.5 percent increase caused by bonuses to auto workers.
Manufacturing salaries edged down 0.5 percent after a 2.2 percent
increase in October.
   The biggest increase in spending last month was for durable
goods, ``big ticket'' items expected to last three or more years.
The category rose 1.5 percent, followed by a 0.6 percent increase
for non-durable goods and a 0.3 percent rise in spending for
services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-22 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures have closed higher, taking
strength from a surge in crude oil prices the previous session.
   The February contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 15 cents Wednesday to settle at $16.30 a
barrel in New York Mercantile Exchange trading. On Tuesday, the
contract rose 33 cents.
   Wednesday's gains in energy futures were ``tremors and
aftershocks after the earthquake yesterday,'' said Jim Fiedler, an
analyst with E.D.&F. Man International Futures Inc.
   He referred to a $1.42 a barrel gain Tuesday in the expiring
January contract for West Texas Intermediate crude. That pushed the
January contract to $17.73 a barrel.
   Analysts said the January advance was due to technical buying by
a trader who was caught short and was forced to buy January
contracts to close out a position. The advance lent support to
trading Wednesday in contracts for subsequent months, they said.
   Peter Beutel, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc., said reports
that members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
would meet with non-OPEC oil producers also supported prices.
   Members of the cartel are hoping the non-OPEC nations will bring
their production and pricing in line with OPEC's. OPEC members last
month agreed to limit their production in the first half of 1989 in
order to boost world crude prices.
   Among refined products traded on the mercantile exchange, the
January contract for unleaded gasoline settled at 45.70 cents a
gallon Wednesday, up 0.15 cent from the close Tuesday.
   January wholesale home heating oil rose 0.45 cent to 51.92 cents
a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
