<DOCNO> AP881222-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0127EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Platinum Bjt   12-22 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Platinum, Bjt,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Johnson Matthey Rebuffs Suggestions of Impropriety on Platinum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum refining giant Johnson Matthey PLC says
it wasn't improper that it didn't disclose its knowledge of Ford
Motor Co.'s plans to develop platinum-free catalytic converters.
   Last week's announcement by Ford that the converter was being
tested sent platinum futures tumbling in a market that had been made
bullish up to that point by the British refiner's forecasts of
strong platinum demand.
   Johnson Matthey, the world's largest platinum refiner, on
Wednesday reiterated its bullish forecasts and top company officials
shrugged off suggestions that the company acted improperly in not
disclosing its advance knowledge of the device.
   Johnson Matthey not only supplies Ford with platinum, but also
said it had collaborated on the development of the device.
   Some market analysts believed Johnson Matthey had a moral
obligation to disclose its knowledge of Ford's plan.
   But three officials of the British company, who rushed from
London to New York to give a press briefing, rebuffed suggestions of
impropriety.
   ``We don't believe that's an issue,'' said Kevin Gibbons, general
manager of international marketing for Johnson Matthey.
   Gibbons said the company wants to be a ``responsible supplier''
to its customers.
   Johnson Matthey also sells platinum to General Motors Corp.,
Chrysler Corp., Volkswagen of West Germany, Britain's Jaguar and
other big automakers.
   But one metals analyst said Johnson Matthey's failure to disclose
it knew of the project was ``over the line of what was proper and
moral.''
   Gibbons and the other two officials expressed surprise that the
platinum market reacted so strongly to Ford's sketchy announcement
about the experimental device for controlling auto pollution.
   Platinum for current delivery closed last Thursday at $531.90 a
troy ounce on the New York Mercantile Exchange, down $70 an ounce
from Wednesday's close. The heavily traded contract for January
delivery dropped the daily limit of $25 during that session. There
is no limit on the spot contract.
   On Wednesday, platinum settled $6.60 to $8.10 higher on the New
York Mercantile Exchange with the spot December contract at $542.40
a troy ounce and the more active contract for delivery in January at
$538.40 a troy ounce.
   Analysts linked Wednesday's rally to buying by bargain hunters
whose confidence was bolstered by Johnson Matthey's statements.
   In a statement, Johnson Matthey called the market's negative
reaction last week ``exaggerated'' and ``inconsistent with the
technical possibilities'' of Ford's new catalyst. The feasibility of
the catalyst for wide use has yet to be proven, the company said.
   Ford has said it plans to test the device on 40,000 to 50,000 new
Ford Thunderbirds and Mercury Cougars sold in California, a state
with the toughest air quality standards in the nation.
   The Johnson Matthey officials reiterated their bullish forecast
for platinum, which first was published Nov. 15 in a 24-page review.
   In that report, the company predicted a supply shortfall for
platinum for the next five years, including a record 465,000-ounce
shortfall this year.
   Platinum is an essential element in automobile pollution-control
systems. The metal, in conjunction with certain other metals, acts
as a catalyst in chemical reactions that convert harmful exhaust
pollutants into harmless carbon dioxide and water. This process
occurs inside metal boxes called catalytic converters that have been
required since 1975 on all cars sold in the United States.
   Johnson Matthey said it expected the use of platinum in catalytic
converters in 1988 to account for nearly 75 percent of platinum
demand in North America and for more than a third of world demand
for the metal.
   The refiner also said new pollution standards in Europe would
contribute to a steady increase in global platinum demand for the
next six years.
   ``Platinum is and will remain overwhelmingly the prime metal for
use in cleaning up automobile exhaust gases,'' the company said in
the statement issued Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
