<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-Kenosha Bjt   12-22 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Kenosha, Bjt,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Car Rolls Off Line At Chrysler Kenosha Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final car made at the Kenosha auto plant
has rolled off the Chrysler Corp. assembly line, followed by the
layoffs of another 700 Chrysler workers as automaking neared its end
here after 86 years.
   United Auto Workers Local 72 president Ed Steagall said the final
car, a maroon Omni subcompact, rolled out about 2:30 p.m. Wednesday.
   ``There are some who are sad and other people were crying _ and
still others were relieved to know that the stress was ending, the
awaited plant closing was here,'' said Steagall, who spent the
morning with workers in the final assembly division.
   The workers laid off Wednesday were among nearly 4,000 to lose
jobs since Friday, Steagall said. He said only 300 to 500 more
remained in the plant to close down operations and strip equipment
in preparation for Friday's formal closing.
   Chrysler, which bought the plant from the former American Motors
Corp. in 1987, announced in January it would end car production
here, eliminating 5,300 jobs. The company will continue operating a
Kenosha engine plant with about 1,000 employees.
   Those who worked on the final car began emerging from the Gate 6
plant exit at mid-afternoon. Many went straight to gather with
friends at local taverns.
   ``It just got quieter and quieter as the jobs closed down along
the line and people were allowed to leave,'' said Barbara Schneider,
a worker in final assembly and 14-year veteran at the plant. ``By
the time the car was ready it was so quiet it was almost
depressing.''
   She said workers no longer were bitter but were sad about having
to leave their ``expanded family.''
   The impact of the plant closing would be more noticeable as she
and other dislocated workers begin looking for new jobs, she said.
   ``I raised my kids working here and now they've grown up and now
I'm going to be looking for a new job in the same market that my
kids are entering,'' Schneider said. ``I'm going to be competing
against my kids to get a job.''
   Kitty Koski, a 10-year employee, said leaving behind the memories
of working in the same plant that her parents did would be more
difficult than finding a new job.
   ``e solidarity, the friendship and tut you're not going to find
the solidarity, the friendship and the pride that workers have
here,'' she said.
   Her husband, Wayne, a 15-year plant employee, was one of the last
people to work on the final Omni.
   ``We just jacked up the engine, put it in the car and we left,''
he said.
   Chrysler officials did not allow reporters or photographers into
the plant to watch the final cars processed, but Steagall said many
workers brought their own cameras and video cameras to photograph
the work on the last cars.
   Automaking in Kenosha began when Thomas P. Jeffrey Co. built its
one-cylinder Rambler in 1902. The Jeffrey Co. became Nash Motors
Corp. in 1918, then Nash-Kelvinator in 1937 and American Motors in
1954.
   Citing the age and inefficiency of its Kenosha plant, Chrysler
told state officials Jan. 27 that it would shut down the operation.
   State officials threatened to sue Chrysler, saying the No. 3
automaker had promised verbally to keep the plant open through 1992
in exchange for $5 million in state job training money.
   Chrysler later reached an out-of-court settlement taht included
$250 million in aid to workers, the community and the state.
</TEXT>
