<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ChristmasShopping Bjt   12-22 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Christmas Shopping, Bjt,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last-Minute Shopping Push Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's retailers are getting a sales boost
as millions of Americans crowd into stores and malls for last-minute
Christmas shopping expeditions.
   Meanwhile, many of the procrastinators are getting an unwelcome
surprise: Some of the gifts they want were snapped up by the early
birds and are now out of stock.
   ``We're definitely having a rush here,'' Kristine King, a
spokeswoman at Macy's in the Houston Galleria, said Wednesday.
``We've seen a tremendous increase in business.''
   Macy's flagship store in New York also reported brisk sales, with
selling floors getting busier every day. And across town at
Bloomingdale's, parts of the first floor look as crowded as an
anthill, spokeswoman Miraed Smith said.
   California retailers also said sales seemed to be growing
steadily.
   ``They are all big days this week, very heavy,'' said Bill
Dombrowski, spokesman for Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc., which owns
Broadway, Emporium Capwell, Thalheimers and Weinstock's department
stores in California and the Southwest.
   At Oshman's, a Houston-based sporting goods chain, ``The late
shopping surge seems to be materializing as we expected,'' said
company president Marvin Aronowitz. ``We have had snow in California
and we've had good sales on ski apparel and accessories.''
   The pace was even pushed at elegant Edmund T. Ahee Jewelry Co. in
the wealthy Detroit suburb of Grosse Pointe Woods.
   ``These three days, you can't believe how fast people buy,
they're so desperate,'' owner Edmund T. Ahee said.
   Some of the desperation is from the late shoppers who can't find
the items they're looking for. Retailers, forced to take a cautious
stance by nearly two years of sluggish sales, have kept inventories
tight so they would not be saddled with surplus merchandise or
forced to slash prices.
   At Dallas-based Neiman-Marcus, catalog sales have exceeded
expectations and the store has run out of some items, spokeswoman
Pat Zajac said.
   ``As people call in to order we are offering alternatives,'' she
said.
   She said about 15 to 20 items were out of stock, including some
crystal, $25-and-under gifts and apparel.
   At Upton's, a chain of 19 department stores in Georgia, South
Carolina, North Carolina and Tennessee, ``We're scrounging to get
more inventory in here,'' said Chuck Kremers, director of sales
promotion. ``We hope to have inventory to satisfy everybody that's
coming this weekend.''
   Demand also was outstripping supply for some of the season's
biggest toys. The hottest toy of 1988, the Nintendo video system,
was racking up phenomenal sales but retailers reported that some
Nintendo games _ including Super Mario Brothers II _ were in very
short supply.
   Part of the problem was a shortage of chips at Nintendo, a
Japanese company. But some toys put out by other manufacturers also
are hard to find.
   Angela Bourdon, a spokeswoman for Toys R Us Inc., the nation's
largest toy store chain, said Real Ghostbusters equipment and
figures, based on a Saturday morning cartoon, and Fisher-Price's
Magic Scan Checkout, a pretend supermarket cash register, also have
become scarce.
   ``Ninety percent of the consumers who are last-minute (shoppers)
are not getting the items,'' she said.
   Toys R Us has gotten new shipments of the toys, but ``there they
are _ and they're gone,'' Ms. Bourdon said.
   The retailers were expecting that Saturday, Christmas Eve, would
be the biggest day of their year.
   Because consumers won't be working, ``that'll be a very busy
day,'' said Dombrowski of Carter Hawley Hale.
   ``We're anticipating that Saturday will be very, very heavy,''
agreed Ms. Zajac of Neiman-Marcus. ``No more looking around. The
browsers will be buyers.''
   Storeowners generally are reporting that holiday sales have
improved modestly from last year's disappointing results. The
Christmas season is the biggest of the year for retailers and is
closely watched by economists as an indicator of consumer demand,
which consititutes about two-thirds of all economic activity.
   Retailers whose Christmas performance has been lackluster are
hoping the last few days will make a difference.
   One of those retailers is Scarbroughs department stores, with
three branches in Austin, Texas. Company president Scott Glass said
Wednesday, ``The good news is that things today seem to be coming to
life.'
   ``We just hope that can carry over through the week,'' he said.
</TEXT>
