<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BilzerianProfile     12-22 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bilzerian Profile,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corporate Raider Also A Dropout, Veteran and Little League Coach</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bilzerian Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate takeover strategist Paul
Bilzerian is a former high-school dropout, a Vietnam veteran, and
little league coach who prefers life in this quiet retirement haven
to that in a frenzied financial center.
   His wife Terri says he's also a driven man, who skips breakfast
and lunch and goes on little sleep.
   One day recently, stubble was thick on his chin because he forgot
his razor a couple of days earlier in Minnesota, where he had left
his family vacationing.
   Bilzerian, who took control of defense contractor Singer Co. last
February after a $1.06 billion takeover fight, was indicted
Wednesday in New York on securities fraud charges. He immediately
blamed the indictment on what he called overzealous prosecutors and
vowed to vindicate himself in court.
   In an era of financial predators and insider trading, Bilzerian
became a big player in the big-money game while staying somewhat
apart from it.
   He's not a flashy, well-coiffed hustler in a slick suit. He has
long, sideburns and a thick mustache. His aversion to suits and ties
has become a trademark.
   While professing that the goal of his takeover battles is to
finally win control of a company _ which he did with Singer _ he has
made a fortune from his string of apparent near-misses.
   Four times in the last two years Bilzerian has tried to purchase
companies, only to lose, either because he was outbid or
out-maneuvered. Yet in losing, Bilzerian has done well for himself
and his investors.
   In failed attempts to buy Cluett, Peabody & Co., Hammermill Paper
Co., Allied Stores Corp. and Pay 'N Pak, Bilzerian has reaped
profits of about $50 million, accounts of those takeover forays show.
   By selling his Pay 'N Pak shares, which he bought in April, he
and a partner reportedly earned about $8 million in profits for
three months' work.
   Bilzerian has always maintained his ambition is to own a company.
   The Worcester, Mass., native has accomplished much in a short
period. He collected a degree from Stanford and an MBA from Harvard.
After a radio-station failure here, he began investing in Florida
shopping centers with the financial help of his father-in-law.
   In 1982, he pulled out of real estate and invested in stocks at
the time the strongest bull market in history was about to get under
way. Then he started his takeover business.
   Among his noteworthy business partners are shopping-center
magnate Edward J. DeBartolo and the New Jersey real-estate barons
William and Earl Mack.
   In line with his ambitions, Bilzerian is building a palatial new
home: a $1-million structure in Tampa's ultra-exclusive Avila
subdivision. It's not expected to be completed for a year or so.
   Bilzerian declines to comment on his next financial move, saying
only: ``We'll continue to seek companies and make a lot of money.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
