<DOCNO> AP881222-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0145EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel-History     12-22 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-History,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Plea Climaxes Government Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s proposed settlement
is the most stunning achievement of an insider-trading probe by the
government that reached the public eye 19 months ago.
   From the start, the government's tactic was to give a break to
each person it caught in return for his help in bringing down others.
   It was May 12, 1986, when the Securities and Exchange Commission
charged Drexel's Dennis Levine with making $12.6 million in profits
from illegal trading on inside information.
   Levine was arrested and agreed to surrender the money, plead
guilty to criminal charges and cooperate with the government.
   From Levine, the government progressed to Ivan Boesky. The stock
speculator agreed on Nov. 14, 1986, to pay a record $100 million
penalty to settle charges of trading on inside information supplied
by Levine in 1985 and 1986.
   Boesky's testimony helped the government extract penalties from a
variety of lesser Wall Street figures. On Feb. 13, 1987, Martin A.
Siegel resigned as a managing director of Drexel and pleaded guilty
to illegal stock trading and tax evasion.
   Along the way, Levine was sentenced to two years in prison and
Boesky to three. Boesky remains incarcerated; Levine got out early.
But attention shifted to Drexel and whether the firm itself _ not
just individual executives _ would be prosecuted.
   On Sept. 7 of this year, the SEC formally accused Drexel of a
range of securities fraud violations in a civil suit that asserted
the firm had conspired with Boesky. The case was stalled by pretrial
arguments over the impartiality of the presiding judge, Milton
Pollack.
   On Wednesday, the other shoe dropped as Drexel agreed to a
proposed settlement in which it would plead guilty to six federal
felony counts and pay a record $650 million fine to settle the
biggest securities fraud case in history. The agreement requires
approval of senior Justice Department officials and the SEC.
   Overshadowed by the Drexel deal was the indictment Wednesday of
Paul A. Bilzerian, a takeover speculator who was accused of lying to
the government and illegally hiding stock. Bilzerian, too, was an
indirect victim of Boesky's disclosures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0146EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel-Joseph Bjt   12-22 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-Joseph, Bjt,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Chief a Tenacious Fighter on Firm's Behalf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederick Harold Joseph fought tenaciously to
spare Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. from criminal charges, and then,
when it appeared the investment firm couldn't avoid them, the chief
executive fought just as hard to fashion a deal that would protect
his company's reputation and bottom line.
   Drexel said Wednesday it would plead guilty to six felony counts
and pay a fine of $650 million to end a two-year investigation of
the company by federal prosecutors. The deal must be approved by the
Securities and Exchange Commission and senior Justice Department
officials.
   Only Monday, it appeared that Joseph, 51, a 14-year Drexel
veteran, would refuse to give in to the government's demands. He
told Drexel employees via the company's public-address system that a
settlement with the government did not make sense at that point.
   On Wednesday, Joseph told employees the settlement ``makes sense
from a business and human point of view.''
   ``It leaves the firm in a very strong financial position and
allows us to refocus our energies on running the business
successfully,'' he said.
   Joseph, a soft-spoken Boston native and Harvard graduate, joined
Drexel in 1974 after spending seven years with E.F. Hutton & Co. and
four with Shearson Hamill Co.
   He worked his way up to the head of corporate underwriting at
Drexel. It was in that position that he and Michael Milken, who
heads Drexel's junk bond department, led the firm to a near monopoly
in the mushrooming junk bond market.
   Joseph's success catapulted him to the chief executive's job in
1985.
   When stock speculator Ivan Boesky settled insider trading charges
with the federal government two years ago, he implicated Drexel in
his plea agreement. Joseph steadfastly maintained the firm's
innocence and said it would fight any charges.
   He reiterated that position over and over, even after the
Securities and Exchange Commission filed civil charges against
Drexel in September.
   It was only in recent weeks that it became apparent that Drexel's
_ and perhaps Joseph's _ resolve had weakened.
   He likely was influenced by several key Drexel executives who had
been pushing for a settlement on grounds the continuing barrage of
publicity and negative speculation was eroding the firm's ability to
maintain its business.
   Joseph also was likely swayed by the investigation's toll on its
bottom line. In a memo to employees last month, the chairman said
the government's investigation had cost the firm an estimated $1.5
billion in revenue.
   If Drexel had been indicted, that amount would have soared and
the firm might have lost financing from major banks. And it could
have taken years for the charges to be resolved.
   But even with those obstacles, Joseph fought hard, reportedly
letting pass several deadlines set by the government for a
settlement.
   The investigation has cast doubt on Joseph's future with Drexel,
although he reportedly has said he expects to outlast the firm's
problems. Drexel has talked recently to former White House Chief of
Staff Howard Baker about Baker's becoming chairman of the firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel-Chronology     12-22 0894</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-Chronology,0922</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rundown of Major Events Leading Up to Settlement Pact on Drexel
Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of major developments in the prosecution of
insider trading cases on Wall Street that led up to Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.'s record agreement to settle securities fraud charges
Wednesday:
   May 12, 1986 _ The Securities and Exchange Commission charges
Dennis Levine, a Drexel mergers executive, with making $12.6 million
in profits from illegal trading on inside information. He is
arrested and agrees to surrender the money, plead guilty to criminal
charges and cooperate with the government.
   Nov. 14 _ Stock speculator Ivan Boesky agrees to pay a record
$100 million penalty to settle charges of trading on inside
information supplied by Levine in 1985 and 1986. He also agrees to
cooperate with investigators.
   Feb. 13, 1987 _ Martin A. Siegel resigns as a managing director
of Drexel and pleads guilty to illegal stock trading and tax
evasion. He agrees to cooperate with the government and surrender $9
million to settle civil charges that he engaged in insider trading
with Boesky.
   Feb. 20 _ Levine is sentenced to two years in prison and fined
$362,000 on charges of securities fraud, tax evasion and perjury.
   March 19 _ Boyd L. Jefferies, founder of the Los Angeles
securities firm Jefferies & Co., agrees to plead guilty to two
securities fraud charges, one of which involves a relationship with
Boesky. Jefferies resigns as chairman of his company and agrees to
stay out of the securities business for five years.
   April 23 _ Boesky pleads guilty to one criminal charge,
conspiracy to make false statements to the SEC, and is released
without bail as he continues to cooperate with the government's
investigation.
   June 4 _ Kidder, Peabody & Co. agrees to pay $25.29 million to
settle civil charges of insider trading and an improper ``stock
parking'' scheme with Boesky. The U.S. attorney's office says Kidder
will not be prosecuted.
   Dec. 18 _ Boesky is sentenced to a 3-year prison term, and no
fine.
   March 24 _ Boesky begins serving his sentence at a
minimum-security facility in Lompoc, Calif.
   May 31 _ The SEC votes to authorize civil charges against Drexel
and its controversial junk bond financier, Michael Milken. The
government's investigation of Drexel stems directly from information
supplied by Boesky.
   July 5 _ Levine is released from a Lewisburg, Pa., federal prison
camp to serve the remainder of his term under limited federal
supervision.
   July 6 _ A federal grand jury indicts GAF Corp., its vice
chairman, James Sherwin, and two subsidiaries on charges they
manipulated the price of Union Carbide Corp. stock in 1986 after a
failed attempt to acquire the company. The indictments mark the
first formal charges against a U.S. industrial company that stem
indirectly from the Boesky scandal.
   July 14 _ GAF and Sherwin plead innocent.
   Aug. 4 _ A federal grand jury indicts five partners of the
investment firm Princeton-Newport Partners and a former Drexel
official on charges of racketeering, conspiracy and mail and wire
fraud. The case, which grew out of the Boesky scandal, marks the
first time officials of a securities firm are charged with
violations of the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations
Act. All defendants deny any wrongdoing.
   Sept. 7 _ The SEC formally accuses Drexel of a range of
securities fraud violations.
   Oct. 20, 1988 _ A federal appeals court stops all proceedings in
the Drexel case and related civil litigation while considering
defense arguments that the presiding judge, Milton Pollack, should
disqualify himself.
   Nov. 3, 1988 _ A federal grand jury indicts Salim B. ``Sandy''
Lewis, a well-known takeover speculator, on charges he manipulated
the stock price of Fireman's Fund Corp. in 1986 to help American
Express Co. sell part of its Fireman's Fund stake for more money.
The indictment is based partly on disclosures by Boyd Jefferies more
than a year earlier. Lewis denies guilt.
   Nov. 16, 1988 _ A federal appeals court rejects Drexel defense
motion to disqualify Judge Pollack.
   Nov. 21, 1988 _ Drexel re-appeals motion to disqualify Pollack.
Civil case remains stalled.
   Nov. 30, 1988 _ Intense secret negotiations are reported between
Drexel attorneys and federal prosecutors in a last-ditch attempt by
the firm to avert an indictment, particularly charges of
racketeering, which carry enormous penalties. U.S. attorney is said
to have Justice Department approval to pursue racketeering case if
he believes it appropriate.
   Dec. 1, 1988 _ Drexel's chief executive Frederick Joseph tells
employees in a memorandum that negotiations wth the U.S. attorney
have reached a ``crucial stage,'' and suggests Drexel may settle by
pleading guilty to lesser charges.
   Dec. 6, 1988 _ Cary Maultasch, a senior Drexel trader accused in
the SEC case and threatened with numerous indictments, turns state's
evidence in a plea-bargain agreement with the government.
   Dec. 7, 1988 _ Princeton Newport Partners liquidates because of
what lawyers for its indicted parters call brutal government misuse
of the racketeering laws to coerce them into cooperating in the
Drexel investigation. Prosecutors decline to comment.
   Dec. 8-20, 1988 _ Speculation persists of an imminent agreement
to settle the charges, as more Drexel employees agree to turn
state's evidence.
   Dec. 21 _ Drexel agrees to plead guilty to six felonies and pay a
record $650 million fine, contingent upon approval from the SEC and
senior Justice Department officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
