<DOCNO> AP881222-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0741EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Britain-Eggs     12-22 0769</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Eggs,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister's Fortunes See-Saw Through A Poisoned Egg Panic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Margaret Thatcher told the House of Commons
the other day that she'd eaten a scrambled egg for lunch, she was
doing much more than making small talk.
   The prime minister was trying to calm a salmonella panic that has
forced a government minister to resign, hurt the poultry industry,
cost taxpayers more than $35 million, and left the public bewildered
about whether Britain's eggs are safe.
   The crisis began Dec. 3 when Edwina Currie, then the junior
health minister, told a television interviewer that ``most of the
egg production in this country, sadly, is now infected with
salmonella.''
   Coming from anyone else, it might have passed unnoticed. But Mrs.
Currie, 42, is no ordinary politician; she is colorful, outspoken
and ambitious, and her words command attention.
   Ever since she brandished handcuffs during a law-and-order debate
at the Conservative Party's 1981 convention, her well-timed
headline-grabbers have made her famous.
   Elected to Parliament in 1983, she became a deputy health
minister in 1986, arriving at work in a T-shirt that said: ``Never
underestimate the power of this woman.''
   Mrs. Thatcher was known to be fond of the woman who had once said
of a defeated election rival: ``I eat people like Peter Kent for
breakfast.''
   Reveling in the role of national nanny, Mrs. Currie crusaded
against smoking and drinking; exhorted pensioners to knit themselves
winter garments; told families to forgo holidays and spend the money
on their teeth; denounced northerners' fondness for junk food; and
advised traveling businessmen to avoid AIDS by taking their wives
along.
   So when she made her salmonella remark, the knives were drawn.
``She should really think before she opens her mouth,''
editorialized the tabloid Sun. Writer Auberon Waugh called her ``a
bossy, garrulous and foolish woman.''
   On Dec. 4, as egg producers said sales were falling rapidly, Mrs.
Thatcher sought to calm the waters by saying she ate scrambled eggs
for lunch. But despite opposition ridicule and the anger of Tory
lawmakers from farming constituencies, the government refused to
give eggs a clean bill of health.
   The gist of official statements was that while Mrs. Currie may
have overstated the problem, it was real. Salmonella, a strain of
food poison that causes severe vomiting, fever and diarrhea, can be
fatal, and 26 people who died this year were carrying
poultry-related salmonella, the Health Department said.
   It launched a $900,000 advertising campaign that said eggs posed
``very little risk'' for the healthy, but that the elderly, sick and
pregnant should cook them thoroughly.
   The ads also said 49 salmonella outbreaks affecting 1,000 people
this year were traced to eggs and that ``this underestimates the
numbers.''
   Furious egg producers said the ad only made things worse. They
said sales were down 60 percent, 400 million unsold eggs had
accumulated, and many of Britain's 39 million egg-laying hens would
have to be slaughtered.
   As newspapers reached for outrageous puns on ruffled feathers and
curried eggs, poultry farmers appeared on TV talking of bankruptcy.
   The egg producers filed a dozen damage suits against Mrs. Currie,
the press ridicule mounted, and on Dec. 16, after meeting with Mrs.
Thatcher, Mrs. Currie resigned.
   But at this point, her image began to shift to that of a
scapegoat brought down by the powerful farming industry and its
friends in government.
   Asked Frank Dobson, an opposition Labor Party lawmaker: ``If she
was right, why did she have to resign? If she was wrong, why was she
not corrected? ... All in all, no one any longer knows what the
truth is.''
   On Monday, when the government announced a $34 million bailout
for the farmers, the Daily Express was one of several newspapers
that denounced the government for paying off the very industry that
had unleashed the disease. ``The egg industry has behaved
appallingly in the hounding of Mrs. Currie,'' it editorialized.
   Even the venerable violin virtuoso Yehudi Menuhin weighed in,
writing to The Times to say Mrs. Currie shared ``the classical fate
of all bearers of bad tidings ... The scapegoat is sacrificed, thus
delaying, diverting and betraying the remedy.''
   Helen Morris of London, whose husband contracted salmonella from
eggs and was sick for 10 weeks, said if the producers sued Mrs.
Currie, she might countersue the producers.
   Many praised Mrs. Currie for using her publicity skills to raise
health consciousness, while former lawmaker Tom Benyon said the
affair would help Britons ``understand better, now they have seen it
in action, the brute power of the lobby.''
</TEXT>
