<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Japan-Cards     12-22 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Cards,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Tech Christmas Cards A Hit In Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report. Store name Tokyu Hands in 4th
graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They stand up, they sing, they flicker on and off.
   Ingenuity and high technology have led to some unusual Christmas
cards, which retailers say are a big hit with Japanese holiday
shoppers this year.
   Take, for example, the card that unfolds into an upright
Christmas tree, complete with blinking red lights and a two-tune
repertoire of ``Rudolph the Red-nosed Reindeer'' and ``Santa Claus
Is Coming to Town.''
   ``It's very big with 18- to 25-year-old women this year,'' said
Takehiro Ushishima of the sales promotion department at Tokyu Hands,
a popular store for hobby goods.
   The songs are stored in a tiny integrated circuit that is
activated by a light sensor when the card is opened. The cost is
about $15.
   Tokyu Hands has already sold out of cards made with real gold
costing upwards of $3.
   ``The most popular new cards this year are those that come with
compact discs,'' Ushishima said. The discs feature one or two
Christmas tunes and are often decorated to match the cards they are
sold with.
   High-tech cards are decidedly upscale, averaging over $8 each, or
more than four times the price of the conventional printed card.
   ``But this year card makers in general have been more
elaborate,'' bringing up the average price, Ushishima said.
   Christians are a 1 percent minority in Japan, where Buddhism and
the indigenous Shinto faiths are most common, and Christmas is not a
national holiday. However, many Japanese non-Christians celebrate
Christmas by having parties, exchanging gifts or eating special
foods.
   ``Sales of Christmas cards are now at their peak,'' said Ichiro
Saito, public relations director of Itoya, a major stationery store
in the swank Ginza district.
   ``It's been a good year for Christmas cards because of the
emperor's illness,'' Saito said.
   Emperor Hirohito, 87, has been seriously ill since Sept. 19,
causing a mood of self-restraint in the public, including a slump in
the sale of New Year's greeting cards.
   It appears that Christmas cards are more popular because their
neutral message of ``Season's Greetings'' is more appropriate than
``Happy New Year,'' Saito said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0834EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Drexel-Milken Bjt   12-22 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-Milken, Bjt,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michael Milken, Architect of Junk Bond Market, at Center of Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Milken, the man at the center of the
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trading scandal, built the modern market
in ``junk bonds,'' the favored financing tool of ambitious
entrepreneurs and corporate raiders.
   The Milken-controlled network of investors who buy and sell the
high-yield, high-risk bonds is so pervasive that Drexel reportedly
has been pressed to re-work terms of its settlement to protect its
prime trader.
   Drexel agreed Wednesday to plead guilty to six felony counts and
pay a record $650 million fine to settle a criminal case filed by
the U.S. attorney's office in New York. The deal requires approval
by the Securities and Exchange Commission and senior Justice
Department officials.
   Milken wasn't involved in the tentative settlement, but is named
in a parallel civil case filed by the SEC against Drexel.
   A New York public relations firm Milken hired to represent him
issued a statement saying: ``There is no change in his position, and
his attorneys are continuing to prepare to defend him against any
charges that might be brought.''
   Milken, a boyish evangelist of free enterprise, is credited with
broadening the market for junk bonds, once spurned by many
investors. Under Milken's leadership, Drexel transformed the
securities into a handy tool for corporate raiders and small
businesses to raise cash, either to buy companies or to expand those
that weren't big enough to swing big bank loans or attract
conservative bond investors.
   Milken became central to the junk bond market's operation,
presiding over a network of investors from an office he persuaded
Drexel to set up in Beverly Hills.
   Though many other firms now deal in the bonds, Drexel remains a
leader, and Milken a prime mover. When it comes time for a junk bond
issue, Milken can line up buyers from among those who have
previously benefited by selling their own junk bonds.
   Milken works long hours and lives unobtrusively in a home in
suburban Encino that once was owned by Clark Gable. He is rarely
available for media interviews, and only on his own terms.
   Said to be a devoted family man, he also is a philanthropist on a
grand scale. He has contributed nearly $263 million to three
endowments over the last six years. Those organizations, Capital
Fund Foundation, the Milken Family Foundation and the M&L Milken
Foundation, have paid out $17 million to more than 200 charities and
community groups.
   But that part of Milken's life, too, has come under the cloud of
the Wall Street scandal.
   Capital Fund is named in the SEC's civil complaint against Drexel
as one of the organizations that took part in illegal trades.
   After a Los Angeles Times story detailed the foundation's
activities, the California attorney general's office began a probe.
Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., demanded last month that the Internal
Revenue Service investigate to see if the organization had violated
rules for tax-exempt charitable trusts.
   The state audit will focus on possible self-dealing by officers
of the foundations, said Assistant Attorney General Carole Ritts
Kornblum.
   Capital Fund Foundation spokesman Lance Morgan has denied any
wrondgoing by the foundation.
   A Los Angeles businessman who has dealt with Milken's charities
described them as well-run ventures that have supported innovative
projects to improve public and private education, among other
causes. Richard Riordan, an attorney and philanthropist, disputed
critics of Milken's charity work.
   ``Here the guy gave away $263 million,'' Riordan said Wednesday.
``The guy could have bought a yacht bigger than (financier Donald)
Trump's and more planes than (Adnan) Kashoggi's.''
   ``He gives money in a brilliant way; he doesn't just throw it
around,'' Riordan said. ``He has a good staff and they rifle in on
what's needed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0845EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RJRNabisco-Japan     12-22 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco-Japan,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Banks Undecided on Joining in RJR Nabisco Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following meetings with corporate takeover
specialist Henry Kravis, Japanese banking officials said Thursday
they remained undecided about their role in his firm's record $24.53
billion buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Kravis, a partner in Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co., met Wednesday
and Thursday with more than a dozen leading Japanese banks to urge
them to participate in financing the purchase.
   Japanese banks are expected to provide a significant portion of
the $14 billion in bank financing needed for the RJR takeover.
   Representatives of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., one of KKR's main
financial brokers, also met Wednesday in Tokyo with about 250
Japanese bankers and institutional investors to pitch the sale of
$3.5 billion in high-yield, high-risk ``junk bonds'' that will help
finance the purchase, company officials said.
   Officials at leading Japanese banks said they were not given
enough information about the buyout plan to decide on participation,
which a Sanwa Bank official said ``would require a careful weighing
of the high risks against the high profits.''
   ``We're still deciding whether to become involved,'' said a
official at Mitsubishi Bank, who also spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``The meetings (with Kravis and Drexel) were just a
general presentation of the purchase, not a request for a specific
amount of funds.''
   An official at Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, the world's largest bank,
said it had not received a detailed analysis of the transaction or
of plans to sell off certain RJR assets, a common way to finance
corporate takeovers.
   ``We're very interested, but aren't able to make a decision
without the full materials,'' he said.
   Some newspapers have speculated that KKR will attempt to sell off
some portions of Nabisco, a food producer, to Japanese firms.
   Kravis said in an interview with the nationally circulated
newspaper Asahi Shimbun that Japanese banks responded ``very
positively'' to his contacts, but that he still was unsure how much
they would provide. He said he was considering approaching other
Japanese banks early next year in a bid to increase the number of
participants.
   Asked about estimates that he hopes to raise as much as one-third
of the total bank loan in Japan, or about $5 billion, Kravis said
KKR had not decided on a division of financing.
   In recent weeks, Japanese newspapers have reported that the
Finance Ministry was frowning on Japanese participation in the
buyout plan because of potential risks and concern that such
leveraged buyouts might spread to Japan, where they remain very rare.
   A senior ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Thursday the ministry had ``concern'' about the issue, but
``the decision whether to participate is up to each bank.''
   Bank officials said they had not received any direct
communication from the ministry regarding participation.
   In a leveraged buyout, a purchaser uses a portion of the assets
and future earnings of a company to pay for its purchase. Junk
bonds, which are issued by companies whose credit ratings are below
normal investment grade, often are used to help finance such a
transaction.
</TEXT>
