<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Turn Slightly Lower On Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly lower
in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, due mainly to
profit-taking following strong rallies Wednesday in the corn and
soybean markets.
   Soybean futures opened slightly higher, contrary to expectations,
on technically inspired, speculative buying. But those gains were
quickly trimmed.
   The soybean complex also was pressured by the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Wednesday that the Soviet Union had
canceled a purchase of 102,500 metric tons of U.S. soybean meal,
analysts said.
   Wheat futures were expected to open higher on the USDA's
announcement that it had targeted Morocco for sales of 1 million
metric tons of wheat at subsidized prices.
   But with several wheat contracts trading at lifetime highs, ``the
wheat market is probably keeping its powder dry and looking to the
outside mkts, with people tending to be cautious,'' said Arthur
Parrish, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   ``You've got a fair amount of profit-taking at these levels,'' he
said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 2} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.36 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 2 cents lower with March at $2.83{ a bushel; oats were { cent
lower to } cent higher with March at $2.32 a bushel; soybeans were \
cent to 2 cents lower with January at $7.93{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange with frozen pork-belly prices down
sharply in reaction to Wednesday's USDA monthly cold-storage report
showing supplies of frozen bellies as of Nov. 30 at a record-high
level for that date.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .25 cent lower with February at
73.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .42 cent lower
with January at 83.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to .35
cent lower with February at 46.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .65 cent to 1.05 cents lower with February at 44.25 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Wednesday while pork futures
were mixed.
