<HEAD>Management To Buy Out Maxwell Printing Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC said Thursday its
BPCC unit, a British printing business, would be sold to a
management group, as expected, for the equivalent of $479 million.
   Maxwell Communication Chairman Robert Maxwell said last month he
intended to sell BPCC, as well as other parts of his printing and
publishing empire, following his succesful $2.5 billion takeover of
Macmillan Inc., the New York-based publisher.
   Maxwell, who also recently bought Dun & Bradstreet Corp.'s
Official Airlines Guide for $750 million, is selling assets to
reduce debt and focus his company's interests on publishing.
   The sale of BPCC to Bucksmere Ltd., a company formed from the
management of the printing group and a syndicate of institutional
investors, was widely anticipated. The sale is conditional on
approval from Maxwell Communication's sharholders.
   Under the agreeement, Maxwell Communication will retain certain
BPCC properties and it also will take a minority stake in the
company doing the buyout.
