<DOCNO> AP881222-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1914EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PolaroidPetition     12-22 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid Petition,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employees Tell Shamrock No Thanks On Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 Polaroid Corp. employees
have signed a petition that sends a clear message to hostile suitor
Shamrock Holdings Inc. and its president, Stanley P. Gold: Thanks,
but no thanks.
   The petition, which includes signatures from about 60 percent of
Polaroid's worldwide work force, also was designed as a protest
message that corporate takeovers are potentially damaging to
employees.
   ``We don't believe his takeover of Polaroid is in our best
interests,'' Richard Duffy, a 30-year Polaroid employee and member
of the steering committee for the petition drive, said Thursday.
   The petition, circulated at Polaroid headquarters here and in
plans around the world in the last 10 days, says Shamrock ``has no
experience in managing a high-tech company and has not yet explained
to Polaroid employees the method of paying the astronomical debt
needed to acquire'' the company.
   It also says Polaroid workers have ``no comfort or confidence''
that the acquisition would benefit the company, its shareholders or
the community.
   Shamrock, a Burbank, Calif.-based television and radio concern
wholly owned by the Roy E. Disney family, has offered $42 a share in
a bid that values the instant camera pioneer at about $2.6 billion.
Polaroid has called the bid too low and asked stockholders to reject
it.
   The takeover hinges on the pending outcome of a trial in Delaware
Chancery Court, where Shamrock is seeking to have Polaroid's
10-million-share, $300-million employee stock ownership plan
overturned. Shamrock claims it was enacted to forestall a takeover.
   The plan would all but block a takeover because it puts 14
percent of Polaroid stock in the hands of employees. Under Delaware
takeover law, a hostile bidder must acquire more than 85 percent of
a target's outstanding shares for control. Polaroid is incorporated
in Delaware.
   The employee petition opposing the takeover has no bearing on the
court case.
   The petition was the idea of employees who want to form an
independent group of supervisors and hourly workers at Polaroid
plants in eastern Massachusetts and around the country.
   The petition was signed by salaried and non-salaried workers. It
represents a clear majority of Polaroid's 8,300 employees.
   ``It focuses specifically on employee rights,'' Duffy said. ``Our
belief is what is happening to employees in the takeover arena is an
afterthought if a thought at all.''
   ``To some extent we felt we were sitting on the sidelines,
observing and hearing what's going on. It was disempowering,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
