<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Drifts Higher, Gold Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against most major currencies
Thursday in extremely light trading. Gold prices also edged higher.
   Business was so light that many banks stopped dealing directly
with each other and instead did deals through international brokers,
who match buyers and sellers, said Jerry Egan, senior trader of the
Bank of Boston.
   ``They took the sails down and put the motor on. The market has
been becalmed,'' Egan said.
   The market showed little reaction to the Commerce Department
report that orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods, excluding the
volatile defense category, shot up 1.8 percent in November, the best
showing since August.
   The dollar gained against the British pound. In London, it cost
$1.7990 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8065 Wednesday. In New
York, it cost $1.7988, cheaper than $1.8065 Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.40 yen to a closing 124.62 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 124.65 yen. In New York, the dollar rose to
124.68 yen from 124.55 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.7729 West German marks, up from
1.7690; 1.4950 Swiss francs, up from 1.4945; 6.0510 French francs,
up from 6.0390; 1.306.25 Italian lire, up from 1,300.50; and 1.1963
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1986.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday's
prices, included: 1.7735 West German marks, up from 1.7720; 1.4970
Swiss francs, down from 1.4980; 6.0540 French francs, up from
6.0500; 2.0035 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9920; 1,306.00 Italian
lire, up from 1,302.00; and 1.1959 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2012.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $1.51 a troy ounce to close at a bid
$417.45 an ounce. Later, gold rose in London to a late bid price of
$417.25 a troy ounce, from $415.75 bid late Wednesday. In Zurich,
gold rose to close at a bid $417 from $414.60 bid late Wednesday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $418 a troy ounce from $415.30 Wednesday.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at
$417.60 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $415 late Wednesday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market, where the metal
traded at a late bid price of $6.15 a troy ounce, compared with
Wednesday's $6.14. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery rose to $6.160 an ounce from $6.116.
</TEXT>
