<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0865</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit-Taking Snaps Coffee Market's Streak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices fell sharply Thursday on New York's Coffee,
Sugar & Cocoa Exchange, ending a six-day rally amid pre-holiday
profit-taking on signs that a Brazilian dockworkers' strike was
nearing an end.
   On other exchanges, precious metals futures continued to rise,
grains and soybeans were mixed; livestock and meat futures were
mixed; energy futures rose; and stock-index futures retreated.
   Trading activity on most markets was light, with many independent
traders starting the Christmas weekend early. Most U.S. futures
markets will close at noon local time on Friday and reopen Tuesday
morning.
   Futures prices for green, unroasted coffee settled 5 cents to
6.55 cents lower with the contract for delivery in March at $1.4939
a pound.
   Exchange officials halted trading in coffee futures for 55
minutes shortly after a chaotic opening in which the market was
swamped with sell orders linked to reports that some dockworkers had
returned to their jobs in the Brazilian port of Santos, the busiest
coffee port in the world's largest coffee-producing country.
   The strike, which began Dec. 13, has been a key factor in
coffee's dramatic price surge from less than $1.25 a pound on Dec. 1
to the two-year high of $1.59 a pound recorded Wednesday.
   Other fundamental factors underpinning coffee's gains include
tight U.S. warehouse stocks, delayed shipments from Central America,
a rain-slowed harvest in Colombia and a drought in the prime growing
areas of Brazil.
   These bullish developments have been playing out against a
backdrop of rising demand; coffee consumption peaks each year during
the winter months in the Northern Hemisphere.
   ``Today we reacted strongly to expectations that the port strike
in Brazil is close to a resolution,'' said Arthur Stevenson, a
coffee analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``Also,'' he said, ``the market has had almost a vertical advance
over the last two weeks and you don't need a Harvard Ph.D. to
realize it was time for a correction.''
   Prices of precious metals futures advanced for the third
consecutive day in a continuing rebound from the steep sell-off that
occurred last week after Ford Motor Co. announced its development of
a platinum-free catalytic converter.
   The use of platinum in the automobile pollution-control devices
accounts for about one-third of world platinum consumption. But
analysts say Ford's experimental converter is unlikely to
significantly reduce platinum demand for several years.
   ``We're seeing a natural, very tentative gravitation toward the
prices that we saw before the Ford announcement,'' said Richard
Levine, vice president of precious metals and foreign exchange
trading with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   Platinum settled $1.80 to $8.30 higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with the spot December contract at $544.20 a troy ounce and
the more actively traded January contract at $540.70 a troy ounce.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled $2.50 to $2.90
higher with February at $421.30 a troy ounce; silver was 3.8 cents
to 4.4 cents higher with March at $6.268 a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mixed on the Chicago Board of
Trade in light, thin trading as players evened up their positions
ahead of the long Christmas weekend.
   After the close, the USDA announced the Soviet Union had
purchased 1 million metric tons of U.S. corn and China had been
awarded 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with March at
$4.38} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to 2\ cents higher with
March at $2.83\ a bushel; oats were { cent to 1\ cents lower with
March at $2.32 a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 8{ cents
higher with January at $7.92\ a bushel.
   Frozen pork-belly futures prices fell steeply on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in reaction to Wednesday's monthly USDA
cold-storage report showing supplies of frozen bellies as of Nov. 30
at a record high level for that date.
   Livestock futures finished mixed in lackluster trading.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .10 cent higher with February
at 73.90 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .27 cent lower to .08
cent higher with January at 83.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .18
cent lower to .17 cent higher with February at 46.57 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .98 cent to 1.10 cents lower with February
at 44.07 cents a pound.
   Energy futures advanced in light pre-holiday trading on the New
York Mercantile Exchange, reflecting investor optimism that oil
prices would move higher.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 19 cents to 25 cents
higher at $16.49 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent to .77 cent
higher with January at 52.48 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.82 cent to .95 cent higher with January at 46.57 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange. The contract for March delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 settled .40 point lower at 280.05. Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
