<HEAD>CBS To Buy 2 Detroit Radio Stations For $58 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. said Thursday it had agreed to buy two
radio stations in Detroit for $58 million, bringing its total number
of stations to 20 and giving it a presence in each of the top 10
markets.
   The purchase of WWJ-AM and WJOI-FM from Federal Broadcasting Co.,
a subsidiary of Federal Enterprises Inc. of Southfield, Mich., is
expected to be completed in the first half of 1989, pending
regulatory approval, CBS said.
   WWJ assignment editor Pete Barkey said it was believed to be the
highest price paid for a dual station in the Detroit market.
