<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pepperell-Farley     12-22 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pepperell-Farley,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Side With Pepperell; Shareholders Meeting Set for Feb.
25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 35 congressmen _ most of them from
textile states _ has complained to top banking and security
officials about Farley Inc.'s unsolicited $1.4 billion bid for West
Point-Pepperell Inc., claiming the proposed deal would weaken the
nation's battle against textile imports.
   The letter to Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and
Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman David Ruder includes
general worries about leveraged buyouts and also echoes Pepperell's
specific charges that the bid is too heavily financed by debt.
   Among those who signed the letter sent this week are Rep. Richard
Ray, D-Ga., whose district includes Pepperell's headquarters in West
Point, Ga., and Rep. Henry Gonzalez, D-Texas, who will chair the
House Banking Committee in the new Congress.
   Meanwhile, Farley on Thursday again extended its $48-per-share
offer until Jan. 4. The offer originally was made in October, and
has been extended past several expiration dates.
   And Pepperell's board set a special shareholders meeting for Feb.
25. At the meeting, Farley will attempt to replace current board
members with its own nominees who would be expected to rescind
Pepperell's anti-takeover defenses.
   Leveraged buyouts, in which acquisitions are financed with
borrowed money secured by the target's cash flow or assets, ``may be
saddling corporations with a dangerous level of debt which will
restrict their ability to modernize and to weather economic
downturns,'' the congressmen's letter said.
   The 1934 Securities Exchange Act ``directed the Federal Reserve
Board to issue margin regulations to limit the excessive use of
credit in securities transactions,'' the letter said. ``Now, more
than ever, Congress expects the Federal Reserve Board and the
Securities and Exchange Commission to assure that those margin
regulations are enforced.''
   Pepperell has filed suit trying to block Farley's bid, claiming
among other things that the offer violates those regulations, but a
federal district judge ruled against the Georgia company. The case
has been appealed to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals which
has set a Jan. 11 hearing date.
   ``By any objective measure, West Point-Pepperell is a growing and
healthy company,'' the letter says, but Farley's plans to break up
the company after a takeover means ``we risk losing one of the
strongest U.S. competitors in the world's textile market.''
   Textile manufacturers long have complained about what they see as
unfair foreign competition, and the signers of the letter include
some of the leaders in unsuccessful efforts to erect import quotas.
   Of the signers, 21 of the congressmen are from North Carolina,
South Carolina, Georgia and Alabama _ all of which have a
concentration of the nation's textile industry.
   Chicago-based Farley, a privately owned conglomerate that
manufactures such items as Fruit of the Loom underwear and Acme
Boots, said Thursday it had been tendered or already owns about 58
percent of Pepperell's outstanding stock.
   Farley also has succeeded in forcing Pepperell to call the
special shareholders meeting, getting holders of more than 25
percent of the outstanding stock to call for the session.
   Pepperell, the nation's largest publicly owned textile company,
has about 29.4 million outstanding shares. Its products include Gold
Toe socks, Arrow shirts and Martex towels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1811EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Macmillan     12-22 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Macmillan,0517</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Backs Out Of Macmillan Unit Purchases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. said Thursday the buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. had terminated its proposed purchase
of four Macmillan units for $400 million, but the publisher said it
still expected to find buyers for the properties.
   Macmillan, which was acquired for $2.5 billion last month by
Britain's Maxwell Communication Corp., said Kohlberg Kravis
indicated it was dropping the deal due to rising interest rates and
problems in arranging financing for the purchase.
   But a Kohlberg Kravis spokesman said the firm backed out of the
deal because of restrictions set by Macmillan and Maxwell.
   Earlier this month, Macmillan and Maxwell announced they had
agreed to sell Kohlberg their Macmillan Books Clubs Inc., an
operator of several specialty book clubs specializing in the
sciences; Gryphon Editions, which publishes reprints in medicine and
law; Intertec Publishing Corp., which publishes 14 specialty
magazines; and Webb Publishing, which publishes agricultural
magazines.
   Proceeds from the sale were to be used to help pay off some of
the debt incurred in the Maxwell buyout.
   Kohlberg Kravis had backed senior Macmillan managers who
unsuccessfully competed against Maxwell for Macmillan.
   ``KKR suspended moving ahead with this deal because Macmillan and
Maxwell imposed certain structures and special requirements to
complete the transaction by yearend because of tax reasons,'' said
Thomas Daly, a spokesman for Kohlberg Kravis. ``That could not be
done.''
   Daly also said that as negotiations proceeded, the firm decided
``the values initially understood to be there were not there given
the arrangements and structure placed on the transaction by Maxwell
and Macmillan.''
   Macmillan also said in a news release it was confident of getting
buyers for the properties ``at similar prices'' and expected to make
further announcements shortly.
   Dave Jackson, a spokesman for Macmillan and Maxwell North
America, said there were ongoing talks with possible buyers, but
declined to comment on when any deals might be announced.
   Macmillan has outlined a number of divestitures in the wake of
the Maxwell buyout, including the planned sales of its Gumps retail
unit, Katharine Gibbs Schools, Technical Schools and Direct
Marketing Group.
   Macmillan said its previously announced sale of Michie Co. to the
Mead Corp. for $226.5 million was proceeding smoothly. Michie
publishes materials for the legal profession, and Mead is a paper,
forest products and electronic publishing concern.
   Macmillan also announced that the Delaware Chancery Court had
invalidated the so-called ``lock-up'' agreement between Macmillan
and Kohlberg Kravis.
   While battling to thwart Maxwell, Macmillan had agreed to a
buyout by Kohlberg Kravis and granted the firm the option to acquire
four of its prize properties for $865 million in the event their
deal fell through. Such options generally are used to discourage
competing suitors.
   The Delaware Supreme Court enjoined the lock-up, clearing the way
for Maxwell to win the bidding fight, and the Chancery Court removed
the restriction entirely.
   Properties in the lock-up were Macmillan's Directory, Direct
Marketing, Berlitz language school and Michie businesses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
