<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Fell $2.03 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Figures are for the week ended Wednesday. Interest rate
figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report are not available.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 456 money market mutual
funds fell $2.03 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The decline, to $278.64 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $2.03 billion drop in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $281.89 billion in the week
ended Nov. 23, 1988.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 228 general purpose funds fell $328.4 million to $89.68
billion, assets of 93 broker-dealer funds dropped $504.7 million to
$117.36 billion, and assets of 135 institutional funds declined
$1.20 billion to $71.60 billion.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.18 percent as of Wednesday from 6.17 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, were unchanged at 5.13 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.16
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 8.12 the
previous week. Yields were 8.43 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.39
percent; 8.55 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.52 percent; and 8.70
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.68 percent.
</TEXT>
