<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 1841EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ThriftsAcquired 1stLd-Writethru   12-22 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thrifts Acquired, 1st Ld-Writethru,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifteen Texas Thrifts Acquired in $1.85 Billion Bailout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds byline, rewrites throughout with details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators announced a plan Thursday to
merge 15 insolvent savings and loan institutions in Texas in a $1.85
billion bailout, bringing to 175 the number of failed that rescued
nationwide this year.
   The 15 Texas S&Ls will be acquired by CFSB Corp. Inc., a holding
company headed by James M. Fail of Phoenix Ariz., who agreed to put
up $120 million to acquire the insolvent institutions.
   The Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., which guarantees
deposits at 3,000 S&Ls, will provide assistance amounting to $1.85
billion.
   The transaction was part of the Southwest Plan launched last May
to clean up the problems of 109 failed S&Ls in Texas, a state where
financial institutions have been hard-hit by depressed conditions in
real estate and oil.
   The latest rescue package brings the total of failed institutions
which have been closed or merged to 69 in Texas and to 175 around
the country.
   ``We now have consolidated more than half of the 109 Texas
thrifts that were insolvent when we started the Southwest Plan and
we are rapidly moving toward our goal of completing the work in
Texas by the end of the 1989 fiscal year (next Sept. 30),'' said M.
Danny Wall, chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which
oversees the FSLIC fund.
   The institutions Fail acquired will reopen Friday as Consolidated
Federal Bank FSB. Consolidated will initially operate all 59 of the
branches of the former institutions, the bank board said.
   Fail is chairman of Lifeshares Service Co. and several other
insurance companies which operate in 47 states.
   The S&Ls involved in Thursday's action include Commodore Savings
Association, Dallas; Mesquite Savings and Loan Association,
Mesquite; Mineral Wells Savings and Loan Association, Mineral Wells;
Sentry Savings, Slaton; Interwest Savings Association, Fort Worth;
Metroplex Federal Savings Association, Hurst; North Park Savings
Association, Richardson; and Southern Federal Banc SLA, Lancaster.
   Other S&Ls involved are First Western Savings and Loan
Association, Colorado City; First Federal Savings and Loan
Association of Big Spring, Big Spring; Hi-Plains Savings and Loan
Association, Hereford; Reliance Savings Association, Houston; Vista
Savings Association, Odessa; Home Savings, Lufkin; and Lamesa
Federal Savings and Loan Association, Lamesa.
   The bank board's contribution in the latest group of mergers
brings to more than $24 billion the amount the agency has pledged to
resolve the cases of 175 failed S&Ls this year, up from 48 last year.
   Wall says he wants to do 200 by the end of the year. The board is
rushing to complete transactions because tax breaks for institutions
getting government assistance will be reduced after Jan. 1.
   More than 400 insolvent thrifts remain open and hundreds more are
close to insolvency. Estimates of the cost of cleaning up the
industry range from $50 billion, the bank board's figure, to $112
billion, the estimate of the General Accounting Office, the auditing
arm of Congress.
   The problem is getting worse by more than $1 billion a month.
Industry losses in the first nine months totaled $9.4 billion,
already surpassing the post-Depression record of $7.8 billion set in
1987.
   Private analysts, members of Congress and the GAO have criticized
the bank board for resolving most of the cases through assistance to
private merger partners. The rescues rely heavily on promissory
notes which pledge income the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance
Corp. expects to receive over the next decade.
   Critics say most of the deals fail to attract enough money from
institutions and investors taking over the failed thrifts. The GAO,
in a report earlier this month, said it may be cheaper in the long
run to give the FSLIC the money to close the institutions and pay
off depositors.
   Congress is planning to begin considering a taxpayer bailout of
FSLIC when it convenes in January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
