<2ND_LINE>BC-NL Industries,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NL Industries Shareholders Approve Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of NL Industries Inc. overwhelmingly
have approved a previously-announced restructuring that spins off
the company's petroleum services business into a new publicly-held
company, officials said Thursday.
   The restructuring, effective Thursday, leaves NL with only its
chemical operation.
   Under the plan, the company redeemed its Series C preferred stock
and declared a one-for-10 reverse split of its outstanding common
stock. Preferred shareholders could get either one share of
post-split stock or $15.66 cash for each of their Series C shares.
   The transactions leave preferred shareholders controlling 90
percent of the surviving company and former common shareholders
holding 10 percent.
   NL common stockholders also received on a pro-rata basis all of
the outstanding common stock of the newly spun-off petroleum
business, Baroid Corp.
   Valhi Corp., NL Industries' parent, will control about 52 percent
of Baroid's 61 million outstanding common shares. Valhi will control
about 66 percent of NL's 66 million outstanding common shares.
   Baroid Corp. common stock and post-split NL common stock were
expected to begin trading Friday on the New York and Pacific Stock
exchanges under the symbols ``BRC'' and ``NL'' respectively.
   Houston-based Baroid is a worldwide supplier of petroleum
services. NL, as restructured, will consist primarily of the
business of NL Chemicals Inc.
</TEXT>
