<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 2312EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Shipping     12-22 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Shipping,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Major Japanese Shipping Firms To Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major Japanese shipping firms announced Friday
that they will combine operations next year in what potentially will
be Japan's largest shipping company, in an apparent response to the
economic blow dealt by the strong yen.
   Details outlining the merger plan between Japan Line Ltd., one of
the world's leading tanker operators, and Yamashita-Shinnihon were
signed Friday, officials said.
   While the officials refused to reveal details, the merged
companies' combined current capital of about $579.8 million far
outstrips Nippon Yusen, currently Japan's biggest shipping company
with capital of about $467.7 million.
   ``The yen's rapid rise was particularly a severe blow for us,''
said an official of Yamashita-Shinnihon, one of Japan's six core
shipping companies.
   ``At the time when the entire industry is in a deep slump, we aim
to rationalize operations through the merger,'' the official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The export-heavy shipping industry has been particulary hit by
the strengthening of the yen against the U.S. dollar over the past
several years. A stronger yen makes Japanese products more expensive
overseas, and many firms have been forced to close down plants and
cut back on their work force because of slashed profits.
   Officials said Japan Line suffered a cumulative loss estimated at
$403.2 million while Yamashita-Shinnihon lost about $201.6 million.
   Transport Minister Shintaro Ishihara welcomed the merger, and
said, ``I hope such a move as this will revitalize the sluggish
industry.'' His comments were carried Japan Broadcasting Corp.
   The merger is the largest of its kind in the shipping industry
since 1964, when the ministry orchestrated a series of mergers
between dozens of small- and medium-sized firms into six major
companies.
</TEXT>
