<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-OilRoyalties     12-22 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Oil Royalties,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Texaco And Chevron To Pay $2.9 Million Oil Concession
Royalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered Texaco Inc., a Texaco
subsidiary and Chevron U.S.A. Inc. to pay $2.9 million in back
royalties for an oil concession in Ecuador to an Albany, Ga., oil
and mining company.
   The order filed by U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler last week
concludes a 12-year-old lawsuit filed by Norsul Oil & Mining Co.
Ltd. against Texaco Inc. and a Texaco subsidiary and against Gulf
Oil Corp., now Chevron U.S.A. Inc.
   The lawsuit claimed a contract between Norsul and the defendants
provided for the transfer of an oil concession in Ecuador from
Norsul in exchange for the payment of royalties to Norsul. The
royalties were to have been based on the production of oil within
the property in consideration.
   Norsul's attorneys have contended the defendants used an
unreliable and unapplicable survey to show improperly that an oil
well known as Shushufindi No. 1 in Ecuador, the greatest producer
within the area transferred, was exempt from royalty payments.
   Hoeveler ruled as valid Norsul's claims that the defendants were
guilty of breach of contract. He ordered the defendants to pay $2.93
million to Norsul in back royalties and that royalties continue to
be paid until termination of the contract.
   The rate of royalty payment amounts to about 1 percent of the
rate of production of Shushufindi No. 1, which in February was
measured at about 3,500 barrels per day. By early 1988, Shushufindi
No. 1 had produced an estimated 17 million barrels of oil since its
production began in 1972.
   Norsul Oil & Mining is a Canadian corporation with its principal
office in Albany, Ga.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881222-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0026EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Mexico-Debt     12-22 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Debt,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico's Treasury Secretary Goes To Washington For Debt Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Pedro Aspe flew to
Washington Wednesday night for talks on Mexico's $102 billion
foreign debt, the Treasury Department said.
   Aspe was to hold talks with U.S. Treasury Secretary-designate
Nicolas Brady and with Barber Conable, head of the World Bank, the
department said in a brief statement.
   Mexico's new president, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, wants debt
payments cut so the stagnant Mexican economy can begin growing again
and has has made renegotiating the debt, the second highest in the
developing world after Brazil's, a top priority.
   Aspe told congressmen last week that he hopes to persuade foreign
creditors to reduce debt payments from the current level of about 5
percent of the gross national product to about 3 percent.
   He said Salinas had sent a proposal to creditor banks in the
United States and Europe.
   Aspe did not disclose the details of the proposal. But the Mexico
City financial daily El Financiero said it would nearly halve the
amount Mexico expects to pay in 1989 and devote more of the payments
to principal, rather than interest.
   Debt payments amounted to about $14 billion in 1988 and are
expected to reach $16 billion in 1989.
   Salinas said in his first budget last week that Mexico's economy
will begin growing again toward the end of 1989 after debt payments
fall. He predicted 1.5 percent growth in the gross national product,
nearly four times that of 1988.
   Mexico, the world's sixth-largest oil producer, began
accumulating its huge debt in a borrowing spree during the oil boom
of the late 1970s. When the bottom fell out of the international oil
market in 1982, the Mexican economy nosedived into a crisis that
still grips the nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
